Dialogue: 0,0:02:26.32,0:02:28.19,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,-Get me a cab, will you?\N-Yes, sir.\N 请给我叫辆马车？―是,先生
Dialogue: 0,0:02:28.23,0:02:30.84,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,The most brilliantly written play I've seen in years.\N已经好几年没有看到这样好的戏剧了.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:30.88,0:02:32.15,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,The man's a born wit.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:32.19,0:02:33.84,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,The whole play was\Ntremendously exciting.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:33.89,0:02:35.50,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I hear he's writing a new one.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:35.54,0:02:37.41,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I can hardly wait to see it.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:37.46,0:02:39.33,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Cab!
Dialogue: 0,0:02:39.37,0:02:42.46,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Well, gentlemen, the English\Ntheater has just given birth\Nto a genius.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:42.51,0:02:44.86,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I feel sure\NWilde would be the first\Nto agree with you, Harry.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:44.90,0:02:47.55,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I wish I could approve of\Nthe playwright as much as\NI approve of his play.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:47.60,0:02:50.30,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Who cares about him as long\Nas he continues to give us\Nplays like this?
Dialogue: 0,0:03:22.94,0:03:25.07,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Well, Oscar, how does it feel\Nto be a success?
Dialogue: 0,0:03:25.11,0:03:26.85,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Did you have\Nany doubts, Robbie?
Dialogue: 0,0:03:33.12,0:03:35.95,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Congratulations, Oscar.\NBrilliant play! Brilliant!
Dialogue: 0,0:03:35.99,0:03:38.04,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Ah, there I'm bound\Nto agree with you,\NLord Sonning.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:39.69,0:03:42.78,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,My dear Mr. Wilde, I was\Nsimply delighted with\Nyour play.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:42.83,0:03:43.96,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I even enjoyed the interval.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:45.74,0:03:49.27,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Dear Lady Sonning,\Nshe has the remains\Nof a remarkable ugliness.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:49.31,0:03:52.10,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I've always been\Na great admirer of\Nyour work, Mr. Wilde.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:52.14,0:03:54.27,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,And I've always\Nbeen a great admirer\Nof my work, Mr. Shaw.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:55.49,0:03:56.84,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,-Frank!\N-Oscar!
Dialogue: 0,0:03:56.88,0:03:58.23,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,-Wonderful play.\N-Thank you.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:58.28,0:03:59.76,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,-My dear lady mother.\N-Oscar.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:59.80,0:04:03.28,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,My dear boy, a triumph.\NA magnificent triumph.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:03.33,0:04:06.68,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Ada, what are you going to say\Nabout my play in that woman's\Nmagazine you run?
Dialogue: 0,0:04:06.72,0:04:09.07,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I shall praise\Nit as highly as you\Nwould yourself, Oscar.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:09.11,0:04:10.55,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,You've always been\Nthe best critic\Nof my work.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:10.59,0:04:12.60,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,-But I never\Ncriticize your work.\N-Exactly.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:15.03,0:04:16.69,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I'm so proud, Oscar.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:16.73,0:04:18.21,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,And I'm so proud of you.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:18.91,0:04:20.08,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,You look wonderful.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:20.95,0:04:22.30,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Oscar, people are watching.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:22.34,0:04:23.91,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I hardly think Oscar\Nis the type of man
Dialogue: 0,0:04:23.95,0:04:25.74,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,to worry about his behavior\Nin public.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:25.78,0:04:27.52,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,And how did brother Willie\Nlike the play?
Dialogue: 0,0:04:27.57,0:04:28.79,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Or couldn't you\Nsee it from the bar?
Dialogue: 0,0:04:28.83,0:04:30.35,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Ooh, I'm perfectly sober,\Nthank you, Oscar.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:30.40,0:04:32.14,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I've ordered a table\Nat the Savoy.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:32.18,0:04:33.92,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,OSCAR: Get a cab, Robbie,\Nthere's a good chap.\NROBBIE: Of course.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:33.96,0:04:35.79,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Constance, you don't mind\Nnot coming.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:35.84,0:04:37.92,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,-But you know,\Nthese supper parties.\N-Very well, Oscar.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:37.97,0:04:40.06,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,-Mother will take you.\NNow, won't you, Mother?\N-Yes, of course.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:40.10,0:04:41.75,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,-Willie, get my wrap.\N-Goodbye, my dear.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:41.80,0:04:42.63,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Ada.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:43.28,0:04:44.24,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Come along, Bosie.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:45.28,0:04:46.98,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Good night, Mrs. Wilde.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:47.02,0:04:48.07,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Good night, Bosie.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:51.55,0:04:54.72,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,A green carnation.\NHow delightfully eccentric.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:54.77,0:04:56.29,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Damned ridiculous,\Nif you ask me.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:56.33,0:04:58.29,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,But who's the handsome\Nyoung boy with him?
Dialogue: 0,0:04:58.34,0:05:00.30,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Good heavens, Edith,\Nyou are out of touch.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:00.34,0:05:02.12,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Why, the whole of London\Nis talking about them.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:02.17,0:05:04.34,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,It's a damn disgrace\Nthe way the fellow\Nis carrying on.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:04.39,0:05:06.65,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,These artistic fellows\Nthink they can get away\Nwith anything.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:06.69,0:05:07.95,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,But who is he? Well, you...
Dialogue: 0,0:05:08.00,0:05:10.87,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,He's Lord Alfred Douglas.\NQueensberry's son.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:10.91,0:05:13.66,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,If I were Queensberry, I'd...
Dialogue: 0,0:05:13.70,0:05:16.22,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,You'd do what, sir?\NWhat would you do?
Dialogue: 0,0:05:18.97,0:05:19.79,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,What would you do?
Dialogue: 0,0:05:21.32,0:05:22.14,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Excuse me.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:23.45,0:05:26.45,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Lord Alfred, you remember\Nmy daughter?
Dialogue: 0,0:05:26.50,0:05:28.24,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,-Oh, Mrs. Somers.\NHow do you do?\N-Phyllis.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:28.28,0:05:29.72,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Poor Mrs. Somers.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:29.76,0:05:32.20,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Still trying to get\Nthat daughter off\Nher hands.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:32.24,0:05:34.07,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Well, she's wasting\Nher time with him.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:34.11,0:05:35.98,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Oh, my lord.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:36.03,0:05:37.33,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,You wicked man.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:44.34,0:05:45.17,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Bosie!
Dialogue: 0,0:05:46.91,0:05:48.87,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Don't you even\Nacknowledge me anymore?
Dialogue: 0,0:05:48.91,0:05:50.17,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,What do you want, Father?
Dialogue: 0,0:05:51.43,0:05:53.04,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Have you any idea\Nhow sick it makes me
Dialogue: 0,0:05:53.09,0:05:55.13,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,to watch you making\Na fool of yourself?
Dialogue: 0,0:05:55.18,0:05:57.83,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,A fine spectacle you are, sir,\Nfawning and crawling round\Nthis fellow, Wilde,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:57.87,0:05:59.48,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,like some damn little lapdog.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:59.53,0:06:01.14,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Are we going to\Nhave another one of\Nyour scenes, Father?
Dialogue: 0,0:06:01.18,0:06:03.40,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Scenes or no scenes, sir.\NI'll not tolerate\Nthis behavior.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:03.45,0:06:06.23,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Would you sooner I went\Naround with professional\Nboxers and sporting gentry?
Dialogue: 0,0:06:06.27,0:06:07.75,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,At least my friends\Nbehave like men.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:07.80,0:06:09.76,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,-Father, I'm over 21...\N-Only just.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:09.80,0:06:11.76,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I don't see that\NI have to answer to\Nyou for my behavior,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:11.80,0:06:13.85,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,nor seek your permission\Nfor the choice of my friends.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:13.89,0:06:15.76,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,You are a disgrace to\Nthe name of Queensberry!
Dialogue: 0,0:06:15.81,0:06:17.76,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I really don't have...\NBosie, is the cab ready yet?
Dialogue: 0,0:06:19.07,0:06:21.33,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Oscar, this unpleasant\Nlittle man is my father.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:21.38,0:06:22.46,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,-Lord Queensberry?\N-Yes.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:22.51,0:06:23.68,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Pleasure to meet you, sir.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:23.73,0:06:24.77,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,The pleasure is entirely yours,\NMr. Wilde.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:24.81,0:06:26.34,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,-Oscar, let's go.\N-Just a minute.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:26.38,0:06:27.86,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,-I have a few things\Nto say to this gentleman.\N-Father!
Dialogue: 0,0:06:27.90,0:06:29.56,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,-You listen to me, sir.\N-Oh, really, Lord Queensberry.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:29.60,0:06:31.30,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I think the public\Nhave had enough play\Nacting for one night.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:31.34,0:06:33.00,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I demand to be heard!
Dialogue: 0,0:06:33.04,0:06:34.26,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,You are being heard, sir,\Nby the entire theater.\NI should...
Dialogue: 0,0:06:34.30,0:06:35.96,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Well done, Wilde.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:36.00,0:06:38.96,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Most entertaining.\NWe both thought so,\Ndidn't we, my dear?
Dialogue: 0,0:06:39.00,0:06:40.61,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,You're very flattering,\NYour Royal Highness.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:40.66,0:06:42.57,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,And Mrs. Langtry,\Nyou're very beautiful.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:42.61,0:06:45.40,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I adore flattery almost\Nas much as you do, Oscar.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:45.44,0:06:47.53,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I didn't know\Nyou were a patron\Nof the arts, Queensberry.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:47.58,0:06:51.14,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I thought\Nfist fighting was\Nmore in your line.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:51.19,0:06:53.54,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Well, thank you for a most\Nenjoyable evening, Wilde.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:53.58,0:06:55.28,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,We shall look forward\Nto the next play.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:59.41,0:07:00.24,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Good night, sir.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:01.11,0:07:01.94,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,You coming, Bosie?
Dialogue: 0,0:07:04.03,0:07:07.03,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Let me just say this, Father.\NYou've been hounding me\Nlong enough.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:07.07,0:07:08.81,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,If you try and interfere\Nwith me again,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:08.86,0:07:10.69,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,or write anymore of\Nyour abusive letters,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:10.73,0:07:13.43,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I shall have no hesitation\Nin seeking the protection\Nof the law.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:13.47,0:07:16.30,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,You may have the law on your\Nhands much sooner than you\Nthink, my boy.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:49.12,0:07:50.42,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Good morning, Edward.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:50.47,0:07:52.73,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Good morning, Mr. Wilde, sir.\NLovely morning.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:52.77,0:07:54.99,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Yes, I think I'll\Nwalk a little. Follow.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:58.04,0:07:59.26,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Where to, sir?
Dialogue: 0,0:07:59.30,0:08:01.13,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,The Cafe Royal.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:01.17,0:08:03.22,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Cafe Royal? Very good, sir.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:11.62,0:08:13.92,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Mr. Wilde. Mr. Wilde, sir.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:13.97,0:08:16.14,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Mr. Wilde, one thing my\Nreaders are anxious to learn.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:16.19,0:08:18.14,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,-What paper do\Nyou write for, sir?\N-The Echo,sir.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:18.19,0:08:20.10,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Well, if your readers\Nwere anxious to learn\Nanything,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:20.15,0:08:21.10,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,they wouldn't take the Echo.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:22.93,0:08:25.54,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,May I ask you, sir,\Nwhy do you always wear\Na green carnation?
Dialogue: 0,0:08:25.59,0:08:27.11,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,REPORTER: Mr. Wilde,\Nyour book Dorian Gray...
Dialogue: 0,0:08:27.15,0:08:28.33,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Wait a minute.\NWhat did you say, sir?
Dialogue: 0,0:08:28.37,0:08:29.90,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Why do you always\Nwear a green carnation?
Dialogue: 0,0:08:29.94,0:08:31.68,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I consider nature\Nto be quite inadequate.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:31.72,0:08:33.81,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Why she never thought\Nof a green carnation,\NI can't imagine.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:33.86,0:08:35.90,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,REPORTER: Mr. Wilde.\NNo doubt she will\Nget around to it in time.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:37.86,0:08:40.04,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Mr. Wilde, your book\NDorian Grayhas been\Nseverely criticized.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:40.08,0:08:41.78,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Not by me.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:41.82,0:08:44.17,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Yes, but, many people\Ndo consider it immoral.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:44.21,0:08:48.22,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Ah, now, sir.\NWhat is immorality?\NI consider that to conform
Dialogue: 0,0:08:48.26,0:08:50.92,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,to the narrow\Nmoral standards of\Nthis Victorian age
Dialogue: 0,0:08:50.96,0:08:53.62,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,the grossest form\Nof immorality.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:53.66,0:08:55.23,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Yes, but, you know,\Nit is said, sir,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:55.27,0:08:57.84,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,that much of your writing\Nand indeed your basic\Nphilosophy
Dialogue: 0,0:08:57.88,0:08:59.93,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,is fundamentally immoral.\NWhat have you to say to that?
Dialogue: 0,0:08:59.97,0:09:01.49,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I may have offended\Nsome people,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:01.54,0:09:03.58,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,but I'm sure that in 50 years,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:03.63,0:09:05.50,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,the works of Oscar Wilde\Nwill be standard literature
Dialogue: 0,0:09:05.54,0:09:07.50,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,for every fifth form schoolboy.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:07.54,0:09:08.67,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Hear! Hear!
Dialogue: 0,0:09:08.72,0:09:10.55,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,My only regret is\Nthat I shan't be there
Dialogue: 0,0:09:10.59,0:09:12.85,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,-to collect the royalties.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:14.59,0:09:16.38,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I must say I hardly\Nthink a newspaperman
Dialogue: 0,0:09:16.42,0:09:18.34,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,is in a position to\Nspeak of immorality.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:18.38,0:09:20.29,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,-What?\N-Indeed, Lord Alfred.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:20.34,0:09:22.60,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Well, what could be more\Nimmoral than a newspaper?
Dialogue: 0,0:09:22.64,0:09:24.56,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,It condemns gambling\Non the front page
Dialogue: 0,0:09:24.60,0:09:26.78,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,and prints racing tips\Non the back.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:26.82,0:09:28.61,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Brilliant, Bosie.\NI wish I'd said that.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:28.65,0:09:30.65,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,You will, Oscar. You will.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:32.52,0:09:35.18,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,When you go back to Oxford,\Nyou can say you outwitted\NOscar Wilde.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:35.22,0:09:37.62,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,If I ever go back,\NI certainly will.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:37.66,0:09:38.57,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,What do you mean?
Dialogue: 0,0:09:40.66,0:09:42.53,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Well, didn't you know?\NI've been sent down.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:42.58,0:09:44.23,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Congratulations!
Dialogue: 0,0:09:44.27,0:09:46.32,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,All the best people\Nare being sent down\Nthese days.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:46.36,0:09:48.71,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,What did you do, Bosie?\NSet fire to the\Ndean's trousers?
Dialogue: 0,0:09:48.76,0:09:50.15,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Waiter! Waiter!\NMore champagne.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:50.19,0:09:52.98,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Frankly I believe too much\Neducation's a bad thing.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:53.02,0:09:54.15,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Don't you agree, Oscar?
Dialogue: 0,0:09:54.20,0:09:55.85,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I certainly do.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:55.89,0:09:58.07,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Ignorance is\Na delicate blossom.\NTouch it and it's gone.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:01.73,0:10:03.77,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,You didn't tell me\Nthat you'd been sent down.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:05.21,0:10:06.69,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,-Didn't I?\N-No.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:08.47,0:10:09.60,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,-Oh.\N-Why?
Dialogue: 0,0:10:10.74,0:10:12.08,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,It was all rather tedious.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:12.13,0:10:13.78,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Tedious or not,\NI'd like to hear about it.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:19.44,0:10:21.31,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Well, there was\Nsome scandal over\Na boy in the town.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:21.35,0:10:23.27,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,You know how\Nprovincial Oxford\Ncan be in some ways.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:25.40,0:10:26.75,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Frankly, I find\Nthe whole thing\Nrather amusing,
Dialogue: 0,0:10:26.80,0:10:30.32,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,but unfortunately\Nmy father didn't.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:30.36,0:10:33.72,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,He was so disgusted with\Nhis "so called son"\Nas he put it,
Dialogue: 0,0:10:33.76,0:10:36.02,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,that he's disowned\Nme completely.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:36.07,0:10:38.28,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,So now, I haven't\Na penny in the world.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:38.33,0:10:39.98,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,MAN: Frank, you're drunk.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:40.03,0:10:41.90,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,FRANK: Drunk? Who's drunk?
Dialogue: 0,0:10:41.94,0:10:45.03,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Oscar, have you\Never seen me when I had\Nmore than I could carry?
Dialogue: 0,0:10:45.07,0:10:47.86,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,No, but I've seen\Nyou when you should have\Ntaken more than one trip.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:50.51,0:10:53.08,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Why didn't you tell\Nme about this before?
Dialogue: 0,0:10:53.13,0:10:54.69,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Well, you were so busy,\Nwhat, with your play and...
Dialogue: 0,0:10:54.74,0:10:58.57,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,If you're in any trouble,\Nyou only have to come to me.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:58.61,0:11:00.66,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,And if it's\Nmoney you need,\Nyou needn't worry.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:03.14,0:11:05.31,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,You're very kind to me, Oscar.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:05.36,0:11:06.62,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I'm very fond of you.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:07.79,0:11:10.58,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Besides, what is\Nfriendship for?
Dialogue: 0,0:11:10.62,0:11:12.41,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Come on, Mr. Wilde,\Nwe're running out\Nof conversation.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:12.45,0:11:13.97,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,As long as we're not\Nrunning out of wine.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:15.76,0:11:17.41,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Waiter! Waiter!
Dialogue: 0,0:11:17.45,0:11:19.41,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,You know, gentlemen,\Nin the past few years,
Dialogue: 0,0:11:19.46,0:11:20.85,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I've made\Na remarkable discovery.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:20.89,0:11:22.11,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,What was that, Oscar?
Dialogue: 0,0:11:22.15,0:11:23.55,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Alcohol, if taken in\Nsufficient quantities,
Dialogue: 0,0:11:23.59,0:11:25.68,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,produces all the effects\Nof intoxication.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:27.29,0:11:28.81,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Gentlemen, I give you a toast.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:29.77,0:11:31.21,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,To youth.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:31.25,0:11:33.38,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,HARRIS: Oscar,\Nyou talk as if\Nyou're an old man.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:33.43,0:11:35.73,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I am. I'd do anything\Nto regain my lost youth
Dialogue: 0,0:11:35.78,0:11:38.65,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,except take up exercise or\Nget up early in the morning.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:40.00,0:11:41.87,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Waiter! Waiter,\Nwhere's that champagne?
Dialogue: 0,0:11:41.91,0:11:43.35,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,MAN: Ah, thank you.\NHere we are.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:05.81,0:12:07.63,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,-Good evening, sir.\N-Hello, Arthur.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:07.68,0:12:10.46,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Oscar! You said\Nyou'd be in for lunch.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:11.60,0:12:13.77,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Yes, I had a meeting\Nwith my publisher.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:13.82,0:12:15.29,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,The children have\Nbeen asking for you.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:15.34,0:12:16.91,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,OSCAR: Oh.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:16.95,0:12:19.52,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,They refuse\Nto go to sleep until\Nyou tell them a story.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:20.26,0:12:21.52,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Oh, very well.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:24.56,0:12:26.13,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,BOYS: Daddy! Daddy!
Dialogue: 0,0:12:26.18,0:12:28.83,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Now, what's all\Nthis about your not sleeping?
Dialogue: 0,0:12:28.87,0:12:30.88,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,We want you to tell us a story.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:31.22,0:12:32.88,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I see.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:32.92,0:12:34.57,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Well, now,\Nwhat shall I tell\Nyou tonight about?
Dialogue: 0,0:12:34.62,0:12:35.75,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Not too long, Oscar.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:35.79,0:12:38.14,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Giants or dragons?
Dialogue: 0,0:12:38.19,0:12:41.71,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,You told us the story\Nabout giants last night.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:41.76,0:12:45.19,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Well, have I told you\Nthe story about\Nthe Happy Prince?
Dialogue: 0,0:12:45.24,0:12:46.06,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,No.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:47.46,0:12:50.24,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,High above the city\Non a tall column
Dialogue: 0,0:12:50.29,0:12:53.64,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,stood the statue\Nof the Happy Prince.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:53.68,0:12:57.73,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,He was gilded all over\Nwith thin leaves\Nof fine gold.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:58.95,0:13:02.21,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,For eyes he had\Ntwo bright sapphires
Dialogue: 0,0:13:02.25,0:13:05.26,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,and a large red ruby\Nglowed on his sword hilt.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:06.61,0:13:09.52,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,He was as beautiful\Nas a weather cock.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:17.84,0:13:18.84,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Yes, sir?
Dialogue: 0,0:13:18.88,0:13:20.62,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Mr. Oscar Wilde?
Dialogue: 0,0:13:20.66,0:13:22.75,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I don't know that\Nhe's at home, sir.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:22.80,0:13:24.41,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Ah. My name is Wood.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:24.45,0:13:25.97,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,-Wood, sir?\N-Yes.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:26.02,0:13:27.85,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I'm a friend of\NLord Alfred Douglas.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:27.89,0:13:30.98,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Oh, I see, sir.\NWould you step\Ninside, sir?
Dialogue: 0,0:13:31.02,0:13:34.11,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I'll enquire if Mr. Wilde\Nwill see you, sir.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:34.16,0:13:36.72,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,"Dear little swallow,"\Nsaid the prince.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:38.60,0:13:40.51,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,"You tell me marvelous things,
Dialogue: 0,0:13:42.43,0:13:44.78,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,"but more marvelous\Nthan anything
Dialogue: 0,0:13:44.82,0:13:47.73,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,"is the suffering\Nof men and women."
Dialogue: 0,0:13:51.61,0:13:55.61,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Excuse me, sir.\NThere's a person\Nto see you, sir.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:55.66,0:13:56.74,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Very well.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:06.36,0:14:08.93,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,-He gave his name as Wood, sir.\N-Wood?
Dialogue: 0,0:14:08.97,0:14:10.93,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Said he was a friend\Nof Lord Alfred's, sir.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:10.98,0:14:11.98,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Oh, I see.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:12.02,0:14:13.15,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,He's in the front room, sir.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:13.20,0:14:14.54,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Thank you, Arthur.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:17.59,0:14:18.42,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Mr. Wood?
Dialogue: 0,0:14:20.38,0:14:22.38,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,That's right, sir.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:22.42,0:14:26.60,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Oh. Very delicate.\NVery delicate indeed.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:26.64,0:14:28.91,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I understand you are\Na friend of Lord Alfred's.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:28.95,0:14:32.00,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Uh, well, I suppose\Nyou might say that,\Nsir, yes.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:32.04,0:14:34.65,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,A very friendly gentleman,\NHis Lordship, sir,\Nvery friendly.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:34.69,0:14:36.74,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Well, he didn't mention you,\NMr. Wood, but...
Dialogue: 0,0:14:36.78,0:14:38.92,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Uh, Alfred Wood, sir.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:38.96,0:14:41.09,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Same name as His Lordship, sir.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:41.14,0:14:42.79,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I'm no lord, of course, sir,
Dialogue: 0,0:14:42.83,0:14:45.75,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,but as a poet like\Nyourself might say,\N"What's in a name?"
Dialogue: 0,0:14:46.92,0:14:48.19,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Cognac, Mr. Wood?
Dialogue: 0,0:14:48.23,0:14:49.06,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Thank you, sir.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:50.06,0:14:51.84,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,You knew Lord Alfred at Oxford?
Dialogue: 0,0:14:51.89,0:14:54.67,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Well, not\Nexactly at Oxford, sir.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:54.71,0:14:56.67,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,No, sir,\Nnot in the way\Nthat you might mean.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:56.72,0:14:59.63,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I used\Nto do odd jobs\Nfor His Lordship.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:59.68,0:15:01.77,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Oh, very kind he\Nwas to me, sir. Yes.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:01.81,0:15:04.07,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,A gentleman\Nlike yourself, sir,\Nin every particular.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:04.12,0:15:07.03,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Thank you, sir.\NWell, I'm very glad to\Nmeet any friend of Bosie's.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:07.08,0:15:08.16,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Bosie?
Dialogue: 0,0:15:08.21,0:15:09.64,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Oh.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:10.38,0:15:11.34,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Yes, of course, sir.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:18.83,0:15:19.65,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Your health, sir.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:27.70,0:15:31.06,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Very fine brandy this, sir.\NDrives the cold from\Nthe bones.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:35.63,0:15:37.98,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Well, I, uh...
Dialogue: 0,0:15:38.02,0:15:40.20,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I won't beat about\Nthe bush, sir,\Nas the saying goes.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:47.38,0:15:50.34,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Quite by accident, sir,\NI assure you, I a...
Dialogue: 0,0:15:50.38,0:15:54.99,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I came across\Nthat letter from you\Nto Lord Alfred Douglas.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:55.04,0:15:58.13,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Very beautiful letter,\Nif I might say so, sir.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:59.39,0:16:01.26,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Only I think that perhaps
Dialogue: 0,0:16:01.30,0:16:05.13,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,there are parts that\Ncould be "misconstrued,"\NI think is the word, sir.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:06.35,0:16:07.53,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,How did you come by this?
Dialogue: 0,0:16:07.57,0:16:09.14,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Ah, yes, well, I used to...
Dialogue: 0,0:16:09.18,0:16:11.18,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Used to press\NLord Alfred's clothes.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:11.23,0:16:13.66,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Very particular\Nabout his clothes, sir.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:13.71,0:16:14.53,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,As well you may know.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:15.71,0:16:18.02,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I, uh, found it\Nin one of his pockets.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:18.06,0:16:21.37,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Are you asking me to\Npurchase my own work,\NMr. Wood?
Dialogue: 0,0:16:21.41,0:16:24.63,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Well, sir, I...\NCome, sir, that's not\Nvery sound economics.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:24.67,0:16:28.33,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Well, I've already\Nbeen offered 拢60\Nfor it, sir.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:28.37,0:16:31.42,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Then I suggest that\Nyou sell it at once.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:31.46,0:16:34.12,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I myself have seldom\Nbeen offered so much
Dialogue: 0,0:16:34.16,0:16:36.34,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,for a prose work\Nof that length.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:38.08,0:16:39.82,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,You take the letter, sir.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:39.86,0:16:42.04,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,It was stupid of me\Nto try and rent you.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:42.08,0:16:44.91,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,The thing is, sir,\Nthat I'm desperate\Nfor money and...
Dialogue: 0,0:16:44.96,0:16:47.22,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,A hungry man gets\Ndriven to do stupid things.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:47.26,0:16:49.05,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Oh, would you like\Na ham sandwich?
Dialogue: 0,0:16:49.09,0:16:50.40,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Now you're making\Nfun of me, sir.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:50.44,0:16:52.05,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,On the\Ncontrary, Mr. Wood.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:52.09,0:16:54.44,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,You're doing\Nremarkably well yourself.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:54.49,0:16:55.97,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Well, I think I'll\Nbe going now, sir.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:56.01,0:16:58.80,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,No, no, no, no.\NPlease stay and\Nfinish your drink.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:58.84,0:16:59.84,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,That's very kind of you.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:03.06,0:17:07.15,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,You're a very poor criminal,\NMr. Wood, if I may say so.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:07.20,0:17:12.20,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,The fact is\NI came to London\Nto look for some work.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:12.24,0:17:15.77,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Ah, work, Mr. Wood, is the\Ncurse of the drinking classes.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:19.16,0:17:21.08,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,The secret of maintaining youth
Dialogue: 0,0:17:23.73,0:17:27.61,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,is an inordinate\Npassion for pleasure.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:34.70,0:17:36.49,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,拢40, sir?
Dialogue: 0,0:17:36.53,0:17:39.58,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I'm going\Nout to dine in a moment.\NPerhaps you'd care to join me.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:39.62,0:17:41.88,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Well, that's very kind\Nof you, sir.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:41.93,0:17:43.41,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,There's a fascinating charm
Dialogue: 0,0:17:43.45,0:17:47.28,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,about your halfhearted\Ncriminal tendencies,\NMr. Wood.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:47.32,0:17:51.37,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I suspect that you lead\Na wonderfully wicked life.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:51.41,0:17:53.68,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Ah, well,\Nthere's good and\Nbad in all of us, sir.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:53.72,0:17:55.42,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Mr. Wood, you're\Na born philosopher.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:55.46,0:17:57.20,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I'm sure we shall\Nget along extremely well.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:57.25,0:17:58.07,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Your health, sir.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:15.09,0:18:16.70,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Shall I serve dinner, madam?
Dialogue: 0,0:18:18.18,0:18:20.22,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I can't understand it.\NI'm sure Mr. Wilde said
Dialogue: 0,0:18:20.27,0:18:22.01,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,he would be in for dinner.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:22.05,0:18:24.97,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Well, perhaps\Nhe's been detained\Non business, madam.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:25.01,0:18:26.23,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Yes.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:26.27,0:18:27.10,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Shall we wait?
Dialogue: 0,0:18:29.19,0:18:30.71,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,No, Arthur, I'll dine alone.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:30.76,0:18:31.58,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Very well, madam.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:58.22,0:19:00.00,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Bosie, you're\Nnearly an hour late.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:00.05,0:19:00.87,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Yes, I know.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:02.14,0:19:03.70,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Oh, I know what\Nthat face means.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:03.75,0:19:06.27,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,It usually heralds\Nan unpleasant scene.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:06.31,0:19:08.14,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,It would be nice\Nif it could be avoided.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:08.19,0:19:10.01,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I'm in a singularly good mood.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:10.06,0:19:12.28,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,-Are you?\N-I was.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:12.32,0:19:15.06,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,No doubt, having\Nentertained your friend\Nat the Savoy last night.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:15.85,0:19:17.76,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,You mean Mr. Wood?
Dialogue: 0,0:19:17.80,0:19:20.20,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Really, Oscar, have\Nyou no sense of propriety?
Dialogue: 0,0:19:20.24,0:19:21.42,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,The man is a valet.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:21.46,0:19:23.68,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,A very amusing valet.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:23.72,0:19:27.73,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Thank heavens, Bosie,\NI am not inhibited\Nby your sense of class.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:27.77,0:19:29.47,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,So it seems.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:29.51,0:19:30.95,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Anyway, he was your friend.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:31.77,0:19:33.69,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I hardly knew the man.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:33.73,0:19:35.60,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,That's not the impression\Nthat he gave to me.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:35.65,0:19:37.13,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,WAITER: Good morning, My Lord.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:37.17,0:19:38.82,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,What did he want anyway?
Dialogue: 0,0:19:38.87,0:19:40.83,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Money. What do\Nthe poor usually want?
Dialogue: 0,0:19:40.87,0:19:42.35,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Would you like to\Norder now, My Lord?
Dialogue: 0,0:19:42.39,0:19:43.53,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,And you gave it to him?
Dialogue: 0,0:19:44.57,0:19:47.36,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,For a valuable\Npiece of property.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:47.40,0:19:49.75,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,A letter I wrote you at Oxford.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:49.79,0:19:51.45,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,WAITER: May I recommend\Nthe lobster, My Lord?
Dialogue: 0,0:19:52.80,0:19:55.01,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,-I'll have the sole meuniere.\N-Very good.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:55.06,0:19:58.63,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Do you mean he blackmailed you?
Dialogue: 0,0:19:58.67,0:20:02.72,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Leaving that letter\Naround for anyone to find\Nwas not only careless of you,
Dialogue: 0,0:20:02.76,0:20:04.81,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,but singularly\Nlacking in respect
Dialogue: 0,0:20:04.85,0:20:08.07,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,for something\Nthat I'd hoped was\Nprivate and personal.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:10.25,0:20:11.51,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Waiter, bring some\Nchampagne right away.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:11.55,0:20:12.38,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Very good, My Lord.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:15.56,0:20:17.99,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,It'd seem, Bosie,\Nthat I am forever paying
Dialogue: 0,0:20:18.04,0:20:20.52,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,for your indiscretions\Nand your extravagances.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:20.56,0:20:22.22,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Money, is that all\Nyou ever think of?
Dialogue: 0,0:20:22.26,0:20:24.91,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Ah, when I was young\NI thought money was\Neverything.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:24.96,0:20:26.66,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Now that I'm older\NI know that it is.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:26.70,0:20:28.79,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,My God, Oscar,\Nyou're never satisfied.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:28.83,0:20:29.92,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,You have a successful book out,
Dialogue: 0,0:20:29.96,0:20:31.14,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,a play running\Nin the West End...
Dialogue: 0,0:20:31.18,0:20:33.44,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Playing to packed\Nhouses of creditors.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:33.49,0:20:36.32,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Have you any idea\Nhow much money I've spent\Nsince we've been together?
Dialogue: 0,0:20:36.36,0:20:39.28,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I'm sure you've\Nkept an account.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:39.32,0:20:43.59,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Luncheon every day here,\Ndinner at the Savoy,\Nsupper at...
Dialogue: 0,0:20:43.63,0:20:45.28,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,-Oh, look what you've done.\N-I'm sorry, sir.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:45.33,0:20:46.85,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,-Please.\N-Oh, go away, stop fussing.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:48.89,0:20:50.29,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,And always the best champagne
Dialogue: 0,0:20:50.33,0:20:52.51,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,because you have\Na very delicate palate.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:52.55,0:20:55.86,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Bosie, you seem to think\Nthat you have a right to\Nlive at my expense
Dialogue: 0,0:20:55.90,0:20:59.82,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,in a profuse luxury to\Nwhich you have never\Nbeen accustomed.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:59.86,0:21:03.30,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I pay\Nyour hotel bills,\Nyour tailor's bill,
Dialogue: 0,0:21:03.34,0:21:04.69,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,your gambling debts.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:06.48,0:21:09.70,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,You demand\Nwithout grace and you\Nreceive without thanks.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:11.40,0:21:12.35,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Have you finished?
Dialogue: 0,0:21:15.23,0:21:18.14,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Now tell\Nme honestly, Oscar.\NWhat did you expect, hmm?
Dialogue: 0,0:21:18.18,0:21:20.58,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Did you think I was\Nsome common street Arab
Dialogue: 0,0:21:20.62,0:21:22.23,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,to be bought\Nwith cheap trinkets
Dialogue: 0,0:21:22.28,0:21:25.50,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,and an occasional supper\Nin some Soho restaurant?
Dialogue: 0,0:21:25.54,0:21:27.85,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I've given\Nyou my friendship\Nfor two years, Oscar.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:27.89,0:21:31.33,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I've admired your genius,\Nlaughed at your jokes,\Nflattered your vanity.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:31.37,0:21:34.77,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,And now you question the\Nprice of such a friendship.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:34.81,0:21:36.55,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,It isn't worthy of you, Oscar.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:19.90,0:22:21.73,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,-Good evening, Mr. Wilde.\N-Evening, William.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:22.29,0:22:23.12,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Sydney.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:24.12,0:22:25.38,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Thank you, sir.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:25.43,0:22:27.47,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,-Good evening, Mr. Wilde.\N-Good evening.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:27.52,0:22:31.00,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I want you to take\Nthis to this address.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:32.43,0:22:33.70,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,It's just around the corner.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:36.13,0:22:37.74,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,-Straight away, hmm?\N-Right away, sir.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:41.62,0:22:42.44,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Hello, Robbie.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:43.18,0:22:44.01,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Hello, Oscar.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:44.97,0:22:46.14,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,What will you have?
Dialogue: 0,0:22:46.19,0:22:48.67,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Brandy, and a large one.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:48.71,0:22:50.45,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,John. A large brandy.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:52.15,0:22:53.45,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Give me a cigarette,\Nthere's a dear fellow.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:53.50,0:22:54.50,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I seem to have\Nleft mine at home.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:55.28,0:22:56.81,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,-What?\N-A cigarette.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:56.85,0:22:57.94,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Oh, yes, of course.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:59.42,0:23:00.24,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Thank you.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:08.90,0:23:11.60,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,What is it, Oscar?\NAre you not well?
Dialogue: 0,0:23:11.65,0:23:13.47,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,No, just very tired,\Nthat's all.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:14.48,0:23:15.39,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Your brandy, sir.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:17.48,0:23:18.30,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Thank you.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:22.48,0:23:25.70,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Oscar, did you know that\Nsome of the club members
Dialogue: 0,0:23:25.75,0:23:27.88,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,have approached\Nthe Committee\Nto get you to resign?
Dialogue: 0,0:23:27.92,0:23:29.66,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Well, I hope not. I shall\Nhave to find somewhere else
Dialogue: 0,0:23:29.71,0:23:31.41,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,to sleep in the afternoons.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:31.45,0:23:33.41,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Have you any idea how much\Npeople are talking about you
Dialogue: 0,0:23:33.45,0:23:34.54,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,or what they are saying?
Dialogue: 0,0:23:34.58,0:23:36.85,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I adore scandal\Nabout other people,
Dialogue: 0,0:23:36.89,0:23:39.50,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,but about myself\NI find it extremely dull.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:39.54,0:23:41.50,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,It hasn't the charm of novelty.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:41.55,0:23:44.90,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I don't think you'll\Nfind this gossip dull.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:44.94,0:23:47.68,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Robbie, are you being\Nsolicitous about my welfare?
Dialogue: 0,0:23:47.73,0:23:49.47,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,That is very\Nimpertinent of you.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:49.51,0:23:50.99,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I don't mean to be.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:51.03,0:23:53.99,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Oscar, I realize\Nthat much of your\Nextravagant behavior
Dialogue: 0,0:23:54.04,0:23:56.26,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,is done purely for effect.\NYou're an artist.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:56.30,0:23:58.34,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,The public expects\Nyou to be different.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:58.39,0:24:01.39,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,But you're no longer\Nan ascetic young poet\Njust down from Oxford.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:01.44,0:24:03.65,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,-Relax.\N-You're a highly\Nsuccessful playwrighter
Dialogue: 0,0:24:03.70,0:24:05.40,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,at the peak of your career.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:05.44,0:24:08.79,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,You dine with royalty.\NYou mix in the highest\Nsocial circles.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:08.83,0:24:10.57,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Ah.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:10.62,0:24:12.10,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,You're walking along\Na precipice, Oscar.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:12.14,0:24:14.71,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Just as long\Nas you continue\Nto play court jester,
Dialogue: 0,0:24:14.75,0:24:16.06,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,society will accept you.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:16.10,0:24:18.67,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,But tax their tolerance too far
Dialogue: 0,0:24:18.71,0:24:20.63,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,and they'll send you\Ncrashing from the heights
Dialogue: 0,0:24:20.67,0:24:22.67,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,-to the depths of obscurity.\N-Oh, really.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:22.72,0:24:25.50,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,A halo doesn't have to fall\Nvery far, Oscar, to become\Na noose.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:25.55,0:24:27.37,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Really, Robbie,\Nthis all very tedious.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:28.33,0:24:29.51,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Just tell me one thing.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:30.46,0:24:32.73,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,These stories I hear about you.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:32.77,0:24:34.51,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,There isn't any truth\Nin them, is there?
Dialogue: 0,0:24:34.56,0:24:35.90,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,As I don't know\Nwhat the stories are,
Dialogue: 0,0:24:35.95,0:24:37.25,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I'm hardly in a position\Nto answer you.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:37.30,0:24:39.08,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,They say that you...
Dialogue: 0,0:24:39.12,0:24:43.39,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,You're being\Nblackmailed because of\Nyour association with Bosie.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:43.43,0:24:48.53,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,That you consort with\Ncriminals, stable boys.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:51.96,0:24:54.23,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,This sounds all very\Nexciting and intriguing.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:54.27,0:24:55.66,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Do go on.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:55.71,0:24:57.49,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I just want to hear\Nyou tell me it isn't true.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:00.10,0:25:02.19,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Robbie,
Dialogue: 0,0:25:02.23,0:25:06.02,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I'm deeply hurt\Nthat you use our friendship\Nto pry into my private life.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:07.68,0:25:12.20,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I thought\Nyou were a gentleman.\NI now see that you are not.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:12.24,0:25:13.99,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I just want to\Nhear you deny it, Oscar.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:14.03,0:25:16.03,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,You must think\Nwhat you will, Robbie.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:17.64,0:25:18.82,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Mr. Wood to see you, sir.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:18.86,0:25:19.69,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Thank you.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:27.30,0:25:30.74,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Robbie, because\NI'm very fond of you
Dialogue: 0,0:25:30.79,0:25:32.44,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I shall forget everything\Nyou've said tonight.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:33.61,0:25:34.48,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Good night.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:35.35,0:25:36.18,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Good night.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:40.06,0:25:41.67,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Hello, Oscar.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:45.80,0:25:47.58,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Lovely club you've got here.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:47.63,0:25:50.11,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,-I like that.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:50.15,0:25:51.72,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I'd like some\Nchampagne tonight.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:10.39,0:26:11.61,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Oh, you shouldn't\Nhave bothered.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:12.70,0:26:14.05,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,You must eat something.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:19.01,0:26:20.75,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,All right?
Dialogue: 0,0:26:20.79,0:26:22.36,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,You know, I've eaten in all\Nof the best restaurants\Nin Europe
Dialogue: 0,0:26:22.40,0:26:24.58,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,but I've never tasted\Nanything like your\Nsweetbreads.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:25.49,0:26:26.36,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Where's the wine?
Dialogue: 0,0:26:27.58,0:26:28.97,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,They didn't deliver\Nany this week.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:29.02,0:26:31.59,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,For heaven's sake, why not?
Dialogue: 0,0:26:31.63,0:26:34.59,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Perhaps the fact that we\Nowe the wine merchant 拢85
Dialogue: 0,0:26:34.63,0:26:36.85,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,might have something\Nto do with it.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:36.89,0:26:39.64,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,We're living on credit,\NOscar, and that can't\Ngo on much longer.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:39.68,0:26:43.25,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Well, if I can\Nfinish this play,\Neverything will be all right.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:45.42,0:26:47.34,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,If that's Bosie,\Ntell him I'm not at home.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:51.91,0:26:53.52,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,QUEENSBERRY: I wish\Nto see Mr. Oscar Wilde.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:53.56,0:26:55.57,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,ARTHUR: I'm sorry, sir,\Nbut Mr. Wilde is not at home.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:55.61,0:26:56.83,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Well, I'm sorry,\Nbut I demand to\Nsee him.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:56.87,0:26:57.79,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,You can't go in there, sir.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:57.83,0:26:59.18,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,If you please, sir.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:59.22,0:27:00.70,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Wilde, I want to have\Na word with you. Sit down.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:02.79,0:27:05.31,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Well, Lord Queensberry.\NIt's all right, Arthur,\Nyou can go.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:05.36,0:27:08.36,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,It seems\Nthe peerage don't have\Na monopoly of good manners.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:08.40,0:27:10.23,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,To hell with good manners, sir.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:10.28,0:27:12.93,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,What I have to say\Nto you has very little\Nto do with good manners.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:12.97,0:27:15.28,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Indeed?\NAnd I presume you've\Nbrought your ugly friend
Dialogue: 0,0:27:15.32,0:27:16.98,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,to lend you moral support.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:17.02,0:27:19.20,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,When it comes\Nto morals, I have\Nall the support I need,
Dialogue: 0,0:27:19.24,0:27:21.16,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,thank you very much.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:21.20,0:27:23.46,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I've seldom\Ncome across anybody in whom\Nthe moral sense was dominant
Dialogue: 0,0:27:23.51,0:27:27.34,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,who was not heartless,\Ncruel, vindictive\Nand completely lacking
Dialogue: 0,0:27:27.38,0:27:29.43,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,in the smallest\Nsense of humanity,\NLord Queensberry.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:29.47,0:27:32.73,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Personally,\NI'd sooner have\N50 unnatural vices
Dialogue: 0,0:27:32.78,0:27:34.43,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,than one unnatural virtue.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:34.47,0:27:37.61,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Yes, I can\Nwell believe that.\NNow, you listen to me, sir.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:37.65,0:27:39.26,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I presume you have\Ncome to make a speech.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:39.30,0:27:41.92,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,If so,\NI hope it's a short one\Nbecause I have work to do.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:45.83,0:27:46.66,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Wilde.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:48.97,0:27:49.79,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Wilde.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:53.06,0:27:54.93,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I've come here today\Nto protest against
Dialogue: 0,0:27:54.97,0:27:57.67,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,your disgusting\Nrelationship with my son.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:03.76,0:28:06.72,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,That is a revolting\Nand slanderous statement,
Dialogue: 0,0:28:06.77,0:28:08.55,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,and I demand an apology.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:08.59,0:28:10.29,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I refuse to apologize.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:12.08,0:28:15.25,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I refuse to apologize for\Nsaying something which is\Ncommon knowledge
Dialogue: 0,0:28:15.30,0:28:17.73,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,to every cab driver\Nand messenger boy\Nin London.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:17.78,0:28:19.61,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Lord Queensberry,\Nare you seriously\Nsuggesting that
Dialogue: 0,0:28:19.65,0:28:21.83,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,there is improper conduct\Nbetween your son and myself?
Dialogue: 0,0:28:22.78,0:28:25.26,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I do not say that you are.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:25.31,0:28:28.27,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I say\Nthat you look it,\Nwhich is just as bad.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:28.31,0:28:29.49,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,But I'll tell you this.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:30.70,0:28:33.18,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,If I catch you\Ntwo again together,
Dialogue: 0,0:28:33.23,0:28:37.80,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I shall take a whip to you,\Nsir, and I shall thrash\Nyou to the ground.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:42.19,0:28:44.46,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I see that when\Nit comes to fighting,
Dialogue: 0,0:28:44.50,0:28:47.50,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,you choose to ignore\Nthe Queensberry rules.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:47.55,0:28:49.64,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,-Yes, well,\NI give you fair warning.\N-And I give you fair warning.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:49.68,0:28:51.73,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,If you're not out of\Nmy house in two minutes,\NI shall throw you out.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:51.77,0:28:53.25,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I refuse to leave\Nuntil I've had my say.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:53.29,0:28:55.25,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,On the contrary, sir,\Nyou are leaving now.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:55.29,0:28:57.73,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Hit him! Hit him!
Dialogue: 0,0:29:00.95,0:29:04.30,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Arthur, open the door!\NThis gentleman is leaving.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:04.35,0:29:05.26,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Gladly, sir.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:07.74,0:29:09.92,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,This, Arthur,\Nis the Marquis\Nof Queensberry.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:09.96,0:29:12.70,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,The most infamous brute in\NLondon and you're never to\Nlet him in my house again.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:12.75,0:29:14.01,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,-Is that clear?\N-Perfectly, sir.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:14.84,0:29:16.31,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Now get out.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:16.36,0:29:17.79,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Very well.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:17.84,0:29:19.88,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,But you'll regret this,\NI promise you.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:19.93,0:29:21.02,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I promise you.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:24.80,0:29:26.32,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Go back to your room\Nthis instant.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:27.67,0:29:29.37,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Will that be all, sir?
Dialogue: 0,0:29:29.41,0:29:30.59,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I hope so, Arthur.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:44.21,0:29:45.21,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Now, this has got to stop.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:47.61,0:29:49.43,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,You are the only one\Nwho can stop it, Oscar.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:49.48,0:29:51.96,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,My God, am I\Nnot allowed to get on\Nwith my work in peace?
Dialogue: 0,0:29:52.00,0:29:53.61,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,What with creditors\Nknocking at the door
Dialogue: 0,0:29:53.66,0:29:55.53,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,and Bosie dropping in\Nas if this was some\Nsort of club.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:55.57,0:29:58.57,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,And now this coarse brute\Nwith his hired pugilists.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:58.62,0:30:01.66,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I can stand brute force,\Nbut brute reason is\Nquite intolerable.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:01.71,0:30:02.80,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,It's like hitting\Nbelow the intellect.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:06.89,0:30:10.41,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Oscar, I beg of you\Nto give up this friendship\Nwith Bosie.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:12.02,0:30:14.16,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Not for me,\Nbut for your own sake.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:14.20,0:30:16.20,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,He takes up\Ntoo much of your time,
Dialogue: 0,0:30:16.24,0:30:18.20,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,demands too much\Nof your emotions.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:19.33,0:30:20.25,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I know.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:21.77,0:30:25.17,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,The truth is the boy has\Na strange fascination\Nfor me
Dialogue: 0,0:30:25.21,0:30:28.17,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,that I can't get free of.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:31.39,0:30:34.57,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,He needs you more\Nthan you need him.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:34.61,0:30:37.57,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,He needs you\Nbecause he is\Nweak and conceited.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:37.61,0:30:40.14,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,And you give him\Na stature he could\Nnever acquire alone.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:40.18,0:30:42.88,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,And he will\Ngo on taking and taking\Nuntil there's nothing left.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:42.92,0:30:44.53,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,He'll destroy you, Oscar.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:46.36,0:30:48.28,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,When I married you,
Dialogue: 0,0:30:48.32,0:30:51.67,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I didn't believe\Nit was possible to love\Nanybody more than I loved you.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:55.28,0:30:57.89,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I still love you, darling.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:57.94,0:31:01.68,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,To me you are higher and\Ngreater than any man in\Nthe world.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:01.72,0:31:02.90,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Help me, Constance.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:03.60,0:31:04.42,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Help me.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:08.73,0:31:10.65,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Why not go away\Nfor a little while?
Dialogue: 0,0:31:10.69,0:31:13.43,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,At least until you\Nhave finished your play.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:13.48,0:31:15.83,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Maybe it will\Ngive you a chance\Nto think more clearly.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:16.91,0:31:17.74,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Yes, I may.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:19.18,0:31:22.44,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,You always liked the sea.\NWhy not go down to Brighton?
Dialogue: 0,0:31:22.48,0:31:24.18,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,It should be very quiet\Nat this time of year.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:25.97,0:31:28.01,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,It's a wonderful idea,\NConstance,
Dialogue: 0,0:31:28.06,0:31:32.19,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,but we've hardly enough money\Nto pay the tradesmen,\Nlet alone hotel bills.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:32.23,0:31:35.19,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I haven't\Ntouched my father's\Nallowance for some months.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:35.24,0:31:36.85,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,-It isn't very much,\NI'm afraid.\N-No, no, Constance.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:36.89,0:31:38.20,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Please. Please.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:45.33,0:31:46.42,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I love you.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:47.68,0:31:48.60,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I love you.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:52.18,0:32:55.19,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Goodness Lordy, Mr. Wilde,\Nwherever have you been?
Dialogue: 0,0:32:55.23,0:32:57.49,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I've been conversing\Nwith the elements,\NMrs. Burgess.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:57.54,0:32:59.32,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Oh, goodness me,\Nyou're soaked\Nto the skin.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:59.36,0:33:01.93,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Listening to the wisdom\Nof the sea, Mrs. B.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:01.98,0:33:03.76,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Out all night\Nin weather like this.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:03.80,0:33:06.24,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Now, you come upstairs\Nand we'll get those\Nwet clothes off
Dialogue: 0,0:33:06.28,0:33:07.68,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,-before you catch your death.\N-It's all here.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:07.72,0:33:09.42,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Every word and every epigram,\NMrs. Burgess.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:09.46,0:33:11.11,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Oh, I'm very glad, Mr. Wilde,\Nbut do come on.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:11.16,0:33:12.81,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Every move and every curtain.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:12.86,0:33:14.16,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,It's all here.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:14.20,0:33:16.16,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,And the\Nimportant thing\Nis who is Ernest.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:16.21,0:33:17.29,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Oh, yes, that will be nice.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:17.34,0:33:18.86,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Ernest and his little aunt...
Dialogue: 0,0:33:18.90,0:33:21.34,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,But upstairs now, like\Na good boy, please,\NMr. Wilde.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:24.91,0:33:26.61,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,You're very kind, Mrs. Burgess.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:26.65,0:33:30.70,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Well, if we can't show\Na little kindness\Non this earth,
Dialogue: 0,0:33:30.74,0:33:33.88,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,we might\Nas well not be here,\Nthat's the way I see it.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:35.97,0:33:37.84,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Now, you keep nice and warm.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:00.42,0:34:02.38,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Are you sure this is\Nthe right place,\Nmy dear chap?
Dialogue: 0,0:34:02.43,0:34:04.95,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,This is where\NI brung him, sir.\NNo mistaking him.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:04.99,0:34:06.87,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Proper artistic\Ngentleman he was.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:06.91,0:34:07.91,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Just wait here, will you?
Dialogue: 0,0:34:07.95,0:34:08.78,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Right, sir.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:18.40,0:34:20.18,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Good morning, madam.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:20.23,0:34:23.88,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Is it remotely possible you\Nhave a Mr. Oscar Wilde\Nstaying here?
Dialogue: 0,0:34:23.93,0:34:24.93,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Why, yes, sir.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:25.93,0:34:27.58,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,How extraordinary.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:27.63,0:34:29.89,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,-Ah, may I step inside?\N-Certainly, sir.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:31.80,0:34:32.98,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Which is his room?
Dialogue: 0,0:34:33.02,0:34:34.55,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,It's just at\Nthe top of the stairs.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:34.59,0:34:36.77,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Oh, but I'd rather\Nyou didn't disturb him, sir.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:36.81,0:34:39.86,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,You see, he was out\Nall night and he's\Nnot at all well.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:40.99,0:34:42.68,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Indeed?
Dialogue: 0,0:34:42.73,0:34:45.51,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I was wondering if\NI'd send for the doctor.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:45.56,0:34:47.34,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,A doctor, madam,\Nwould probably\Nprescribe
Dialogue: 0,0:34:47.38,0:34:49.17,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,a little less brandy\Nin his soda.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:56.18,0:34:57.00,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Well.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:58.79,0:35:01.22,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,So this is\Nwhere you've been\Nhiding yourself, hmm?
Dialogue: 0,0:35:01.27,0:35:02.53,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Bosie.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:02.57,0:35:04.18,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Really, Oscar, you are\Nthe most tedious person.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:04.23,0:35:05.71,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I've been all over Brighton.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:05.75,0:35:07.06,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,From one hotel to another,
Dialogue: 0,0:35:07.10,0:35:09.49,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,tracking you down like\Nsome private detective.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:09.54,0:35:10.84,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,-What do you want?\N-What?
Dialogue: 0,0:35:11.67,0:35:12.84,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,What do I want?
Dialogue: 0,0:35:12.89,0:35:15.37,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I don't want a thing,\NI came to see you.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:15.41,0:35:17.11,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Good heavens,\Nit's so dark in here.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:21.38,0:35:23.81,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Well, I must say\Nyou don't look\Nany too good.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:23.86,0:35:25.03,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Oh, yeah.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:25.07,0:35:26.99,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I think I've got a chill, I...
Dialogue: 0,0:35:27.03,0:35:29.12,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,You must\Nbe out of your mind\Ncoming to a place like this.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:29.17,0:35:30.60,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I can't imagine what\Nthe food must be like.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:30.65,0:35:32.26,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Of course,\Nas soon as I knew\Nyou were in Brighton,
Dialogue: 0,0:35:32.30,0:35:33.78,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I naturally went\Nstraight to The Grand.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:33.82,0:35:35.95,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Naturally.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:36.00,0:35:38.74,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I have a most delightful\Nsuite there overlooking\Nthe sea.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:38.78,0:35:42.09,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,And I shall get the bill,\Nno doubt, in due course.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:42.14,0:35:44.83,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Seriously though, Os,\NI won't allow you to stay
Dialogue: 0,0:35:44.88,0:35:47.10,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,in this dreary little hovel\Nanother minute.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:47.14,0:35:50.67,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Besides, the most fascinating\Npeople are staying at\NThe Grand.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:53.28,0:35:55.45,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Just look\Nat this picture, really.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:56.41,0:35:57.93,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Bosie, can't you understand
Dialogue: 0,0:35:57.98,0:36:01.28,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,that I came here\Nto finish my play\Nin peace and quiet?
Dialogue: 0,0:36:01.33,0:36:04.51,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I was driven\Nnearly frantic in London\Nwith you and your father.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:04.55,0:36:07.16,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Bosie, I've got to work.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:07.20,0:36:10.08,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I'm the last\Nperson in the world to want\Nto interfere with your work.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:10.12,0:36:11.95,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Whether you mean it or not,\Nyou do.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:11.99,0:36:13.86,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,What are you looking for?
Dialogue: 0,0:36:13.91,0:36:15.26,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I'm looking for\Nmy handkerchief. What do\Nyou think I'm looking for?
Dialogue: 0,0:36:15.30,0:36:17.65,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Here it is, for heaven's sake.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:17.69,0:36:19.91,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Really, Oscar,\Nwhen you are ill,\Nyou're singularly unamusing.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:19.96,0:36:21.17,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I can't help being ill.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:21.22,0:36:22.87,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,But you can help being a bore.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:28.09,0:36:29.62,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Is this your new play?
Dialogue: 0,0:36:29.66,0:36:30.84,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,"The Importance\Nof Being Earnest."
Dialogue: 0,0:36:32.92,0:36:35.23,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Yes, it's nearly finished.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:35.28,0:36:39.54,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I'm glad to hear it.\NPoverty ill becomes you.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:39.58,0:36:43.28,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Frankly, I think you're being\Nvery unreasonable about this\Nwhole thing.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:43.33,0:36:46.81,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,You disappear,\Nleaving me in town\Nwithout a penny piece.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:46.85,0:36:48.81,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Are you trying to end\Nthis relationship, Oscar?
Dialogue: 0,0:36:48.85,0:36:50.46,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Is that what you want?
Dialogue: 0,0:36:50.51,0:36:53.21,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I don't know what I want.\NI just want to be left\Nin peace.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:53.25,0:36:54.73,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,"Thank you for your company.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:54.77,0:36:56.91,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,"It was charming while it\Nlasted. Now kindly get out."
Dialogue: 0,0:36:56.95,0:37:00.08,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Bosie, can't you see that I'm\Nill and I hardly know what\NI'm doing?
Dialogue: 0,0:37:00.74,0:37:01.87,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,And what about me?
Dialogue: 0,0:37:01.91,0:37:03.30,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I don't care what you do,
Dialogue: 0,0:37:03.35,0:37:04.61,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,but as long\Nas you go away\Nand leave me alone.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:05.61,0:37:07.92,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,You mean for good?
Dialogue: 0,0:37:07.96,0:37:13.92,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,It can't go on,\Nyour insane tantrums\Nand your extravagances.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:15.01,0:37:16.45,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,It's got to stop, Bosie.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:18.49,0:37:19.75,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Wouldn't my father\Nbe delighted to think
Dialogue: 0,0:37:19.80,0:37:21.63,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,he'd finally broken up\Nour friendship?
Dialogue: 0,0:37:21.67,0:37:23.19,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,My God, it is stuffy in here.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:23.24,0:37:24.80,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I don't know\Nhow you can breathe.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:24.85,0:37:28.42,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Once and for all, I'm sick\Nto death of being a cat's-paw
Dialogue: 0,0:37:28.46,0:37:30.29,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,in this terrible war\Nbetween you and\Nyour father.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:31.59,0:37:33.42,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,And for heaven's sake,\Nclose the window.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:33.46,0:37:35.94,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Am I to be held responsible\Nfor the ravings of my\Nlunatic father?
Dialogue: 0,0:37:35.99,0:37:38.08,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I sometimes think there's very\Nlittle difference between him\Nand you.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:38.12,0:37:39.90,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,You're both insane.\NBosie, the window.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:39.95,0:37:42.39,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,My God, I've had\Njust about had as much\Nas I can stand of this.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:42.43,0:37:44.04,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,-Oh, my God.\N-Is this the thanks I get
Dialogue: 0,0:37:44.08,0:37:45.61,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,-for devoting myself to\Nyou these past two years?\N-My God!
Dialogue: 0,0:37:45.65,0:37:46.91,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,What is happening to me?
Dialogue: 0,0:37:46.96,0:37:48.74,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,How I ever came to think\Nyou were so marvelous...
Dialogue: 0,0:37:48.78,0:37:51.05,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,-Bosie, for God's sake,\Ngo away.\N-Oscar Wilde, the great genius,
Dialogue: 0,0:37:51.09,0:37:52.83,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,the great wit.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:52.87,0:37:54.96,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Idol of society. And look\Nat you sniveling like\Nsome kicked dog.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:56.75,0:37:58.05,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Do you think I'm\Ngoing to let you end\Nthis so easily, Oscar?
Dialogue: 0,0:37:58.10,0:37:59.71,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,You're not going\Nto throw me aside
Dialogue: 0,0:37:59.75,0:38:01.19,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,because you've\Nno further use for me.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:01.23,0:38:02.62,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,You're not my father!
Dialogue: 0,0:38:05.28,0:38:07.06,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Bosie, are you insane?
Dialogue: 0,0:38:07.11,0:38:08.50,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Didn't you know?\NIt runs in the family.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:08.54,0:38:09.54,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Bosie, put it down.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:10.33,0:38:11.24,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Bosie, please!
Dialogue: 0,0:38:20.86,0:38:23.86,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,How insignificant you look\Nwhen you're afraid, Oscar.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:25.39,0:38:27.87,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I never thought\Nyou'd be afraid of me.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:37.61,0:38:39.75,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Oh, this place depresses me.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:55.55,0:38:58.85,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Oh, um...
Dialogue: 0,0:38:58.90,0:39:02.12,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I don't suppose you could let\Nme have some money to pay the\Ncab, could you? I...
Dialogue: 0,0:39:05.82,0:39:06.73,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Oh, well.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:32.10,0:39:33.45,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Wait for me, will you?
Dialogue: 0,0:39:33.50,0:39:34.37,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Yes, ma'am.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:44.77,0:39:47.16,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Good afternoon, madam.\NGood afternoon, Arthur.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:47.21,0:39:48.47,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Is Mr. Wilde at home?
Dialogue: 0,0:39:48.51,0:39:50.17,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Yes, he's working\Nat the moment, madam.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:50.21,0:39:52.17,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,But Mrs. Wilde is\Nin the front room.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:56.35,0:39:58.57,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,-Mrs. Leverson, madam.\N-CONSTANCE: Ada!
Dialogue: 0,0:39:58.61,0:40:00.57,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,My dear,\NI hope you don't mind\Nmy just dropping in.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:00.61,0:40:02.70,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Of course not. Arthur,\Nmay we have some tea,\Nplease?
Dialogue: 0,0:40:02.74,0:40:04.18,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Certainly, madam.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:04.22,0:40:05.96,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,How nice to see you.\NGood heavens, you're freezing.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:06.01,0:40:07.75,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Come and get warm by the fire.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:07.79,0:40:10.93,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I was just embroidering\Nmy birthday present\Nfor Oscar.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:10.97,0:40:12.71,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Do you think\Nhe's going to like it?
Dialogue: 0,0:40:12.75,0:40:16.19,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Oh, I'm sure he will,\Nit's most handsome.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:16.23,0:40:19.59,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Oscar has\Nthe most expensive tastes,\Neven in the simplest things.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:19.63,0:40:20.67,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,How is Oscar?
Dialogue: 0,0:40:20.72,0:40:22.07,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Oh, much better.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:22.11,0:40:24.16,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,He just needed\Nlooking after properly.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:29.12,0:40:30.64,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,What about Bosie?
Dialogue: 0,0:40:34.04,0:40:36.60,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,That's all over now, thank God.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:36.65,0:40:39.78,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I can't tell you\Nwhat it was like, Ada.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:39.82,0:40:41.87,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,To have\Na woman come between\Nyourself and your husband,
Dialogue: 0,0:40:41.91,0:40:43.57,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,that's something\Na wife can understand.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:45.48,0:40:46.44,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,But another man.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:49.01,0:40:52.10,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,OSCAR: Constance,\Nis that Ada's voice I hear?
Dialogue: 0,0:40:52.14,0:40:53.66,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Yes, it is, dearest.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:53.71,0:40:56.14,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I must hide this, I don't\Nwant to spoil the surprise.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:57.49,0:40:59.19,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Ada, my dear.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:59.23,0:41:00.76,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,You're looking\Nwonderful, Oscar.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:00.80,0:41:03.15,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Mm, what a delicious hat!
Dialogue: 0,0:41:03.19,0:41:05.46,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Constance, where's that bottle\Nof champagne I've been\Nhoarding?
Dialogue: 0,0:41:05.50,0:41:07.59,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Oscar, you're not going\Nto start drinking so early.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:07.63,0:41:09.72,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Of course I am.\NThis is a celebration.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:09.77,0:41:10.94,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,You finished the play?
Dialogue: 0,0:41:10.99,0:41:12.55,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,The curtain fell\Non the third act of
Dialogue: 0,0:41:12.60,0:41:14.64,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,The Importance\Nof Being Earnest\Nas the doorbell rang.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:14.68,0:41:15.82,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I'll get the champagne.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:15.86,0:41:17.21,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Ada, your timing is impeccable.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:17.25,0:41:19.21,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,-Is it a good play?\N-Quite extraordinary.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:19.25,0:41:21.30,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Ada, I'm happier than\NI've been for years.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:21.34,0:41:23.48,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I'm working.\NI'm seeing more\Nof the children.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:23.52,0:41:25.43,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Constance is a guardian angel.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:25.48,0:41:29.92,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,In fact, I believe\NI'm getting dull and\Nbourgeois and very old.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:33.83,0:41:35.05,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,You miss him, don't you?
Dialogue: 0,0:41:37.66,0:41:38.67,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Yes.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:42.45,0:41:45.50,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Sometimes when I see the\Nsunlight on an evening sky
Dialogue: 0,0:41:47.06,0:41:49.94,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,or wander by the river\Nand watch the dark waters,
Dialogue: 0,0:41:51.59,0:41:54.25,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I seem to see him\Nflitting by me in\Nthe darkness,
Dialogue: 0,0:41:56.60,0:41:58.60,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,and then I feel terribly alone.
Dialogue: 0,0:42:04.91,0:42:06.00,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Have you seen this?
Dialogue: 0,0:42:12.35,0:42:13.96,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Couldn't find\Nthe champagne glasses.
Dialogue: 0,0:42:14.00,0:42:16.35,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,It's been\Nsuch a long time\Nsince we used them.
Dialogue: 0,0:42:17.79,0:42:19.18,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Oscar, what on earth is it?
Dialogue: 0,0:42:21.36,0:42:24.58,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Bosie's elder brother\Nwas killed yesterday\Nin a hunting accident.
Dialogue: 0,0:42:24.62,0:42:26.97,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Oh, how terrible.
Dialogue: 0,0:42:27.02,0:42:28.80,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,That would be Francis,\Nwouldn't it?
Dialogue: 0,0:42:28.85,0:42:30.93,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Bosie was very fond\Nof him, wasn't he?
Dialogue: 0,0:42:30.98,0:42:32.76,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,-Arthur.\N-Sir?
Dialogue: 0,0:42:32.81,0:42:35.42,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I want you\Nto go to the post office\Npresently and send a telegram.
Dialogue: 0,0:42:35.46,0:42:36.29,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Very good, sir.
Dialogue: 0,0:42:37.20,0:42:38.64,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I think he may need me.
Dialogue: 0,0:42:45.69,0:42:49.08,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,For as much as it has pleased\NAlmighty God
Dialogue: 0,0:42:49.13,0:42:54.22,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,to take unto himself\Nthe soul of our dear\Nbrother departed,
Dialogue: 0,0:42:54.26,0:42:57.66,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,we therefore commit\Nhis body to the ground.
Dialogue: 0,0:43:59.33,0:44:00.33,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Well...
Dialogue: 0,0:44:01.94,0:44:04.90,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,It would seem it takes\Na death to bring about
Dialogue: 0,0:44:04.94,0:44:07.25,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,a family reunion in this house.
Dialogue: 0,0:44:16.74,0:44:18.35,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,You're all very silent.
Dialogue: 0,0:44:20.22,0:44:21.48,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I've just lost a son.
Dialogue: 0,0:44:21.52,0:44:23.66,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Doesn't that mean\Nanything to any of you?
Dialogue: 0,0:44:25.53,0:44:26.62,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Hmm?
Dialogue: 0,0:44:31.71,0:44:34.88,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,You're his mother.\NDon't you weep\Nfor your son?
Dialogue: 0,0:44:36.41,0:44:39.24,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,The only real male son\Nyou ever bore.
Dialogue: 0,0:44:39.28,0:44:42.46,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,-Really, Father...\N-The only real man\Namong the three of you!
Dialogue: 0,0:44:55.30,0:44:56.47,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Goodbye, Mother.
Dialogue: 0,0:44:56.51,0:44:57.39,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Goodbye, Bosie.
Dialogue: 0,0:44:58.08,0:44:58.91,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Bosie!
Dialogue: 0,0:45:03.04,0:45:04.61,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Where the devil do\Nyou think you're going?
Dialogue: 0,0:45:06.96,0:45:08.14,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I've buried my brother.
Dialogue: 0,0:45:09.96,0:45:11.44,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,There's nothing\Nto keep me here any longer.
Dialogue: 0,0:45:11.49,0:45:13.31,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,This is\Nyour home, damn you!
Dialogue: 0,0:45:15.53,0:45:16.93,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,You belong here!
Dialogue: 0,0:45:17.97,0:45:20.63,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,You were born here!
Dialogue: 0,0:45:20.67,0:45:24.19,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Kinmount has been\Nthe House of Douglas\Nfor more than 300 years.
Dialogue: 0,0:45:24.24,0:45:25.98,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,-Goodbye, Percy.\N-Bosie!
Dialogue: 0,0:45:31.68,0:45:32.51,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Bosie.
Dialogue: 0,0:45:35.64,0:45:37.99,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Don't go, boy. Stay here.
Dialogue: 0,0:45:38.03,0:45:39.47,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Just for a few days, eh?
Dialogue: 0,0:45:41.82,0:45:45.22,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,It gets so lonely\Nhere sometimes\Nand...
Dialogue: 0,0:45:47.22,0:45:49.09,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Well, just for a few days,\Neh, Son?
Dialogue: 0,0:45:51.57,0:45:53.05,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,You call me son?
Dialogue: 0,0:45:54.44,0:45:56.71,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I'm not your son.
Dialogue: 0,0:45:56.75,0:45:59.71,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,You disowned me,\Nor had you forgotten?
Dialogue: 0,0:45:59.75,0:46:01.67,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,You disowned me\Njust as you've disowned\Nthe whole family.
Dialogue: 0,0:46:01.71,0:46:02.93,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,You drove Mother\Nout of this house
Dialogue: 0,0:46:02.97,0:46:05.98,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,with your abuse\Nand your immorality.
Dialogue: 0,0:46:06.02,0:46:08.94,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,You persecuted me until I\Nhad to keep away from you
Dialogue: 0,0:46:08.98,0:46:11.46,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,for fear of what\NI might do if I were\Nhere to lay hands on you.
Dialogue: 0,0:46:14.68,0:46:16.07,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I tried to make\Na man out of you.
Dialogue: 0,0:46:17.64,0:46:19.34,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I tried to protect you\Nagainst yourself.
Dialogue: 0,0:46:19.38,0:46:21.25,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,It's no more than any other\Nself-respecting father\Nwould do.
Dialogue: 0,0:46:21.30,0:46:24.34,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,You lost your self respect\Nthe day you threw my mother\Nout of this house
Dialogue: 0,0:46:24.39,0:46:26.56,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,and brought your mistress\Nhere to live with you.
Dialogue: 0,0:46:30.30,0:46:31.96,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,-Damn your insolence!\N-Please!
Dialogue: 0,0:46:32.00,0:46:34.09,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I ought to take a whip\Nand thrash you to the ground.
Dialogue: 0,0:46:34.13,0:46:35.96,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I would welcome\Nthe opportunity,\Nbelieve me.
Dialogue: 0,0:46:36.01,0:46:37.62,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,You talk to me\Nof the moral issue.
Dialogue: 0,0:46:37.66,0:46:39.01,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,-For heaven's sake,\N-Father!
Dialogue: 0,0:46:39.05,0:46:40.44,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Well, what about him and\Nthat damned Wilde fellow?
Dialogue: 0,0:46:40.49,0:46:43.80,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Thank God I succeeded\Nin putting an end to that.
Dialogue: 0,0:46:43.84,0:46:46.06,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,One of these days\Nyou'll get down on your knees
Dialogue: 0,0:46:46.10,0:46:47.36,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,and you'll thank me for it.
Dialogue: 0,0:46:48.98,0:46:51.41,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,He sent me a telegram\Nthis morning.
Dialogue: 0,0:46:51.46,0:46:54.98,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,At least he has more sympathy\Nwith my bereavement than you\Nseem to have.
Dialogue: 0,0:46:55.02,0:46:57.85,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I'm going back to London\Nthis afternoon,\Nand I warn you,
Dialogue: 0,0:46:57.90,0:47:01.38,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,if ever\Nyou try and interfere in\Nmy private affairs again,
Dialogue: 0,0:47:01.42,0:47:05.82,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I'll buy myself a pistol\Nand I'll hunt you down\Nand kill you.
Dialogue: 0,0:47:21.83,0:47:23.01,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Bosie!
Dialogue: 0,0:47:29.49,0:47:30.71,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Bosie!
Dialogue: 0,0:47:33.76,0:47:35.59,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Bosie!
Dialogue: 0,0:47:35.63,0:47:37.72,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,You're no son of mine,\Ndo you hear?
Dialogue: 0,0:47:38.89,0:47:40.90,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,You're not my son!
Dialogue: 0,0:47:40.94,0:47:42.38,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Go back to your\Nprecious friend,
Dialogue: 0,0:47:42.42,0:47:44.55,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,but, I warn you,\NI haven't finished\Nwith you yet!
Dialogue: 0,0:47:44.60,0:47:46.38,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Or him!
Dialogue: 0,0:47:46.42,0:47:48.34,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I'll see you both behind bars!
Dialogue: 0,0:47:49.08,0:47:50.47,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Do you hear?
Dialogue: 0,0:47:51.12,0:47:52.39,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Behind bars!
Dialogue: 0,0:48:09.93,0:48:12.06,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I have a great deal to\Nmake up to you for, Oscar.
Dialogue: 0,0:48:13.97,0:48:15.45,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I've been perfectly\Nhorrible to you\Nin the past.
Dialogue: 0,0:48:15.50,0:48:17.11,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,No, don't mention it anymore.
Dialogue: 0,0:48:18.46,0:48:20.63,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Sometimes it takes\Na good row to clear the air.
Dialogue: 0,0:48:27.60,0:48:29.51,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,What are we going to\Ndo about your father?
Dialogue: 0,0:48:30.82,0:48:32.47,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Believe me, it's\Nonly because of you
Dialogue: 0,0:48:32.51,0:48:35.65,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,that I haven't taken some\Nsort of legal action\Nagainst him.
Dialogue: 0,0:48:35.69,0:48:37.56,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,And involve your\Nwhole family in\Na scandal?
Dialogue: 0,0:48:37.61,0:48:39.96,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,That wouldn't\Nhelp anybody except\Nperhaps the journalists.
Dialogue: 0,0:48:40.00,0:48:41.83,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Just so long as he\Nleaves me alone,\Nthat's all.
Dialogue: 0,0:48:45.96,0:48:48.05,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Good heavens,\Nwhat are we talking\Nabout my father for?
Dialogue: 0,0:48:48.09,0:48:50.14,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Your new play\Nopens on Saturday.
Dialogue: 0,0:48:50.18,0:48:51.88,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,We should be drinking\Nto its success.
Dialogue: 0,0:48:52.40,0:48:54.10,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Its success?
Dialogue: 0,0:48:54.14,0:48:57.32,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,My dear boy,\Nyou don't doubt it'll\Nbe a success, do you?
Dialogue: 0,0:49:00.76,0:49:01.98,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,To The Importance\Nof Being Earnest.
Dialogue: 0,0:49:04.46,0:49:05.94,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,To the importance\Nof friendship.
Dialogue: 0,0:50:20.97,0:50:22.28,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,-Wait there.\N-Yes, sir.
Dialogue: 0,0:50:27.02,0:50:28.28,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Lord Queensberry, sir?
Dialogue: 0,0:50:28.98,0:50:31.02,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Yes.
Dialogue: 0,0:50:31.07,0:50:33.11,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I'm sorry, sir, I've strict\Ninstructions not to let you\Ninto the theater.
Dialogue: 0,0:50:36.42,0:50:37.68,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,You must be out of your senses.
Dialogue: 0,0:50:37.73,0:50:38.55,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I'm sorry, sir.
Dialogue: 0,0:50:39.77,0:50:41.29,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Who the devil are you anyway?
Dialogue: 0,0:50:41.34,0:50:42.64,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I'm a police officer, sir.
Dialogue: 0,0:50:43.64,0:50:45.04,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Are you indeed?
Dialogue: 0,0:50:45.78,0:50:47.17,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Police officer, are you?
Dialogue: 0,0:50:47.91,0:50:49.08,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Are you?
Dialogue: 0,0:50:58.31,0:51:00.05,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Don't forget the cripple, sir.
Dialogue: 0,0:51:01.14,0:51:02.79,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I'm sorry, sir.
Dialogue: 0,0:51:02.84,0:51:04.71,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,No unauthorized persons\Nare permitted to enter\Nthe theater.
Dialogue: 0,0:51:04.75,0:51:06.58,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Do you realize\Nwho you're talking to?
Dialogue: 0,0:51:06.62,0:51:08.71,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Oh, I do indeed, Your Lordship.
Dialogue: 0,0:51:08.76,0:51:10.76,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Now look here, My Lord,\Nwhy don't you run along\Nand forget the whole thing?
Dialogue: 0,0:51:10.80,0:51:13.20,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,You don't want to\Ngo in there and spoil\Neverybody's enjoyment.
Dialogue: 0,0:51:13.24,0:51:14.72,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I'm not\Ncompletely\Nwithout influence.
Dialogue: 0,0:51:14.76,0:51:16.24,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I'm quite sure\Nyou're not, My Lord.
Dialogue: 0,0:51:16.29,0:51:18.77,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,No, I shall\Nreport you to your\Nsenior officer, sir.
Dialogue: 0,0:51:25.12,0:51:27.43,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Bit loose\Nin the upper story,\Nwouldn't you say, sir?
Dialogue: 0,0:51:27.47,0:51:29.30,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Hmm.
Dialogue: 0,0:51:29.34,0:51:31.26,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Well, let's hope that's\Nthe last we've seen\Nof him tonight.
Dialogue: 0,0:51:48.32,0:51:51.89,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Ladies and gentlemen,\NI have enjoyed this\Nevening immensely.
Dialogue: 0,0:51:53.84,0:51:57.72,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,The actors have given\Na charming rendering\Nof a delightful play.
Dialogue: 0,0:52:03.16,0:52:05.42,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,And your appreciation\Nhas been most intelligent.
Dialogue: 0,0:52:07.12,0:52:10.34,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I congratulate\Nyou on the success\Nof your performance,
Dialogue: 0,0:52:10.38,0:52:11.82,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,which proves to me
Dialogue: 0,0:52:11.86,0:52:15.04,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,that you think\Nalmost as highly\Nof the play as I do.
Dialogue: 0,0:52:51.60,0:52:52.69,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,-That's quite a wit...\N-Cab!
Dialogue: 0,0:52:52.73,0:52:54.08,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,There's Queensberry.
Dialogue: 0,0:52:54.12,0:52:55.25,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Queensberry? What's he up to?
Dialogue: 0,0:52:55.30,0:52:56.69,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Mad as ever, I suppose.
Dialogue: 0,0:52:59.78,0:53:00.91,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Mad.
Dialogue: 0,0:53:03.39,0:53:06.40,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,QUEENSBERRY:\NExcuse me! Excuse me!
Dialogue: 0,0:53:14.75,0:53:18.32,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Mr. Wilde,\Nmay I present\Nyou with this, sir?
Dialogue: 0,0:53:20.54,0:53:22.80,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,How charming.
Dialogue: 0,0:53:22.85,0:53:25.59,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Every time I smell them,\NI shall think of you,\NLord Queensberry.
Dialogue: 0,0:53:54.62,0:53:56.23,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,The Albemarle Club.
Dialogue: 0,0:54:02.45,0:54:04.98,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Hurry. Hurry!
Dialogue: 0,0:54:23.95,0:54:25.17,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Can I help you, sir?
Dialogue: 0,0:54:25.21,0:54:26.26,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Give me a pen.
Dialogue: 0,0:54:27.43,0:54:29.52,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Now, I want you
Dialogue: 0,0:54:30.78,0:54:33.57,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,to give this message
Dialogue: 0,0:54:35.83,0:54:37.18,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,to Mr. Oscar Wilde.
Dialogue: 0,0:54:37.23,0:54:38.18,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Very good, sir.
Dialogue: 0,0:55:20.01,0:55:21.31,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Here you are, Edward.
Dialogue: 0,0:55:21.36,0:55:22.53,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Thank you, Mr. Wilde, sir.
Dialogue: 0,0:55:22.58,0:55:24.71,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,-Good morning, Wilde.\N-Congratulations!
Dialogue: 0,0:55:24.75,0:55:25.58,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,-Thank you.\N-Cab!
Dialogue: 0,0:55:33.59,0:55:34.85,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Wilde, my dear fellow.
Dialogue: 0,0:55:34.89,0:55:38.11,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Saw your\Nplay last night.\NLaughed myself sick.
Dialogue: 0,0:55:38.16,0:55:40.46,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,You seem to have made\Na remarkable recovery, Major.
Dialogue: 0,0:55:42.51,0:55:46.16,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Oh, Mr. Wilde.\NA gentleman left this\Nfor you last night, sir.
Dialogue: 0,0:55:46.21,0:55:48.56,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,-Oh.\N-I hear your play\Nwas a big success, sir.
Dialogue: 0,0:55:48.60,0:55:50.34,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Congratulations,\Nif I may say so.
Dialogue: 0,0:55:50.39,0:55:51.21,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Thank you, Sydney.
Dialogue: 0,0:56:06.23,0:56:08.49,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Hello, old chap.\NEnjoyed your play...
Dialogue: 0,0:56:17.80,0:56:19.24,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Well, there's no doubt,\NMr. Wilde,
Dialogue: 0,0:56:19.28,0:56:21.55,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,on the basis\Nof what is written\Non this card alone,
Dialogue: 0,0:56:21.59,0:56:23.51,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,you have the strongest\Npossible grounds
Dialogue: 0,0:56:23.55,0:56:26.42,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,for an action against\NLord Queensberry for\Ncriminal libel.
Dialogue: 0,0:56:26.47,0:56:29.29,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Does that mean,\NSir Edward, that\Nyou will take the case?
Dialogue: 0,0:56:29.34,0:56:31.21,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Well, the question is,\Nof course,
Dialogue: 0,0:56:31.25,0:56:32.82,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,do you want to proceed\Nwith this action?
Dialogue: 0,0:56:33.34,0:56:34.39,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Well, of course!
Dialogue: 0,0:56:35.47,0:56:37.00,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Why do you ask that,\NSir Edward?
Dialogue: 0,0:56:37.04,0:56:38.61,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Well, no doubt,\NQueensberry's defense
Dialogue: 0,0:56:38.65,0:56:40.91,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,will be that the libelous\Nstatement complained of
Dialogue: 0,0:56:40.96,0:56:43.70,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,was justified\Nand in effect true.
Dialogue: 0,0:56:43.74,0:56:45.61,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,It most certainly isn't true.
Dialogue: 0,0:56:45.66,0:56:49.01,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Nevertheless, the defense\Nwill make every effort to\Nprove that it is,
Dialogue: 0,0:56:49.05,0:56:51.45,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,and that could be extremely\Nembarrassing for Mr. Wilde.
Dialogue: 0,0:56:51.49,0:56:53.45,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I agree. Oscar,\Nit simply isn't worth it.
Dialogue: 0,0:56:53.49,0:56:55.19,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Queensberry's\Nobviously a lunatic.
Dialogue: 0,0:56:55.23,0:56:57.54,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,To take\Nan action against him\Nis exactly what he wants.
Dialogue: 0,0:56:57.58,0:56:59.45,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,That's why he left that card.
Dialogue: 0,0:56:59.50,0:57:01.98,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,But if we let\Nhim get away with this,\Nthere'll be no holding him.
Dialogue: 0,0:57:02.02,0:57:05.33,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,We have to\Ndraw a line somewhere.\NIt's a matter of principle.
Dialogue: 0,0:57:05.37,0:57:07.03,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I'm afraid Lord Alfred\Nis right.
Dialogue: 0,0:57:07.07,0:57:09.07,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,The man must be\Nstopped somewhere.
Dialogue: 0,0:57:09.12,0:57:10.94,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Then you\Nwish to proceed\Nwith this action?
Dialogue: 0,0:57:10.99,0:57:13.47,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I do.
Dialogue: 0,0:57:13.51,0:57:16.17,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Can't wait to see\Nmy father's face when\NI go into the witness box.
Dialogue: 0,0:57:16.21,0:57:17.56,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,When I tell...
Dialogue: 0,0:57:17.60,0:57:19.74,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,You're not going into\Nthe witness box, Bosie.
Dialogue: 0,0:57:20.69,0:57:22.65,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Are you mad, Oscar?
Dialogue: 0,0:57:22.70,0:57:24.22,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I've only got\Nto tell them\Nhow he's...
Dialogue: 0,0:57:24.26,0:57:26.00,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,How he's\Npersecuted me\Nthese past two years,
Dialogue: 0,0:57:26.05,0:57:27.87,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,how he drove my\Nmother out of the house\Nwith his insane ravings.
Dialogue: 0,0:57:27.92,0:57:30.09,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I'm not having\Nyou involved, Bosie.
Dialogue: 0,0:57:30.14,0:57:33.53,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I'm afraid, Mr. Wilde,\Nthat Lord Alfred is\Nalready involved.
Dialogue: 0,0:57:33.58,0:57:35.32,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Well, of course I'm involved.
Dialogue: 0,0:57:35.36,0:57:37.80,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I'm not having\Nyou exposed to more\Nscandal than is necessary.
Dialogue: 0,0:57:37.84,0:57:39.58,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Oscar, don't you realize...
Dialogue: 0,0:57:39.63,0:57:41.71,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Bosie, you're not going\Ninto the witness box\Nand that is final.
Dialogue: 0,0:57:58.30,0:58:00.69,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,You'll have\Nto forgive Bosie.\NHe's a little impulsive.
Dialogue: 0,0:58:01.34,0:58:03.26,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,So it would seem.
Dialogue: 0,0:58:03.30,0:58:05.78,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Anyway, you have a very\Nstrong case, Mr. Wilde.
Dialogue: 0,0:58:07.22,0:58:08.35,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,What's the matter, Robbie?
Dialogue: 0,0:58:10.13,0:58:12.27,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Are you determined\Nto bring about your\Nown destruction, Oscar?
Dialogue: 0,0:58:12.31,0:58:13.53,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Is that what you're\Ntrying to do?
Dialogue: 0,0:58:13.57,0:58:14.88,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I don't understand.
Dialogue: 0,0:58:14.92,0:58:15.84,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I used to think\Nyou had a mind\Nof your own.
Dialogue: 0,0:58:15.88,0:58:17.45,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,A great mind. Oh, really.
Dialogue: 0,0:58:17.49,0:58:19.27,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Oscar, you mustn't\Nlet Bosie push you\Ninto this thing.
Dialogue: 0,0:58:19.32,0:58:20.97,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,-What's the alternative?\N-Go abroad.
Dialogue: 0,0:58:21.01,0:58:23.15,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Let Queensberry\Nand his son fight\Ntheir quarrel without you.
Dialogue: 0,0:58:23.19,0:58:24.28,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,They're well-matched.
Dialogue: 0,0:58:24.32,0:58:27.06,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,It's too late, Robbie.
Dialogue: 0,0:58:27.11,0:58:28.98,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Well, Sir Edward,\NI'm entirely at\Nyour disposal.
Dialogue: 0,0:58:29.02,0:58:30.55,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Any further information\Nyou need?
Dialogue: 0,0:58:30.59,0:58:32.68,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,There is one question\NI feel compelled to ask.
Dialogue: 0,0:58:33.42,0:58:34.68,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Please do.
Dialogue: 0,0:58:34.72,0:58:37.12,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I can only accept\Nthis brief, Mr. Wilde,
Dialogue: 0,0:58:37.16,0:58:40.08,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,if you assure\Nme on your honor as\Nan English gentleman
Dialogue: 0,0:58:40.12,0:58:42.99,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,that there is no truth in\Nthe charges made against you.
Dialogue: 0,0:58:46.00,0:58:48.87,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I assure you as\Nan Irish gentleman
Dialogue: 0,0:58:48.91,0:58:52.05,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,that there's no truth\Nwhatever in any of them.
Dialogue: 0,0:58:52.09,0:58:54.53,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Well, then, shall we say\Nhere tomorrow morning\Nat 10:30, Mr. Wilde?
Dialogue: 0,0:58:55.74,0:58:58.05,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Good. Mr. Humphries.
Dialogue: 0,0:59:04.54,0:59:06.97,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Paper! Queensberry arrested!
Dialogue: 0,0:59:07.02,0:59:10.11,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Paper! Paper! Special edition!
Dialogue: 0,0:59:10.15,0:59:11.63,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Queensberry arrested!
Dialogue: 0,0:59:11.67,0:59:14.28,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Paper! Paper, sir! Paper!
Dialogue: 0,0:59:34.74,0:59:36.57,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,COURT USHER: Silence!
Dialogue: 0,1:00:02.03,1:00:04.73,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,That's Edward Carson,\Ndefending Queensberry.
Dialogue: 0,1:00:11.78,1:00:13.91,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,We went to\NTrinity College together.
Dialogue: 0,1:00:13.95,1:00:17.91,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,No doubt he'll perform\Nhis task with all the added\Nbitterness of an old friend.
Dialogue: 0,1:00:18.70,1:00:19.96,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,COURT USHER: Silence!
Dialogue: 0,1:00:20.00,1:00:21.87,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Be upstanding in court.
Dialogue: 0,1:00:24.01,1:00:25.75,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,All persons who\Nhave anything to do
Dialogue: 0,1:00:25.79,1:00:28.84,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,before My Lords,\Nthe Queen's justices\Nof oyer and terminer
Dialogue: 0,1:00:28.88,1:00:32.54,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,and general gaol delivery\Nfor the jurisdiction of\Nthe Central Criminal Court,
Dialogue: 0,1:00:32.58,1:00:36.06,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,draw near and give\Nyour attendance.\NGod save the Queen.
Dialogue: 0,1:00:46.38,1:00:51.64,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Put up\NJohn Sholto Douglas,\NMarquis of Queensberry.
Dialogue: 0,1:00:51.69,1:00:54.52,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,John Sholto Douglas,\NMarquis of Queensberry.
Dialogue: 0,1:01:08.83,1:01:11.88,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Are you\NJohn Sholto Douglas,\NMarquis of Queensberry?
Dialogue: 0,1:01:12.66,1:01:14.36,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I am, sir.
Dialogue: 0,1:01:14.40,1:01:18.32,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,"The jurors for\NOur Lady, the Queen,\Nupon their oath present
Dialogue: 0,1:01:18.37,1:01:22.50,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,"that John Sholto Douglas,\NMarquis of Queensberry,
Dialogue: 0,1:01:22.54,1:01:25.59,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,"contriving and maliciously\Nintending to injure one
Dialogue: 0,1:01:25.63,1:01:28.77,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,"Oscar Fingal O'Flahertie\NWills Wilde,
Dialogue: 0,1:01:28.81,1:01:31.25,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,"and to excite him to\Ncommit a breach of peace,
Dialogue: 0,1:01:31.29,1:01:35.60,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,"and to bring him\Ninto public contempt,\Nscandal and disgrace,
Dialogue: 0,1:01:35.64,1:01:41.13,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,"did on the\N14th day of February in\Nthe year of our Lord 1895,
Dialogue: 0,1:01:41.17,1:01:43.65,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,"and within the jurisdiction\Nof this court
Dialogue: 0,1:01:43.70,1:01:48.13,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,"unlawfully, wickedly and\Nmaliciously write and publish
Dialogue: 0,1:01:48.18,1:01:50.44,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,"a false and scandalous,
Dialogue: 0,1:01:50.48,1:01:55.58,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,"malicious and\Ndefamatory libel,\Nin the form of a card,
Dialogue: 0,1:01:55.62,1:02:00.06,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,"directed to the said Oscar\NFingal O'Flahertie\NWills Wilde,
Dialogue: 0,1:02:00.10,1:02:02.37,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,"on which were\Nwritten the words,
Dialogue: 0,1:02:02.41,1:02:06.11,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,"'To Oscar Wilde,\Nposing as a sodomite.'"
Dialogue: 0,1:02:15.77,1:02:17.73,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,COURT USHER: Silence in court.
Dialogue: 0,1:02:17.77,1:02:21.25,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,"To the great damage,\Nscandal and disgrace
Dialogue: 0,1:02:21.30,1:02:24.34,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,"of the said Oscar Fingal\NO'Flahertie Wills Wilde
Dialogue: 0,1:02:24.39,1:02:30.26,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,"and against the peace of\Nour said Lady the Queen,\Nher crown and dignity,
Dialogue: 0,1:02:30.31,1:02:34.79,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,"John Sholto Douglas,\NMarquis of Queensberry,
Dialogue: 0,1:02:34.83,1:02:37.57,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,"upon the\Naforesaid indictment,\Nhow do you plead?"
Dialogue: 0,1:02:38.31,1:02:40.23,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Guilty or not guilty?
Dialogue: 0,1:02:40.27,1:02:41.67,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Not guilty, My Lord.
Dialogue: 0,1:02:42.88,1:02:44.19,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,If it please you, My Lord,
Dialogue: 0,1:02:44.23,1:02:46.98,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,it is my client's plea\Nthat the alleged libel
Dialogue: 0,1:02:47.02,1:02:49.50,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,according to the natural\Nmeaning of the words thereof
Dialogue: 0,1:02:49.54,1:02:51.33,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,is true in substance\Nand in fact,
Dialogue: 0,1:02:51.37,1:02:54.20,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,and that it was for the\Npublic benefit and interest
Dialogue: 0,1:02:54.24,1:02:57.25,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,that the matter contained in\Nthe alleged libel should\Nbe published.
Dialogue: 0,1:02:57.29,1:03:00.25,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Such a plea has been\Nfiled with this court?
Dialogue: 0,1:03:00.29,1:03:01.56,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,It has, My Lord.
Dialogue: 0,1:03:01.60,1:03:04.47,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Thank you, Mr. Carson.\NLet the jury be sworn.
Dialogue: 0,1:03:06.39,1:03:09.26,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Take the Bible\Nin your right hand\Nand read from the card.
Dialogue: 0,1:03:09.30,1:03:13.09,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,"I swear by Almighty God\Nthat I will well and truly..."
Dialogue: 0,1:03:13.13,1:03:14.66,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I put the card in an envelope,
Dialogue: 0,1:03:14.70,1:03:16.79,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,which I addressed\Nto Mr. Oscar Wilde
Dialogue: 0,1:03:16.83,1:03:18.92,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,and when Mr. Wilde\Ncame into the club,
Dialogue: 0,1:03:18.96,1:03:22.71,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I handed it to him saying that\NLord Queensberry had asked\Nme to give it to him.
Dialogue: 0,1:03:22.75,1:03:25.32,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,And did you look at this card\Nwhen Lord Queensberry\Ngave it to you?
Dialogue: 0,1:03:25.36,1:03:26.45,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I did, sir.
Dialogue: 0,1:03:27.23,1:03:28.06,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Thank you, Mr. Wright.
Dialogue: 0,1:03:29.63,1:03:31.11,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I have no questions, My Lord.
Dialogue: 0,1:03:31.15,1:03:33.02,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,COURT USHER:\NThe witness may stand down.
Dialogue: 0,1:03:37.90,1:03:40.42,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I don't think there's\Nany suggestion by the defense
Dialogue: 0,1:03:40.46,1:03:43.25,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,that Lord Queensberry did\Nnot leave this card at\Nthe Albemarle Club,
Dialogue: 0,1:03:43.29,1:03:46.03,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,nor that he wrote upon it\Nthe words complained of\Nby my client.
Dialogue: 0,1:03:47.38,1:03:49.34,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,In his plea of justification
Dialogue: 0,1:03:49.39,1:03:52.13,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,in which the defendant seeks\Nto malign the character\Nof Mr. Oscar Wilde,
Dialogue: 0,1:03:52.17,1:03:54.61,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,the defendant put\Nin evidence a letter
Dialogue: 0,1:03:54.65,1:03:57.87,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,written by\NMr. Oscar Wilde to\NLord Alfred Douglas,
Dialogue: 0,1:03:57.92,1:03:59.66,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,the son of the accused.
Dialogue: 0,1:03:59.70,1:04:02.44,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I now propose\Nto read the letter\Nto the court, My Lord.
Dialogue: 0,1:04:02.49,1:04:06.49,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,"My own boy, your\Nsonnet is quite lovely,
Dialogue: 0,1:04:06.53,1:04:10.15,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,"and it is a marvel that\Nthose red rose leaf lips\Nof yours
Dialogue: 0,1:04:10.19,1:04:14.93,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,"should have been made\Nno less for music of song\Nthan for madness of kisses.
Dialogue: 0,1:04:14.98,1:04:18.50,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,"Your slim guilt soul walks\Nbetween passion and poetry.
Dialogue: 0,1:04:18.55,1:04:21.50,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,"I know Hyacinthus,\Nwhom Apollo loved\Nso madly,
Dialogue: 0,1:04:21.55,1:04:23.55,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,"was you in Greek days.
Dialogue: 0,1:04:23.59,1:04:27.16,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,"Always with undying love,\Nyours, Oscar."
Dialogue: 0,1:04:29.51,1:04:32.91,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,The words contained in that\Nletter may appear somewhat\Nextravagant
Dialogue: 0,1:04:32.95,1:04:36.65,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,for those normally\Nengaged in the writing of\Ncommercial correspondence.
Dialogue: 0,1:04:38.17,1:04:39.13,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Silence!
Dialogue: 0,1:04:39.17,1:04:41.31,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,But Mr. Wilde is a poet
Dialogue: 0,1:04:41.35,1:04:44.88,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,and that letter\Nis considered by him\Nto be a prose sonnet,
Dialogue: 0,1:04:44.92,1:04:48.40,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,and one in which\Nhe is no way ashamed.
Dialogue: 0,1:04:48.44,1:04:51.32,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I now ask\NMr. Oscar Wilde to\Ngo into the witness box.
Dialogue: 0,1:04:59.24,1:05:02.98,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Take the Bible\Nin your right hand\Nand read from the card.
Dialogue: 0,1:05:03.02,1:05:06.11,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,"I swear by Almighty God\Nthat the evidence I give\Nto this court
Dialogue: 0,1:05:06.16,1:05:08.46,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,"shall be the\Ntruth, the whole truth,\Nand nothing but the truth,
Dialogue: 0,1:05:08.51,1:05:09.55,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,"so help me God."
Dialogue: 0,1:05:14.60,1:05:17.69,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,You are Mr. Oscar Wilde and\Nyou are the prosecutor in\Nthis case.
Dialogue: 0,1:05:17.73,1:05:18.95,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I am.
Dialogue: 0,1:05:19.00,1:05:20.48,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,How old are you, Mr. Wilde?
Dialogue: 0,1:05:20.52,1:05:22.04,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I'm 39.
Dialogue: 0,1:05:22.09,1:05:23.87,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Are you married, Mr. Wilde?
Dialogue: 0,1:05:23.92,1:05:28.22,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I am, and I have two children,\None aged nine and the other\Neight.
Dialogue: 0,1:05:28.27,1:05:30.88,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,And when did you\Nfirst become acquainted\Nwith Lord Alfred Douglas?
Dialogue: 0,1:05:32.23,1:05:34.97,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,In 1891.
Dialogue: 0,1:05:35.01,1:05:36.97,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,A friend\Nbrought him to my house.
Dialogue: 0,1:05:37.02,1:05:39.63,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,And since that time you\Nhave become close friends?
Dialogue: 0,1:05:39.67,1:05:41.93,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,He was a guest at\Nmy house many times.
Dialogue: 0,1:05:41.98,1:05:44.37,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,A guest of yourself\Nand your wife?
Dialogue: 0,1:05:44.41,1:05:45.24,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Certainly.
Dialogue: 0,1:05:47.11,1:05:49.85,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,In March 1893,
Dialogue: 0,1:05:49.90,1:05:54.03,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,did it come to your notice\Nthat a letter addressed by\Nyou to Lord Alfred Douglas
Dialogue: 0,1:05:54.08,1:05:58.17,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,had come\Ninto the hands of\Na certain person?
Dialogue: 0,1:05:58.21,1:06:00.60,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Yes, a man named Wood\Ncame to me
Dialogue: 0,1:06:00.65,1:06:04.74,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,and said that he'd found it in\Na suit of clothes belonging to\NLord Alfred.
Dialogue: 0,1:06:04.78,1:06:06.65,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Did he\Ndemand money\Nfor that letter?
Dialogue: 0,1:06:06.70,1:06:08.92,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,He said a man had\Noffered him 拢60\Nfor it.
Dialogue: 0,1:06:08.96,1:06:10.40,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,And what did you say to that?
Dialogue: 0,1:06:10.44,1:06:12.49,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I said\NI'd never received\Nso large an amount
Dialogue: 0,1:06:12.53,1:06:14.27,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,for a prose work\Nof that length,
Dialogue: 0,1:06:14.31,1:06:17.27,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,and I advised him to\Nsell it to the man\Nat once.
Dialogue: 0,1:06:20.58,1:06:24.50,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Prior to this time,\Nyou had been subjected\Nto considerable annoyance
Dialogue: 0,1:06:24.54,1:06:26.11,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,by Lord Queensberry,\Nhad you not?
Dialogue: 0,1:06:26.63,1:06:28.41,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Oh, yes.
Dialogue: 0,1:06:28.46,1:06:30.85,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,He'd written several\Nabusive letters to myself\Nand my friends
Dialogue: 0,1:06:30.89,1:06:33.51,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,and on one occasion,\Nhe forced his way\Ninto my house
Dialogue: 0,1:06:33.55,1:06:34.94,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,and I was compelled\Nto eject him.
Dialogue: 0,1:06:34.99,1:06:37.29,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,And what\Ntook place on\Nthat occasion?
Dialogue: 0,1:06:37.34,1:06:40.95,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,He made certain accusations\Nabout my relationship\Nwith Lord Alfred
Dialogue: 0,1:06:40.99,1:06:43.04,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,and I said to him,
Dialogue: 0,1:06:43.08,1:06:47.35,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,"Lord Queensberry, do you\Nseriously accuse your son\Nand me of improper conduct?"
Dialogue: 0,1:06:47.39,1:06:49.22,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,And what did he say to that?
Dialogue: 0,1:06:49.26,1:06:52.92,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,He said,\N"I don't say you are,\Nbut I say you look it."
Dialogue: 0,1:06:54.14,1:06:55.75,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Silence in court!
Dialogue: 0,1:06:55.79,1:06:57.75,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,If there\Nis the slightest\Ndisturbance again,
Dialogue: 0,1:06:57.79,1:06:59.01,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I shall have the court cleared.
Dialogue: 0,1:07:00.75,1:07:05.36,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Mr. Wilde,\Nyour attention has been\Ndrawn to certain statements
Dialogue: 0,1:07:05.41,1:07:07.37,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,made in the plea\Nof justification
Dialogue: 0,1:07:07.41,1:07:09.98,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,filed by\Nthe defendant,\NLord Queensberry,
Dialogue: 0,1:07:10.02,1:07:14.37,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,with reference to different\Npersons impugning your\Nconduct with them.
Dialogue: 0,1:07:15.07,1:07:15.94,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Yes.
Dialogue: 0,1:07:16.94,1:07:18.94,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Mr. Wilde,
Dialogue: 0,1:07:18.99,1:07:23.03,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,is there any\Ntruth whatever in any\Nof those accusations?
Dialogue: 0,1:07:23.08,1:07:24.77,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,None whatever in any of them.
Dialogue: 0,1:07:33.74,1:07:34.87,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Thank you, Mr. Wilde.
Dialogue: 0,1:07:41.53,1:07:47.15,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Mr. Wilde,\Nyou stated earlier\Nthat your age was 39.
Dialogue: 0,1:07:47.19,1:07:48.76,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,-Is that correct?\N-Yes.
Dialogue: 0,1:07:51.11,1:07:56.81,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,You were born in 1854.\NThat makes you over\N40, doesn't it?
Dialogue: 0,1:07:59.81,1:08:00.90,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Oh, very well.
Dialogue: 0,1:08:01.81,1:08:04.03,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Hmm.
Dialogue: 0,1:08:04.08,1:08:07.51,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,At what age was\NLord Alfred Douglas\Nwhen you first met him?
Dialogue: 0,1:08:07.56,1:08:09.43,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,He was between 20 and 21.
Dialogue: 0,1:08:09.47,1:08:11.60,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Not yet 21. Hmm.
Dialogue: 0,1:08:13.26,1:08:16.48,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,And since that time you\Nhave been close friends?
Dialogue: 0,1:08:17.35,1:08:18.87,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Yes.
Dialogue: 0,1:08:18.92,1:08:21.40,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,You've stayed with\Nhim at many places?
Dialogue: 0,1:08:22.44,1:08:24.05,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Yes.
Dialogue: 0,1:08:24.10,1:08:27.97,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,At Oxford, Brighton,\Non several occasions?
Dialogue: 0,1:08:28.45,1:08:29.84,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Yes.
Dialogue: 0,1:08:29.88,1:08:32.02,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,And at various\Nhotels in London?
Dialogue: 0,1:08:32.36,1:08:34.02,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Yes.
Dialogue: 0,1:08:34.06,1:08:36.50,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,You've also been abroad\Nwith him several times.
Dialogue: 0,1:08:36.54,1:08:40.37,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Yes, to Egypt,\NParis and Monte Carlo.
Dialogue: 0,1:08:40.42,1:08:44.64,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,One could\Ntherefore describe\Nyour friendship as intimate?
Dialogue: 0,1:08:45.86,1:08:46.68,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Yes, very.
Dialogue: 0,1:08:48.73,1:08:50.73,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Indeed.
Dialogue: 0,1:08:50.77,1:08:54.69,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I have\Nhere a magazine\Ncalled The Chameleon,
Dialogue: 0,1:08:54.73,1:08:56.48,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,in which is\Nan article by yourself.
Dialogue: 0,1:08:56.52,1:08:59.61,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Also, two\Npoems contributed\Nby Lord Alfred Douglas.
Dialogue: 0,1:08:59.65,1:09:01.52,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Yes, I thought them\Nexceedingly beautiful.
Dialogue: 0,1:09:02.87,1:09:04.53,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Did you?
Dialogue: 0,1:09:04.57,1:09:07.23,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Do you remember\Nthe titles of these\Ntwo poems, Mr. Wilde?
Dialogue: 0,1:09:07.27,1:09:09.53,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Yes. One was called\NIn Praise of Shame,
Dialogue: 0,1:09:09.58,1:09:10.40,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,and the other, Two Loves.
Dialogue: 0,1:09:11.53,1:09:13.27,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Thank you.
Dialogue: 0,1:09:13.32,1:09:16.58,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,These two loves,\Nthey were two boys,\Nweren't they?
Dialogue: 0,1:09:17.54,1:09:18.37,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Yes.
Dialogue: 0,1:09:20.54,1:09:26.55,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,One boy calls his love\Ntrue love and the other\Nboy calls his love shame.
Dialogue: 0,1:09:27.20,1:09:28.03,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,That is correct.
Dialogue: 0,1:09:29.90,1:09:32.38,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Do you think that made\Nany improper suggestion?
Dialogue: 0,1:09:32.42,1:09:33.86,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,No, not at all.
Dialogue: 0,1:09:35.38,1:09:36.21,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Hmm.
Dialogue: 0,1:09:38.04,1:09:41.96,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,There's another article\Nin this magazine
Dialogue: 0,1:09:42.00,1:09:45.39,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,entitled The Priest\Nand the Acolyte.\NHave you read that?
Dialogue: 0,1:09:46.09,1:09:47.87,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I have.
Dialogue: 0,1:09:47.92,1:09:51.62,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Did you consider\Nthat this article\Nwas in any way immoral?
Dialogue: 0,1:09:51.66,1:09:53.92,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,It was worse.\NIt was very badly written.
Dialogue: 0,1:09:55.88,1:09:59.84,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Was it not the\Nstory of a priest who fell\Nin love with an altar boy?
Dialogue: 0,1:09:59.89,1:10:02.54,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Well, I read it only once\Nand nothing would induce\Nme to read it again.
Dialogue: 0,1:10:02.58,1:10:04.41,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Do you think the\Nstory blasphemous?
Dialogue: 0,1:10:04.46,1:10:07.46,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I think\Nit violates every\Nartistic canon of beauty.
Dialogue: 0,1:10:07.50,1:10:09.11,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,That is not an answer.
Dialogue: 0,1:10:09.16,1:10:10.81,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,That's the only answer\NI can give.
Dialogue: 0,1:10:10.85,1:10:13.81,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I wish to know\Nwhether you thought\Nthe story blasphemous?
Dialogue: 0,1:10:15.47,1:10:18.34,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,It disgusted me,\Nand the end was\Ncompletely wrong.
Dialogue: 0,1:10:18.38,1:10:19.91,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Will you answer the question?
Dialogue: 0,1:10:19.95,1:10:22.26,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Did you or did you not\Nconsider the story\Nblasphemous?
Dialogue: 0,1:10:22.30,1:10:25.00,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I thought it was horrid.\NBlasphemous is not\Na word of mine.
Dialogue: 0,1:10:25.83,1:10:26.65,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I see.
Dialogue: 0,1:10:28.65,1:10:32.40,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Now, from the same\Nmagazine here
Dialogue: 0,1:10:32.44,1:10:37.23,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,are some of the phrases and\Nphilosophies for the use\Nof the young
Dialogue: 0,1:10:37.27,1:10:39.27,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,which you contributed.
Dialogue: 0,1:10:39.32,1:10:41.54,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,"Wickedness is a myth\Ninvented by good people
Dialogue: 0,1:10:41.58,1:10:44.32,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,"to account\Nfor the curious\Nattractiveness of others."
Dialogue: 0,1:10:45.11,1:10:46.28,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Do you think that true?
Dialogue: 0,1:10:46.32,1:10:48.76,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I rarely think anything\NI write is true.
Dialogue: 0,1:10:52.37,1:10:55.55,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,"Religions die hard when\Nthey are proved to be true."
Dialogue: 0,1:10:55.59,1:10:56.99,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Is that true?
Dialogue: 0,1:10:57.03,1:10:58.34,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Yes, I hold to that,
Dialogue: 0,1:10:58.38,1:11:00.60,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,but it's too big\Na question to go\Ninto here.
Dialogue: 0,1:11:00.64,1:11:02.47,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Did you think\Nthat was a safe axiom
Dialogue: 0,1:11:02.51,1:11:05.13,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,to put forward for the\Nphilosophy of the young?
Dialogue: 0,1:11:05.17,1:11:07.48,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I think it's most stimulating.
Dialogue: 0,1:11:07.52,1:11:11.09,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,"If one tells the truth, one\Nis sure sooner or later to\Nbe found out."
Dialogue: 0,1:11:13.66,1:11:17.09,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,A pleasing paradox, but I do\Nnot set very much store\Non it as an axiom.
Dialogue: 0,1:11:17.14,1:11:19.31,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Whether moral or immoral?
Dialogue: 0,1:11:19.36,1:11:22.84,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,There is no morality\Nor immorality in thought.
Dialogue: 0,1:11:22.88,1:11:24.88,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,There are immoral emotions.
Dialogue: 0,1:11:24.93,1:11:25.97,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Quite so.
Dialogue: 0,1:11:27.76,1:11:30.28,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Now then.
Dialogue: 0,1:11:30.32,1:11:34.63,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,This is the\Nintroduction to your book,\NThe Picture of Dorian Gray.
Dialogue: 0,1:11:36.42,1:11:39.25,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,"There is no such thing\Nas a moral or immoral book.
Dialogue: 0,1:11:39.29,1:11:41.86,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,"Books are\Nwell written\Nor badly written."
Dialogue: 0,1:11:41.90,1:11:43.51,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,That expresses your view?
Dialogue: 0,1:11:43.56,1:11:45.30,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,My view on art, yes.
Dialogue: 0,1:11:45.34,1:11:49.00,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Then no matter how\Nimmoral a book may be,\Nif it is well written,
Dialogue: 0,1:11:49.04,1:11:51.00,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,it is in your opinion\Na good book.
Dialogue: 0,1:11:51.04,1:11:54.26,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,If it is well written so as\Nto produce a sense of beauty.
Dialogue: 0,1:11:54.31,1:11:55.83,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Then a well written book
Dialogue: 0,1:11:55.87,1:11:59.18,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,putting forward perverted\Nmoral views may be\Na good book?
Dialogue: 0,1:11:59.22,1:12:01.53,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,A work\Nof art doesn't\Nput forward views.
Dialogue: 0,1:12:01.57,1:12:03.05,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Views are for people.
Dialogue: 0,1:12:03.10,1:12:05.62,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,A perverted novel\Nmight be a good book?
Dialogue: 0,1:12:05.66,1:12:08.01,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I don't know\Nwhat you mean by\Na perverted novel.
Dialogue: 0,1:12:08.06,1:12:10.19,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Then, I will suggest\NThe Picture of Dorian Gray
Dialogue: 0,1:12:10.23,1:12:13.32,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,as being open\Nto the interpretation\Nof being such a book.
Dialogue: 0,1:12:13.37,1:12:15.37,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Only to brutes and illiterates.
Dialogue: 0,1:12:15.41,1:12:19.72,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,The affection\Nand love of the artist\Nfor the youth, Dorian Gray,
Dialogue: 0,1:12:19.77,1:12:22.20,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,might lead\Nan ordinary individual
Dialogue: 0,1:12:22.25,1:12:25.60,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,to believe\Nthat it might have\Na certain tendency.
Dialogue: 0,1:12:25.64,1:12:28.51,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I have no knowledge\Nof the views of\Nordinary individuals.
Dialogue: 0,1:12:29.82,1:12:30.78,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Hmm.
Dialogue: 0,1:12:30.82,1:12:33.52,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I propose, if I may, to quote
Dialogue: 0,1:12:33.56,1:12:36.56,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,a few passages from this book.
Dialogue: 0,1:12:36.61,1:12:39.57,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,The artist Hallward is\Nspeaking to Dorian Gray.
Dialogue: 0,1:12:39.61,1:12:42.22,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,"It is quite true\Nthat I have worshiped you
Dialogue: 0,1:12:42.27,1:12:46.44,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,"with far more romance than\Na man usually gives to\Na friend.
Dialogue: 0,1:12:46.49,1:12:49.71,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,"I have never loved a woman.
Dialogue: 0,1:12:49.75,1:12:52.01,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,"From the moment I met you,
Dialogue: 0,1:12:52.06,1:12:55.32,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,"your personality had\Nthe most extraordinary\Ninfluence over me.
Dialogue: 0,1:12:55.37,1:13:02.11,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,"I quite admit I adored you\Nmadly, extravagantly,\Nabsurdly."
Dialogue: 0,1:13:02.16,1:13:04.07,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Do you mean to\Nsay that that passage
Dialogue: 0,1:13:04.11,1:13:07.81,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,describes the natural\Nfeeling of one man\Ntowards another?
Dialogue: 0,1:13:07.86,1:13:10.82,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Dorian Gray's was\Na remarkable personality.
Dialogue: 0,1:13:10.86,1:13:15.69,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,May I take it that you as\Nan artist have never known\Nthe feeling described here?
Dialogue: 0,1:13:15.73,1:13:18.43,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,No. It is a work of fiction.
Dialogue: 0,1:13:18.48,1:13:22.18,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Let us go over it\Nphrase by phrase.
Dialogue: 0,1:13:22.22,1:13:25.74,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,"I quite admit that I\Nhave adored you madly."
Dialogue: 0,1:13:25.79,1:13:29.27,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,What do you say to that?\NHave you ever adored\Na young man madly?
Dialogue: 0,1:13:29.31,1:13:31.66,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I've never given\Nadoration to anyone.
Dialogue: 0,1:13:31.71,1:13:33.06,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Except myself.
Dialogue: 0,1:13:36.23,1:13:38.89,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I suppose you think\Nthat a very smart thing?
Dialogue: 0,1:13:38.93,1:13:39.76,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Not at all.
Dialogue: 0,1:13:41.46,1:13:44.15,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,"I have adored\Nyou extravagantly."
Dialogue: 0,1:13:44.20,1:13:46.24,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Do you mean financially?
Dialogue: 0,1:13:46.29,1:13:48.72,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Oh, yes, financially!
Dialogue: 0,1:13:48.77,1:13:51.03,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Do you think that we\Nare talking about finance?
Dialogue: 0,1:13:51.07,1:13:52.60,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I don't know what\Nyou're talking about.
Dialogue: 0,1:13:52.64,1:13:54.43,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Don't you?
Dialogue: 0,1:13:54.47,1:13:56.69,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Then I hope that I shall\Nmake myself very plain\Nbefore I have done.
Dialogue: 0,1:13:59.65,1:14:04.00,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,And we come now\Nto the letter which you\Nwrote to Lord Alfred Douglas.
Dialogue: 0,1:14:05.35,1:14:08.74,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,It begins, "My own boy."
Dialogue: 0,1:14:08.79,1:14:12.57,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Now, why should\Na man of your age\Naddress a young boy
Dialogue: 0,1:14:12.62,1:14:16.40,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,nearly 20\Nyears younger\Nas "My own boy"?
Dialogue: 0,1:14:16.45,1:14:19.49,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I was fond of him.\NI've always been\Nfond of him.
Dialogue: 0,1:14:19.54,1:14:20.97,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Did you adore him?
Dialogue: 0,1:14:22.41,1:14:24.32,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,No, I like him.
Dialogue: 0,1:14:24.37,1:14:25.50,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,And that's not\Nan ordinary letter.
Dialogue: 0,1:14:25.54,1:14:27.11,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,You might as well\Ncross examine me
Dialogue: 0,1:14:27.15,1:14:29.59,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,as to whether a Shakespeare\Nsonnet was improper.
Dialogue: 0,1:14:29.63,1:14:33.03,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Suppose a man\Nwho was not an artist\Nhad written this letter.
Dialogue: 0,1:14:33.07,1:14:35.20,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Would you say that\Nthis was a proper letter?
Dialogue: 0,1:14:35.25,1:14:37.90,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,A man who was not an artist\Nwouldn't have written\Nthat letter.
Dialogue: 0,1:14:37.95,1:14:40.38,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Well, I can suggest, for\Nthe sake of your reputation,
Dialogue: 0,1:14:40.43,1:14:43.04,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,that there's nothing\Nvery wonderful in this.
Dialogue: 0,1:14:43.08,1:14:46.52,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,"Those red rose\Nleaf lips of yours..."
Dialogue: 0,1:14:46.56,1:14:48.52,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,It largely depends on\Nhow it's read.
Dialogue: 0,1:14:50.18,1:14:55.22,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,"Your slim guilt soul walks\Nbetween passion and poetry."
Dialogue: 0,1:14:58.05,1:15:00.71,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Is that\Na beautiful\Nphrase, Mr. Wilde?
Dialogue: 0,1:15:00.75,1:15:03.49,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Not as you\Nread it, Mr. Carson.\NYou read it very badly.
Dialogue: 0,1:15:05.19,1:15:07.89,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I do not profess\Nto be an artist,\NMr. Wilde.
Dialogue: 0,1:15:07.93,1:15:09.37,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,And when I hear\Nyou give evidence,
Dialogue: 0,1:15:09.41,1:15:11.20,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I'm very glad that I am not.
Dialogue: 0,1:15:11.24,1:15:14.33,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,My Lord, I don't think my\Nlearned friend should\Ntalk like that.
Dialogue: 0,1:15:14.37,1:15:15.98,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,May I suggest, Mr. Carson,
Dialogue: 0,1:15:16.03,1:15:19.99,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,that you do not air your\Npersonal opinions in\Nthis court?
Dialogue: 0,1:15:20.03,1:15:21.56,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,It is very difficult, My Lord.
Dialogue: 0,1:15:21.60,1:15:23.86,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,JUDGE: Yet nevertheless.
Dialogue: 0,1:15:23.91,1:15:28.48,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Where did you first meet\Nthe man Wood, Mr. Wilde?
Dialogue: 0,1:15:28.52,1:15:32.35,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,He came to my house.\NI think it was in\NJanuary of 1893.
Dialogue: 0,1:15:32.39,1:15:35.22,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,And on the same evening,\Nyou took him out to supper?
Dialogue: 0,1:15:35.87,1:15:37.40,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Yes.
Dialogue: 0,1:15:37.44,1:15:40.31,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Did you consider that\Nhe'd come to levy blackmail?
Dialogue: 0,1:15:40.36,1:15:42.58,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I did, and I was\Ndetermined to face it.
Dialogue: 0,1:15:42.62,1:15:45.88,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,By taking\Nhim out to supper\Nand giving him 拢40?
Dialogue: 0,1:15:45.93,1:15:48.15,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Well, I saw that\Nthe letter was\Nof no value,
Dialogue: 0,1:15:48.19,1:15:50.50,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,and I gave him\Nthe money after he\Ntold me a pitiful tale
Dialogue: 0,1:15:50.54,1:15:51.85,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,about being out of work.
Dialogue: 0,1:15:51.89,1:15:54.63,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I suggest that you\Nhad immoral relations
Dialogue: 0,1:15:54.68,1:15:56.42,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,with him first and\Nthen gave him the money.
Dialogue: 0,1:15:56.46,1:15:58.16,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,My Lord, I really must protest
Dialogue: 0,1:15:58.20,1:16:00.03,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,at my learned friend's\Nmethod of questioning\Nthe witness.
Dialogue: 0,1:16:00.07,1:16:03.42,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I do not see\Nthat Mr. Carson is\Nin any way out of order.
Dialogue: 0,1:16:06.69,1:16:07.82,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Thank you, My Lord.
Dialogue: 0,1:16:09.34,1:16:12.74,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Do you know a man named\NCharles Parker, Mr. Wilde?
Dialogue: 0,1:16:18.09,1:16:20.53,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,The witness will\Nanswer the question.
Dialogue: 0,1:16:22.31,1:16:24.97,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Yes, he was a friend\Nof Lord Alfred's.
Dialogue: 0,1:16:25.01,1:16:26.58,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,And a man named Atkin?
Dialogue: 0,1:16:28.01,1:16:29.67,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Yes, he was a friend\Nof Parker's.
Dialogue: 0,1:16:29.71,1:16:32.19,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,A man named Grainger?
Dialogue: 0,1:16:32.23,1:16:34.85,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Yes, he was\Na manservant\Nof Lord Alfred's.
Dialogue: 0,1:16:34.89,1:16:38.89,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,And Taylor, Mr. Wilde.\NDo you know anyone\Ncalled Taylor?
Dialogue: 0,1:16:38.94,1:16:41.64,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Yes, I have been to parties\Nat his house. We...
Dialogue: 0,1:16:41.68,1:16:46.60,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Were all these, with\Nthe exception of Taylor,\Nyoung men of about 20?
Dialogue: 0,1:16:46.64,1:16:49.38,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I like the society\Nof young men.
Dialogue: 0,1:16:49.43,1:16:51.78,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Have you given money\Nto any of them?
Dialogue: 0,1:16:52.91,1:16:54.21,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I may have.
Dialogue: 0,1:16:54.26,1:16:55.08,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Or presents?
Dialogue: 0,1:16:56.35,1:16:59.26,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,A silver cigarette case\Nfor Mr. Taylor,
Dialogue: 0,1:16:59.31,1:17:03.48,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,gold-topped walking\Nstick for Mr. Parker,
Dialogue: 0,1:17:03.53,1:17:08.27,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,a book for\NMr. Wood inscribed,\N"To Alfred from Oscar."
Dialogue: 0,1:17:11.06,1:17:13.58,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Did you know, Mr. Wilde,
Dialogue: 0,1:17:13.62,1:17:16.19,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,that Wood had been\Nunemployed for three years,
Dialogue: 0,1:17:16.24,1:17:20.54,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,that Parker was a valet,\Nand that the man Taylor\Nwas also out of work?
Dialogue: 0,1:17:20.59,1:17:22.68,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,That would\Nnot have affected my\Nfriendship with them.
Dialogue: 0,1:17:22.72,1:17:26.59,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,And yet you gave them presents\Nand entertained them to supper\Non diverse occasions.
Dialogue: 0,1:17:26.64,1:17:28.99,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,No doubt you drank\Nwine and champagne.
Dialogue: 0,1:17:29.03,1:17:31.25,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Iced champagne is\Na favorite drink\Nof mine,
Dialogue: 0,1:17:31.29,1:17:32.69,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,much against\Nmy doctor's orders.
Dialogue: 0,1:17:32.73,1:17:34.25,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Never mind\Nyour doctor's orders.
Dialogue: 0,1:17:34.30,1:17:35.17,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I never do.
Dialogue: 0,1:17:37.91,1:17:39.91,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,And at these supper parties
Dialogue: 0,1:17:39.95,1:17:42.30,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,your guests no doubt\Nhad plenty of champagne.
Dialogue: 0,1:17:42.35,1:17:43.52,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I didn't press them to drink.
Dialogue: 0,1:17:43.57,1:17:44.87,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,You did not stint them?
Dialogue: 0,1:17:44.92,1:17:47.14,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,What gentleman\Nwould stint his guests?
Dialogue: 0,1:17:47.18,1:17:50.70,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,What gentleman would stint\Nhis valet and a groom,\NMr. Wilde?
Dialogue: 0,1:17:50.75,1:17:53.62,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,My Lord, I really must protest\Nat my learned friend's\Nsneering remarks.
Dialogue: 0,1:17:53.66,1:17:58.23,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Mr. Carson, I suggest\Nyou confine yourself to\Nquestions, not opinions.
Dialogue: 0,1:17:59.37,1:18:00.67,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Very well, My Lord.
Dialogue: 0,1:18:04.54,1:18:07.07,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Did you know, Mr. Wilde,
Dialogue: 0,1:18:07.11,1:18:09.51,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,that Taylor, Atkin and Parker
Dialogue: 0,1:18:09.55,1:18:13.34,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,had been arrested in a raid\Non a house in Fitzroy Square?
Dialogue: 0,1:18:13.38,1:18:15.29,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Yes, I read about that.
Dialogue: 0,1:18:15.34,1:18:18.60,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,You know\Nthat they were charged\Nwith felonious practices?
Dialogue: 0,1:18:18.65,1:18:21.87,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I understand\Nthat the magistrate\Ndismissed the charge.
Dialogue: 0,1:18:21.91,1:18:24.87,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,About the young man Grainger.
Dialogue: 0,1:18:26.44,1:18:28.31,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Have you ever dined with him?
Dialogue: 0,1:18:28.35,1:18:29.18,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,No, never.
Dialogue: 0,1:18:30.18,1:18:32.09,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,But you know him?
Dialogue: 0,1:18:32.14,1:18:36.10,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Yes, he was a manservant\Nat Lord Alfred's house\Nin Oxford.
Dialogue: 0,1:18:36.14,1:18:37.88,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,So you saw him on\Nseveral occasions?
Dialogue: 0,1:18:37.93,1:18:39.88,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I stayed in the house\Non several occasions.
Dialogue: 0,1:18:39.93,1:18:40.97,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Grainger waited at table.
Dialogue: 0,1:18:43.02,1:18:46.54,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Did you ever kiss him,\NMr. Wilde?
Dialogue: 0,1:18:46.59,1:18:48.81,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Oh, dear, no.\NHe was extremely ugly.
Dialogue: 0,1:19:00.43,1:19:02.17,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Is that the reason\Nyou did not kiss him?
Dialogue: 0,1:19:03.34,1:19:04.95,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Mr. Carson,\Nyou are very insolent.
Dialogue: 0,1:19:05.00,1:19:07.09,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Did you say that\Nyou never kissed him?
Dialogue: 0,1:19:07.13,1:19:08.87,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,It's a foolish question.
Dialogue: 0,1:19:08.91,1:19:11.61,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Then why, sir,\Ndid you mention that\Nthis boy was extremely ugly?
Dialogue: 0,1:19:11.65,1:19:13.31,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I don't know\Nwhy I mentioned\Nthat he was ugly
Dialogue: 0,1:19:13.35,1:19:15.05,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,except that\Nyou stunned me with\Nyour insolent remark
Dialogue: 0,1:19:15.09,1:19:17.01,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,and the insulting way\Nyou've treated me\Nduring this hearing.
Dialogue: 0,1:19:17.05,1:19:19.10,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Why did you mention\Nhis ugliness?
Dialogue: 0,1:19:19.14,1:19:20.40,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,It was simply that I...
Dialogue: 0,1:19:20.45,1:19:21.84,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Why? Why? Why?
Dialogue: 0,1:19:21.88,1:19:24.10,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,"I didn't\Nkiss Grainger\Nbecause he was ugly."
Dialogue: 0,1:19:24.15,1:19:26.06,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Quite untrue...\NI protest, My Lord,\Nat his accusations.
Dialogue: 0,1:19:26.10,1:19:27.76,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,My learned friend\Nputs words into\Nthe witness' mouth.
Dialogue: 0,1:19:27.80,1:19:29.72,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,The witness\Nis putting words\Ninto his own mouth.
Dialogue: 0,1:19:29.76,1:19:31.98,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,-I object.\N-I will not have this\Nbrawling between counsels.
Dialogue: 0,1:19:32.02,1:19:33.94,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,If I may say so, My Lord,
Dialogue: 0,1:19:33.98,1:19:35.90,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,my learned friend has no right\Nto make suggestions of\Na certain behavior
Dialogue: 0,1:19:35.94,1:19:37.99,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,with a group of persons\Nnot represented in\Nthis court
Dialogue: 0,1:19:38.03,1:19:39.38,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,and whose evidence\Nwe have not heard.
Dialogue: 0,1:19:39.42,1:19:41.29,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,But you will hear it,\NSir Edward.
Dialogue: 0,1:19:41.34,1:19:43.69,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,It is my intention\Nto produce every one of\Nthe persons mentioned here
Dialogue: 0,1:19:43.73,1:19:46.21,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,just now in\Nthis courtroom\Ntomorrow morning.
Dialogue: 0,1:19:46.25,1:19:48.56,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Wood, Parker, Atkin,\NGrainger and Taylor
Dialogue: 0,1:19:48.60,1:19:51.39,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,will relate\Ntheir loathsome experiences\Nat the hands of the witness.
Dialogue: 0,1:19:51.43,1:19:54.05,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,By your own admission,\Na group of blackmailers\Nand police suspects, sir.
Dialogue: 0,1:19:54.09,1:19:56.31,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Nevertheless,\Nthey'll be here\Nto give their testimony,
Dialogue: 0,1:19:56.35,1:19:59.62,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,testimony that will prove my\Nclient's plea of justification
Dialogue: 0,1:19:59.66,1:20:01.57,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,beyond any possible shadow\Nof a doubt.
Dialogue: 0,1:20:02.88,1:20:04.58,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Silence in court.
Dialogue: 0,1:20:04.62,1:20:07.89,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I think this would be\Nan appropriate moment\Nto adjourn.
Dialogue: 0,1:20:07.93,1:20:09.54,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,The witness may stand down.
Dialogue: 0,1:20:15.20,1:20:18.33,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,The court\Nwill reconvene at\N10:00 a.m. tomorrow.
Dialogue: 0,1:20:19.64,1:20:21.29,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Be upstanding in court.
Dialogue: 0,1:20:22.81,1:20:25.47,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,All persons who have\Nanything further to do
Dialogue: 0,1:20:25.51,1:20:28.08,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,before My Lords,\Nthe Queen's justices\Nof oyer and terminer...
Dialogue: 0,1:20:34.91,1:20:37.00,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Before this unfortunate\Ntrial started,
Dialogue: 0,1:20:37.04,1:20:39.13,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,you gave me your word that\Nthere was no truth whatever
Dialogue: 0,1:20:39.18,1:20:41.44,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,in any of these\Ndreadful accusations.
Dialogue: 0,1:20:41.48,1:20:45.31,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I know, Sir Edward. It was\Nunforgivably stupid of me,
Dialogue: 0,1:20:45.36,1:20:48.40,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,but I was afraid you\Nwouldn't take the case.
Dialogue: 0,1:20:50.14,1:20:52.32,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,As it is,\Nyou realize you've\Nalready lost this case.
Dialogue: 0,1:20:53.41,1:20:55.15,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,But what is\Ninfinitely more serious
Dialogue: 0,1:20:55.19,1:20:57.76,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,is that when Carson\Nputs these young men\Ninto the witness box,
Dialogue: 0,1:20:57.80,1:21:00.20,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,as he obviously intends to do,
Dialogue: 0,1:21:00.24,1:21:03.20,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,their evidence\Nwill inevitably result\Nin your being arrested
Dialogue: 0,1:21:03.24,1:21:05.90,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,on some extremely\Ngrave charges.
Dialogue: 0,1:21:05.94,1:21:08.34,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Sir Edward,\Nmay I just say one thing?
Dialogue: 0,1:21:08.38,1:21:10.38,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Please do.
Dialogue: 0,1:21:10.43,1:21:14.21,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,The whole case started with my\Nfather accusing Mr. Wilde\Nof carrying on an...
Dialogue: 0,1:21:14.26,1:21:16.69,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,An immoral relationship\Nwith me, isn't that so?
Dialogue: 0,1:21:17.26,1:21:18.96,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Yes.
Dialogue: 0,1:21:19.00,1:21:20.65,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Then why in heaven's name\Ncan I not go into the\Nwitness box
Dialogue: 0,1:21:20.70,1:21:22.66,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,-and deny this\Ndisgusting accusation?\N-Bosie, for the last time.
Dialogue: 0,1:21:22.70,1:21:24.22,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,-But it isn't true, Oscar.\N-You know it isn't.
Dialogue: 0,1:21:24.27,1:21:25.83,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Such a denial\Nwould undoubtedly add
Dialogue: 0,1:21:25.88,1:21:27.92,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,considerable weight, Mr. Wilde.
Dialogue: 0,1:21:27.97,1:21:32.06,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,In my opinion, not to\Nput Lord Alfred into the\Nbox would be a grave mistake.
Dialogue: 0,1:21:32.10,1:21:34.28,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,One that\Nyou might regret for\Nthe rest of your life.
Dialogue: 0,1:21:36.32,1:21:39.72,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Gentlemen, I have infinite\Nfaith in the good sense\Nof the common man,
Dialogue: 0,1:21:39.76,1:21:41.37,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,and if,\Nas you say,\Nthis case hangs
Dialogue: 0,1:21:41.41,1:21:43.76,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,on the evidence\Nof paid informers
Dialogue: 0,1:21:43.81,1:21:45.68,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,and criminals\Nlike Wood and Parker,
Dialogue: 0,1:21:45.72,1:21:48.90,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I cannot conceive\Nthat a British jury would\Ntake their word before mine.
Dialogue: 0,1:21:50.07,1:21:51.34,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I wish I could\Nshare your faith.
Dialogue: 0,1:21:53.34,1:21:54.86,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Well, what must be must be.
Dialogue: 0,1:21:54.91,1:21:56.60,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,But I want\Nyou to understand\Nthat Lord Alfred is not
Dialogue: 0,1:21:56.65,1:21:57.78,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,to give evidence at this trial.
Dialogue: 0,1:21:59.13,1:22:01.04,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Very well.
Dialogue: 0,1:22:01.09,1:22:04.13,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Well, I shall endeavor to\Nsalvage what is left of\Nyour reputation
Dialogue: 0,1:22:04.18,1:22:07.40,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,by withdrawing\Nfrom the case first thing\Nin the morning.
Dialogue: 0,1:22:07.44,1:22:11.53,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Incidentally, there's no need\Nfor you to be present in\Ncourt tomorrow.
Dialogue: 0,1:22:11.57,1:22:13.92,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Indeed there's\Nno need for you to\Nbe present in this country.
Dialogue: 0,1:22:16.36,1:22:19.32,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,There is a boat train leaving\Nfor Calais at 10:00 tonight,\NMr. Wilde.
Dialogue: 0,1:22:20.76,1:22:21.93,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,You'd be well advised\Nto be on it.
Dialogue: 0,1:22:24.54,1:22:26.76,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Before you condemn\NLord Queensberry,
Dialogue: 0,1:22:26.81,1:22:29.85,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I ask you to\Nconsider whether the\Ngorge of any father ought
Dialogue: 0,1:22:29.90,1:22:32.16,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,not to rise in\Nsuch circumstances.
Dialogue: 0,1:22:32.20,1:22:34.99,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I ask you to\Nbear in mind that\NLord Queensberry's son
Dialogue: 0,1:22:35.03,1:22:39.38,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,was so dominated by Wilde\Nthat he threatened to\Nshoot his own father.
Dialogue: 0,1:22:39.43,1:22:43.21,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I now have\Na more painful part\Nof the case to approach.
Dialogue: 0,1:22:43.26,1:22:45.17,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,It's my unhappy duty\Nto bring before you\Nyoung men...
Dialogue: 0,1:22:45.22,1:22:48.00,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,-Did Wilde get away?\N-No.
Dialogue: 0,1:22:48.05,1:22:50.70,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,...to tell their\Nmiserable tales.
Dialogue: 0,1:22:50.74,1:22:53.09,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I first call Charles Parker.
Dialogue: 0,1:22:53.14,1:22:55.84,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,May I claim Your Lordship's\Nindulgence while I interpose
Dialogue: 0,1:22:55.88,1:22:57.62,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,to make a statement,\Nwhich is, of course,
Dialogue: 0,1:22:57.66,1:22:59.75,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,made under a feeling\Nof great responsibility?
Dialogue: 0,1:22:59.80,1:23:02.02,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,By all means, Sir Edward.
Dialogue: 0,1:23:02.06,1:23:03.02,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Forgive me, Mr. Carson.
Dialogue: 0,1:23:05.24,1:23:06.80,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I'm sure it must be\Napparent to Your Lordship
Dialogue: 0,1:23:06.85,1:23:09.63,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,that those\Nwho represent\NMr. Wilde in this case
Dialogue: 0,1:23:09.68,1:23:12.85,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,have before them\Na terrible anxiety.
Dialogue: 0,1:23:12.90,1:23:15.90,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,A verdict given in favor of\Nthe defendant Lord Queensberry
Dialogue: 0,1:23:15.94,1:23:20.34,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,might be interpreted\Nas conclusive proof as to\Nthe accusations of impropriety
Dialogue: 0,1:23:20.38,1:23:23.56,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,brought against the plaintiff,\NMr. Oscar Wilde
Dialogue: 0,1:23:23.60,1:23:25.56,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,and thus, we would be\Ngoing through,
Dialogue: 0,1:23:25.60,1:23:29.00,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,day after day,\Nan investigation of matters\Nof the most appalling nature.
Dialogue: 0,1:23:30.04,1:23:31.74,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Under these circumstances,
Dialogue: 0,1:23:31.78,1:23:34.22,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I feel I am\Nnot going beyond\Nthe bounds of my duty
Dialogue: 0,1:23:34.27,1:23:37.14,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,if I now interpose\Nand say on behalf\Nof Mr. Wilde
Dialogue: 0,1:23:37.18,1:23:39.92,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,that I would ask to\Nwithdraw from the prosecution.
Dialogue: 0,1:23:39.97,1:23:42.71,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,If that is your wish,\NSir Edward, so be it.
Dialogue: 0,1:23:42.75,1:23:43.97,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,COURT USHER: Silence.
Dialogue: 0,1:23:44.01,1:23:45.80,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,And if I may say so\Nin the circumstances,
Dialogue: 0,1:23:45.84,1:23:47.80,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I think you have\Nmade a wise decision.
Dialogue: 0,1:23:47.84,1:23:49.58,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Are you taking a cab?\NYes, come on.
Dialogue: 0,1:23:49.63,1:23:51.28,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Get this\Nto the office\Nas soon as you can.
Dialogue: 0,1:23:51.33,1:23:53.81,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,"Oscar Wilde\Nwithdraws from case."
Dialogue: 0,1:23:53.85,1:23:56.81,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,-Take a cab and hurry.\N-Yes, sir.
Dialogue: 0,1:23:56.85,1:24:02.29,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Either the words\Ncomplained of were\Njustified or they were not.
Dialogue: 0,1:24:02.34,1:24:06.08,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,If they were,\Nthen the statement,\N"posing as a sodomite"
Dialogue: 0,1:24:06.12,1:24:10.00,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,is true\Nand the publication\Nwas for the public benefit.
Dialogue: 0,1:24:10.04,1:24:12.30,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,You will now consider\Nyour verdict.
Dialogue: 0,1:24:17.61,1:24:19.83,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,We've already agreed\Nupon a verdict, My Lord.
Dialogue: 0,1:24:21.66,1:24:22.75,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,The prisoner will rise.
Dialogue: 0,1:24:27.14,1:24:28.58,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Gentlemen of the jury,\Ndo you find
Dialogue: 0,1:24:28.62,1:24:31.41,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,the plea\Nof justification\Nhas been proved or not?
Dialogue: 0,1:24:31.45,1:24:32.85,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,We do.
Dialogue: 0,1:24:32.89,1:24:35.59,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,And do you\Nfind the defendant\Nguilty or not guilty?
Dialogue: 0,1:24:35.63,1:24:36.98,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Not guilty, My Lord.
Dialogue: 0,1:24:38.50,1:24:41.68,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Silence in court!\NSilence! Silence!
Dialogue: 0,1:24:41.72,1:24:43.90,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Usher, silence the court.
Dialogue: 0,1:24:43.94,1:24:44.81,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Usher!
Dialogue: 0,1:24:46.60,1:24:48.25,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Well, they haven't\Nwasted any time.
Dialogue: 0,1:24:48.30,1:24:49.64,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Why, what do you mean?
Dialogue: 0,1:24:49.69,1:24:51.56,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,A copy\Nof the evidence\Nhas already been sent
Dialogue: 0,1:24:51.60,1:24:52.87,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,to the Director of\NPublic Prosecutions.
Dialogue: 0,1:25:03.75,1:25:07.18,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Bosie, for God's sake,\Nstop walking up and down.
Dialogue: 0,1:25:17.98,1:25:19.54,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Oh.
Dialogue: 0,1:25:19.59,1:25:21.63,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Oh, you haven't\Neaten a thing, sir.
Dialogue: 0,1:25:23.03,1:25:24.24,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I don't really want it.
Dialogue: 0,1:25:25.16,1:25:26.33,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Thank you, Arthur.
Dialogue: 0,1:25:35.52,1:25:38.39,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Oscar, I've just heard\Nfrom one of the reporters.
Dialogue: 0,1:25:38.43,1:25:39.96,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,There's a warrant\Nout for your arrest.
Dialogue: 0,1:25:42.44,1:25:43.96,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,What about Constance\Nand the children?
Dialogue: 0,1:25:45.22,1:25:47.05,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I saw them off\Non the train myself.
Dialogue: 0,1:25:49.05,1:25:49.88,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Thank you, Robbie.
Dialogue: 0,1:25:51.10,1:25:52.40,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Oscar, I beg of you.
Dialogue: 0,1:25:52.45,1:25:53.71,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,There's still time to\Ncatch the 10:00 train.
Dialogue: 0,1:25:53.75,1:25:54.88,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I have a cab waiting outside.
Dialogue: 0,1:25:54.93,1:25:57.02,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,You're wasting\Nyour time, Robbie.
Dialogue: 0,1:25:57.06,1:25:59.28,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I've been trying\Nfor the past two hours.
Dialogue: 0,1:25:59.32,1:26:01.54,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Oscar, will you\Nplease listen to me?
Dialogue: 0,1:26:01.59,1:26:03.37,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,-It's too late.-It's not too late, I tell you.
Dialogue: 0,1:26:03.41,1:26:05.33,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,-Look, it's 9:35.\N-Oh, Robbie, have a drink.
Dialogue: 0,1:26:05.37,1:26:06.77,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,In three hours\Nwe can be in France.
Dialogue: 0,1:26:06.81,1:26:08.29,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,You look as if you need it.
Dialogue: 0,1:26:32.09,1:26:34.36,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,-Mr. Wilde?\N-Yes.
Dialogue: 0,1:26:34.40,1:26:36.88,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,We're police officers.\NWe hold a warrant\Nfor your arrest.
Dialogue: 0,1:26:38.10,1:26:40.10,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Really?
Dialogue: 0,1:26:40.15,1:26:42.41,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I must ask\Nyou to accompany us\Nto the police station.
Dialogue: 0,1:26:54.55,1:26:57.03,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Bosie, do something for me.
Dialogue: 0,1:26:57.90,1:26:59.30,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Anything.
Dialogue: 0,1:26:59.34,1:27:01.39,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Leave the country.\NIf possible, tonight.
Dialogue: 0,1:27:02.78,1:27:04.69,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,-I can't desert you.\N-Bosie, please.
Dialogue: 0,1:27:09.00,1:27:10.22,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Very well.
Dialogue: 0,1:27:12.05,1:27:13.79,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,So it's goodbye, hmm?
Dialogue: 0,1:27:13.83,1:27:15.92,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,-Oscar, I can't believe...\N-Goodbye.
Dialogue: 0,1:27:15.96,1:27:17.40,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,We'll come with you.
Dialogue: 0,1:27:17.44,1:27:19.49,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,-There'll be no need\Nfor that, sir.\N-Thank you.
Dialogue: 0,1:27:47.39,1:27:49.08,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Why do you look\Nat me like that?
Dialogue: 0,1:27:49.91,1:27:51.30,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,It's not my fault.
Dialogue: 0,1:27:51.35,1:27:53.44,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I loved him just as much\Nas you did.
Dialogue: 0,1:27:53.48,1:27:55.27,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Don't you think if there\Nwas anything I could have...
Dialogue: 0,1:27:55.31,1:27:56.53,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,You can do as\NOscar says, Bosie.
Dialogue: 0,1:27:58.70,1:27:59.79,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Leave the country.
Dialogue: 0,1:28:04.62,1:28:06.01,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,And the sooner the better,\NI should say.
Dialogue: 0,1:28:36.18,1:28:37.83,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,"Lord Queensberry\Nis triumphant.
Dialogue: 0,1:28:37.87,1:28:40.40,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,"Mr. Oscar Wilde is\Ndamned and done forever."
Dialogue: 0,1:28:40.44,1:28:41.88,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,And about time.
Dialogue: 0,1:28:41.92,1:28:43.66,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,-"Public morality\Nwill be vindicated."\N-Hear, hear.
Dialogue: 0,1:28:43.70,1:28:47.62,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,"And this evil in our midst\Nwill, I hope, be removed\Nforever."
Dialogue: 0,1:28:47.67,1:28:49.93,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Damn good thing, too.\NI never liked\Nthe fellow from the first.
Dialogue: 0,1:28:49.97,1:28:53.19,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Couldn't stand his plays.\NLot of immoral rubbish.
Dialogue: 0,1:28:53.24,1:28:55.33,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Damn it all, Bentley,\Nthe fellow\Nhasn't been tried yet.
Dialogue: 0,1:28:55.37,1:28:57.46,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Innocent until proved\Nguilty and all that\Nsort of...
Dialogue: 0,1:28:57.50,1:28:58.98,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,If he'd been in\Nmy regiment, sir,
Dialogue: 0,1:28:59.02,1:29:01.11,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,he'd have been lashed to\Na gun carriage and flogged.
Dialogue: 0,1:29:01.16,1:29:03.59,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,These artistic chaps\Nare all the same.
Dialogue: 0,1:29:03.64,1:29:05.47,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,A lot of long-haired\Ndegenerates.
Dialogue: 0,1:29:05.51,1:29:07.95,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I think you fellows are\Ntaking the whole damn\Nthing too seriously.
Dialogue: 0,1:29:07.99,1:29:09.69,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Live and let live,\Nthat's what I say.
Dialogue: 0,1:29:09.73,1:29:11.56,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Anyway, I don't care\Nwhat they do
Dialogue: 0,1:29:11.60,1:29:13.56,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,as long as they don't do it\Nin the street and frighten\Nthe horses.
Dialogue: 0,1:29:27.57,1:29:29.10,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,All right.
Dialogue: 0,1:29:35.32,1:29:37.06,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Do you want me to\Nburn them, Mr. Brace?
Dialogue: 0,1:29:37.11,1:29:40.11,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Good heavens, no.\NFellow might get off.
Dialogue: 0,1:29:58.43,1:29:59.39,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Mr. Humphries.
Dialogue: 0,1:30:00.39,1:30:01.57,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Sir Edward.
Dialogue: 0,1:30:01.61,1:30:04.83,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I... They didn't\Ntell me that it was you.
Dialogue: 0,1:30:07.05,1:30:08.05,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Mr. Wilde.
Dialogue: 0,1:30:10.49,1:30:14.71,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I don't know what\Narrangements you've\Nmade about your defense,
Dialogue: 0,1:30:16.45,1:30:18.10,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,but if you wish it,
Dialogue: 0,1:30:18.15,1:30:20.85,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Sir Edward and I\Nwould be most happy\Nto act on your behalf.
Dialogue: 0,1:30:22.50,1:30:24.94,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Thank you, I'm...\NI'm very grateful.
Dialogue: 0,1:30:24.98,1:30:27.37,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,There are certain legal\Naspects of this case,\NMr. Wilde,
Dialogue: 0,1:30:27.42,1:30:29.29,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,that have shocked me greatly.
Dialogue: 0,1:30:29.33,1:30:32.16,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,The prosecution\Nhas based its entire case\Non the evidence of witnesses
Dialogue: 0,1:30:32.20,1:30:38.69,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,who admitted crimes ranging\Nfrom assault, petty larceny\Nto blackmail.
Dialogue: 0,1:30:38.73,1:30:41.78,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Yet the Crown has\Nno intention of prosecuting\Nany of these witnesses.
Dialogue: 0,1:30:41.82,1:30:43.26,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,They are to go scot-free.
Dialogue: 0,1:30:44.56,1:30:46.48,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Such a state\Nof affairs has\Nprofoundly shaken
Dialogue: 0,1:30:46.52,1:30:49.09,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,my inherent faith\Nin British justice.
Dialogue: 0,1:30:49.13,1:30:51.66,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,In these circumstances,\NI would consider it an honor,
Dialogue: 0,1:30:51.70,1:30:53.49,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,if you'll permit me\Nto offer my services.
Dialogue: 0,1:30:55.14,1:30:57.06,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Thank you.
Dialogue: 0,1:30:57.10,1:31:00.23,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I'm afraid the cost\Nof the other case\Nis still unpaid,
Dialogue: 0,1:31:00.28,1:31:01.45,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,and I'm in considerable debt.
Dialogue: 0,1:31:04.19,1:31:05.93,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Mr. Wilde,
Dialogue: 0,1:31:05.98,1:31:09.11,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Sir Edward and I are\Nagreed that there is\Nno question of a fee.
Dialogue: 0,1:31:11.20,1:31:12.03,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Thank you.
Dialogue: 0,1:31:13.38,1:31:14.94,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Thank you.
Dialogue: 0,1:31:14.99,1:31:17.34,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Well, there are many matters\Nwe should discuss, Mr. Wilde.
Dialogue: 0,1:31:22.21,1:31:26.17,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,CLERK: Put up Oscar\NFingal O'Flahertie\NWills Wilde.
Dialogue: 0,1:31:26.21,1:31:28.83,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Oscar Fingal O'Flahertie\NWills Wilde.
Dialogue: 0,1:31:32.18,1:31:34.92,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,COURT USHER:\NSilence in court. Silence!\NJUDGE: Order. Order.
Dialogue: 0,1:31:37.79,1:31:40.88,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,CLERK:\NAre you Oscar Fingal\NO'Flahertie Wills Wilde?
Dialogue: 0,1:31:40.93,1:31:42.10,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I am.
Dialogue: 0,1:31:42.14,1:31:43.93,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Oscar Fingal O'Flahertie\NWills Wilde,
Dialogue: 0,1:31:43.97,1:31:46.97,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,you stand charged on 25 counts.
Dialogue: 0,1:31:48.89,1:31:52.59,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,On the first count,\Nthe jurors for Our Lady,\Nthe Queen, upon their oath
Dialogue: 0,1:31:52.63,1:31:56.29,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,present that Oscar Fingal\NO'Flahertie Wills Wilde,
Dialogue: 0,1:31:56.33,1:32:00.73,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,on 14th day of March in\Nthe year of Our Lord 1893,
Dialogue: 0,1:32:00.77,1:32:03.73,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,in the County of London\Nand within the jurisdiction\Nof this court,
Dialogue: 0,1:32:03.77,1:32:08.43,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,being a male person,\Nunlawfully did commit\Nacts of gross indecency
Dialogue: 0,1:32:08.47,1:32:12.74,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,with another male person,\None Alfred Wood.
Dialogue: 0,1:32:12.78,1:32:16.57,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,And against the form of the\Nstatuette in such case\Nmade and provided,
Dialogue: 0,1:32:16.61,1:32:18.66,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,and against the peace\Nof Our Lady the Queen,
Dialogue: 0,1:32:18.70,1:32:20.01,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,her crown and dignity.
Dialogue: 0,1:32:21.88,1:32:25.54,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,On the second count,\Nthe juries aforesaid...
Dialogue: 0,1:32:25.58,1:32:29.84,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,...against the form of the\Nstatute in such case\Nmade and provided
Dialogue: 0,1:32:29.89,1:32:34.72,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,and against the peace of\Nour said Lady the Queen,\Nher crown and dignity.
Dialogue: 0,1:32:36.63,1:32:40.59,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Oscar Fingal O'Flahertie\NWills Wilde,
Dialogue: 0,1:32:40.64,1:32:43.73,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,on the aforesaid indictments,\Nhow do you plead?
Dialogue: 0,1:32:43.77,1:32:45.21,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Guilty or not guilty?
Dialogue: 0,1:32:47.08,1:32:48.08,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Not guilty.
Dialogue: 0,1:32:50.43,1:32:53.74,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,My Lord, gentlemen of the jury,
Dialogue: 0,1:32:53.78,1:32:58.26,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,the first nine counts\Nin the indictment refer\Nto the prisoner's misconduct
Dialogue: 0,1:32:58.31,1:33:01.53,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,with a young man\Nnamed Alfred Wood.
Dialogue: 0,1:33:01.57,1:33:03.96,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,The next three\Nto Frederick Atkin.
Dialogue: 0,1:33:04.01,1:33:07.88,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Two to the man Taylor.\NThree to Charles Parker.
Dialogue: 0,1:33:07.93,1:33:11.54,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,And the last\Nto Wilde's conduct\Nwith a lad named Shelley.
Dialogue: 0,1:33:11.58,1:33:14.37,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,It will\Nbe shown that Wilde\Nsystematically endeavored
Dialogue: 0,1:33:14.41,1:33:17.59,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,to influence these young\Nmen's minds towards\Nvicious causes.
Dialogue: 0,1:33:17.63,1:33:20.94,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,And to mold them to\Nhis own depraved will.
Dialogue: 0,1:33:20.98,1:33:24.46,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Gentlemen of the jury,\Nwhen you have heard the\Nevidence of these men,
Dialogue: 0,1:33:24.51,1:33:27.07,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I assure you that\Nyou will be justified
Dialogue: 0,1:33:27.12,1:33:29.42,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,in finding the prisoner\Nguilty on all counts.
Dialogue: 0,1:33:29.47,1:33:31.17,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I call first Alfred Wood.
Dialogue: 0,1:33:33.52,1:33:35.56,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,COURT USHER: Call Alfred Wood.
Dialogue: 0,1:33:35.61,1:33:36.87,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Alfred Wood.
Dialogue: 0,1:33:48.92,1:33:52.10,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Take the Bible\Nin your right hand\Nand read from the card.
Dialogue: 0,1:33:52.14,1:33:55.23,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,"I swear by Almighty God\Nthat the evidence I give\Nto this court
Dialogue: 0,1:33:55.28,1:33:58.45,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,"shall be the truth,\Nthe whole truth and\Nnothing but the truth,
Dialogue: 0,1:33:59.37,1:34:00.46,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,"so help me, God."
Dialogue: 0,1:34:06.46,1:34:09.60,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,In all my years at the bar,\NI cannot remember coming\Nface to face
Dialogue: 0,1:34:09.64,1:34:12.29,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,with such a miserable\Ncollection of witnesses.
Dialogue: 0,1:34:13.64,1:34:16.99,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Wood, Parker, Atkin.
Dialogue: 0,1:34:18.82,1:34:20.35,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,The prosecution\Nmust have scraped
Dialogue: 0,1:34:20.39,1:34:23.04,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,the bottom of the barrel\Nto get that lot together.
Dialogue: 0,1:34:23.09,1:34:26.53,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,What I cannot understand\Nis how a man of Wilde's\Ntaste and breeding
Dialogue: 0,1:34:26.57,1:34:28.27,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,can come to associate\Nwith such people.
Dialogue: 0,1:34:28.31,1:34:29.96,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Well, to understand that,\NCharles,
Dialogue: 0,1:34:30.01,1:34:31.62,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,you'd have to understand the\Nnature of Wilde's perversion.
Dialogue: 0,1:34:31.66,1:34:33.84,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,And I'm a lawyer, not a doctor.
Dialogue: 0,1:34:33.88,1:34:37.14,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,To me, it's loathsome,\Ndegenerate and unnatural.
Dialogue: 0,1:34:38.41,1:34:40.93,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Yet I feel so sorry for him.
Dialogue: 0,1:34:40.97,1:34:44.89,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,It is a terrible thing,\NCharles, when a man of\NWilde's talents and genius
Dialogue: 0,1:34:44.94,1:34:48.98,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,is slowly crucified by\Na lot of blackmailers\Nand common criminals.
Dialogue: 0,1:34:51.90,1:34:54.73,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,There's very little hope\Nfor an acquittal, is there?
Dialogue: 0,1:34:54.77,1:34:58.34,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Well, the case\Nhas already been judged\Nby the press and the public.
Dialogue: 0,1:34:58.38,1:35:01.47,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,As far as\Nthey're concerned,\NWilde is guilty.
Dialogue: 0,1:35:01.52,1:35:04.91,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,It only remains for him\Nto be sentenced.
Dialogue: 0,1:35:04.96,1:35:11.00,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,The most we can hope for is\Nthat, out of this hysteria\Nof prejudice and hatred,
Dialogue: 0,1:35:11.05,1:35:15.84,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,there might shine\Na glimmer of Christian\Ncharity and forgiveness.
Dialogue: 0,1:35:15.88,1:35:17.97,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Do I understand\Nyou to say then,\NMr. Wilde,
Dialogue: 0,1:35:18.01,1:35:20.71,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,that there is no\Ntruth whatsoever in the\Nevidence of Alfred Wood?
Dialogue: 0,1:35:21.93,1:35:23.71,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,It's true\Nthat we had\Nsupper together,
Dialogue: 0,1:35:23.76,1:35:26.67,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,but the accusations of\Nimpropriety are quite untrue.
Dialogue: 0,1:35:26.72,1:35:29.63,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Charles Parker,\Nwhat part of his\Nevidence is untrue?
Dialogue: 0,1:35:31.24,1:35:33.03,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,He never came\Nto the hotel with me.
Dialogue: 0,1:35:33.07,1:35:35.07,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,He never had dinner with me\Nand he never came to my room.
Dialogue: 0,1:35:36.73,1:35:40.86,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,We had tea\Nat the St. James's once,\Nbut all of the rest...
Dialogue: 0,1:35:40.90,1:35:42.60,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Is untrue.
Dialogue: 0,1:35:42.64,1:35:45.47,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Then, Atkin.\NWhat of his evidence?
Dialogue: 0,1:35:45.52,1:35:47.61,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,My Lord,\Nmy learned friend\Nseems to have forgotten
Dialogue: 0,1:35:47.65,1:35:49.78,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,that the witness Atkin\Nperjured himself in\Nthe box.
Dialogue: 0,1:35:49.83,1:35:52.31,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Your Lordship dismissed\Nthis witness for that reason.
Dialogue: 0,1:35:52.35,1:35:55.35,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,The witness's evidence was\Nnot struck from the record,\NSir Edward.
Dialogue: 0,1:35:55.40,1:35:57.88,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,In my humble submission,\NMy Lord, it should have been.
Dialogue: 0,1:35:57.92,1:35:59.44,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,That is for me to decide.
Dialogue: 0,1:36:02.45,1:36:03.88,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,As Your Lordship pleases.
Dialogue: 0,1:36:05.41,1:36:08.76,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,What of Atkins'\Nevidence, Mr. Wilde?
Dialogue: 0,1:36:08.80,1:36:11.54,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,The accusations of indecency\Nare quite untrue.
Dialogue: 0,1:36:11.59,1:36:15.77,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,In fact,\Nthese witnesses,\Naccording to you,
Dialogue: 0,1:36:15.81,1:36:17.77,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,have lied throughout the trial.
Dialogue: 0,1:36:17.81,1:36:19.16,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,With remarkable ease.
Dialogue: 0,1:36:19.20,1:36:21.12,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,As an experienced\Nwriter and storyteller,
Dialogue: 0,1:36:21.16,1:36:23.82,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I'm lost in admiration\Nof their inventiveness.
Dialogue: 0,1:36:25.86,1:36:29.95,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,You seem also to have been\Nlost in admiration for\Ntheir youth, sir.
Dialogue: 0,1:36:30.00,1:36:31.52,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I'm a lover of youth.
Dialogue: 0,1:36:36.61,1:36:39.96,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Yes, we have gathered that.
Dialogue: 0,1:36:40.01,1:36:43.84,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Now, let us turn to this\Npublication, The Chameleon.
Dialogue: 0,1:36:43.88,1:36:46.27,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,My Lord,\Nare we to be subjected\Nto a further discourse
Dialogue: 0,1:36:46.32,1:36:48.97,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,on the\Nliterary morals\Nof the defendant?
Dialogue: 0,1:36:49.02,1:36:51.80,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I understood from\Nmy learned friend that\Nhe's going to confine himself
Dialogue: 0,1:36:51.84,1:36:53.85,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,to the specific charges\Nmade in the indictment.
Dialogue: 0,1:36:53.89,1:36:56.85,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,This is\Ncross examination\Nas to credit, My Lord.
Dialogue: 0,1:36:56.89,1:37:00.24,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I feel obliged to say that\Nquestions which learned\Ncounsel thinks
Dialogue: 0,1:37:00.29,1:37:02.38,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,should go to credit,\Nhe is entitled to put.
Dialogue: 0,1:37:08.34,1:37:11.04,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I shall not keep you long,\NMr. Wilde.
Dialogue: 0,1:37:11.08,1:37:13.30,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I trust not, Mr. Gill.
Dialogue: 0,1:37:13.34,1:37:15.78,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,In this magazine, to\Nwhich you made a contribution,
Dialogue: 0,1:37:15.83,1:37:18.57,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,there appears a poem\Nby Lord Alfred Douglas
Dialogue: 0,1:37:18.61,1:37:21.48,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,entitled Two Loves.
Dialogue: 0,1:37:22.31,1:37:24.18,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,It contains these lines.
Dialogue: 0,1:37:25.44,1:37:27.49,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,"Sweet youth,
Dialogue: 0,1:37:27.53,1:37:29.84,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,"tell me why, sad and sighing,
Dialogue: 0,1:37:29.88,1:37:32.75,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,"does thou rove\Nthese pleasant realms?
Dialogue: 0,1:37:32.80,1:37:36.02,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,"I pray,\Ntell me sooth.\NWhat is thy name?
Dialogue: 0,1:37:37.24,1:37:40.41,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,"He said, 'My name is Love.'
Dialogue: 0,1:37:40.46,1:37:43.20,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,"Then straight\Nthe first did\Nturn himself to me
Dialogue: 0,1:37:43.24,1:37:47.07,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,"and cried, 'He lieth,\Nfor his name is Shame.
Dialogue: 0,1:37:47.12,1:37:50.90,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,"'But I am Love, and I was to\Nbe alone in this fair garden,
Dialogue: 0,1:37:50.95,1:37:53.30,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,"'till he came\Nunasked by night.
Dialogue: 0,1:37:53.95,1:37:55.95,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,"'I am true Love.
Dialogue: 0,1:37:56.00,1:37:59.48,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,"'I fill the hearts of boy\Nand girl with mutual flame.'
Dialogue: 0,1:38:00.70,1:38:02.96,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,"Then, sighing, said the other,
Dialogue: 0,1:38:03.61,1:38:05.66,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,"'Have thy will,
Dialogue: 0,1:38:05.70,1:38:10.40,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,"'I am the love that\Ndare not speak its name.'"
Dialogue: 0,1:38:13.32,1:38:20.19,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,And what, Mr. Wilde,\Nis the love that dare\Nnot speak its name?
Dialogue: 0,1:38:23.98,1:38:27.94,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,The love\Nthat dare not speak\Nits name, in this century,
Dialogue: 0,1:38:27.98,1:38:31.60,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,is such a great affection\Nof an elder for a younger man.
Dialogue: 0,1:38:31.64,1:38:34.73,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,As there was between\NDavid and Jonathan.
Dialogue: 0,1:38:34.77,1:38:37.43,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Such as Plato made\Nthe very basis of philosophy
Dialogue: 0,1:38:37.47,1:38:40.91,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,and such as you will find in\Nthe sonnets of Michelangelo\Nand Shakespeare.
Dialogue: 0,1:38:42.39,1:38:46.87,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,It is a deep,\Nspiritual affection
Dialogue: 0,1:38:46.92,1:38:49.22,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,that is as perfect\Nas it is pure.
Dialogue: 0,1:38:50.92,1:38:54.53,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,It is in this\Ncentury misunderstood,\Nso much misunderstood
Dialogue: 0,1:38:54.58,1:39:00.23,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,that it may\Nbe called the love that\Ndare not speak its name.
Dialogue: 0,1:39:00.28,1:39:03.24,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,And on account of it,\NI'm placed where I\Nam today.
Dialogue: 0,1:39:04.80,1:39:06.24,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,But it is beautiful,
Dialogue: 0,1:39:06.89,1:39:09.07,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,it is fine,
Dialogue: 0,1:39:09.11,1:39:11.64,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,it is the noblest\Nform of affection.
Dialogue: 0,1:39:11.68,1:39:13.77,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,There is nothing\Nunnatural about it.
Dialogue: 0,1:39:14.77,1:39:16.60,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,It is intellectual.
Dialogue: 0,1:39:16.64,1:39:20.65,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,And is repeatedly to be\Nfound between an elder\Nand a younger man
Dialogue: 0,1:39:20.69,1:39:25.74,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,when the elder man has\Nintellect and the younger\Nman has all the hope and joy
Dialogue: 0,1:39:25.78,1:39:27.91,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,and glamour of life before him.
Dialogue: 0,1:39:30.31,1:39:32.83,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,But it is so the world\Ndoes not understand.
Dialogue: 0,1:39:34.14,1:39:36.57,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,The world mocks at it.
Dialogue: 0,1:39:36.62,1:39:39.14,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,And sometimes puts\None in the pillory\Nfor it.
Dialogue: 0,1:39:45.28,1:39:46.71,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,COURT USHER: Silence in court.
Dialogue: 0,1:39:46.76,1:39:47.72,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Rubbish!
Dialogue: 0,1:39:47.76,1:39:50.85,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Silence in court!\NSit down, sir!
Dialogue: 0,1:39:50.89,1:39:55.03,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,If there is the\Nslightest manifestation\Nof feeling like this again,
Dialogue: 0,1:39:55.07,1:39:57.29,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I shall have the court cleared.
Dialogue: 0,1:39:57.33,1:40:00.47,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I have no further\Nquestions, My Lord.
Dialogue: 0,1:40:00.51,1:40:02.08,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,JUDGE:\NThe witness\Nmay stand down.
Dialogue: 0,1:40:08.04,1:40:10.43,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,That concludes the case\Nfor the prosecution,\NMy Lord.
Dialogue: 0,1:40:23.06,1:40:27.41,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,May it\Nplease you, My Lord,\Ngentlemen of the jury,
Dialogue: 0,1:40:27.45,1:40:31.85,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,this is a serious\Nand grave question\Nfor you to decide.
Dialogue: 0,1:40:31.89,1:40:34.28,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,And yours is a position\Nof great responsibility.
Dialogue: 0,1:40:36.16,1:40:39.12,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Now, a great deal of\Npublic feeling has been\Nexcited against Mr. Wilde
Dialogue: 0,1:40:39.16,1:40:42.25,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,by the\Nquotation of passages\Nof poetry and literature
Dialogue: 0,1:40:42.29,1:40:46.04,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,and in particular\Nfrom Mr. Wilde's book,\NThe Picture of Dorian Gray.
Dialogue: 0,1:40:46.08,1:40:48.12,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Now I ask you,\Nmembers of the jury,
Dialogue: 0,1:40:48.17,1:40:52.43,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,is an author to be judged on\Nthe morals of the characters\Nof his book?
Dialogue: 0,1:40:52.48,1:40:55.61,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Was Stevenson accused of\Nbeing a lustful and\Ndepraved monster
Dialogue: 0,1:40:55.65,1:40:58.74,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,because he wrote\NDr. Jekyll and Mr. Hyde?
Dialogue: 0,1:40:58.79,1:41:03.40,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,As to the affection which\NMr. Wilde expressed in\Nhis letters,
Dialogue: 0,1:41:03.44,1:41:06.45,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,he himself\Nhas described it as\Npure, true affection,
Dialogue: 0,1:41:06.49,1:41:09.41,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,absolutely unconnected with\Nand completely alien to the
Dialogue: 0,1:41:09.45,1:41:12.10,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,filthy practices\Ndescribed in this court
Dialogue: 0,1:41:12.15,1:41:14.67,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,by the prosecution's\Nband of criminals.
Dialogue: 0,1:41:16.46,1:41:19.16,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Mr. Wilde is not\Nan ordinary man.
Dialogue: 0,1:41:19.20,1:41:22.33,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,He is a man\Nwho has written\Npoetry and prose,
Dialogue: 0,1:41:22.38,1:41:25.90,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,brilliant dramas,\Ncharming essays.
Dialogue: 0,1:41:25.94,1:41:28.69,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,He writes letters in\Na tone which to most\Nof us may appear
Dialogue: 0,1:41:28.73,1:41:34.47,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,high-flown, inflated,\Nexaggerated, even absurd.
Dialogue: 0,1:41:34.52,1:41:38.48,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,But he's not ashamed\Nor afraid to produce\Nthose letters.
Dialogue: 0,1:41:38.52,1:41:41.57,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,When a man comes forward\Nwith letters such as\Nthese and says,
Dialogue: 0,1:41:41.61,1:41:44.66,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,"I do not shrink\Nfrom the judgment of the\Nworld upon these productions,"
Dialogue: 0,1:41:44.70,1:41:48.92,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,has he not given the\Nbest proof of his innocence?
Dialogue: 0,1:41:48.97,1:41:51.75,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Innocence,\Ngentlemen of the jury,\Nhas courage and faith
Dialogue: 0,1:41:51.80,1:41:53.89,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,in the ultimate\Njudgment of mankind.
Dialogue: 0,1:41:56.02,1:42:00.41,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,As to the evidence\Nof the youths,\NParker, Atkin, Wood
Dialogue: 0,1:42:00.46,1:42:03.29,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,and their associates,
Dialogue: 0,1:42:03.33,1:42:06.51,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I respectfully submit that\Nno jury can find a man guilty
Dialogue: 0,1:42:06.55,1:42:09.21,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,on their tainted evidence.
Dialogue: 0,1:42:09.25,1:42:12.08,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,It deepens\None's horror to think\Nthe prisoner's freedom
Dialogue: 0,1:42:12.12,1:42:13.86,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,is at the peril\Nof such persons.
Dialogue: 0,1:42:16.56,1:42:19.22,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Before you consider\Nthis case, therefore,
Dialogue: 0,1:42:19.26,1:42:24.00,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I implore you to\Nlet your judgment only be\Naffected by those witnesses
Dialogue: 0,1:42:24.05,1:42:27.01,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,of whom you,\Nas true and honorable men
Dialogue: 0,1:42:27.05,1:42:29.14,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,can say, with a clear\Nconscience have given
Dialogue: 0,1:42:29.18,1:42:33.40,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,true, honest and\Nhonorable testimony.
Dialogue: 0,1:42:33.45,1:42:36.80,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,And if, upon the examination\Nof the evidence, you find\Nit your duty to say
Dialogue: 0,1:42:36.84,1:42:40.11,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,that the charges\Nagainst the prisoner\Nhave not been proved,
Dialogue: 0,1:42:40.15,1:42:43.20,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I know you'll be glad\Nthat that bright reputation,
Dialogue: 0,1:42:43.24,1:42:46.29,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,so nearly quenched\Nin a torrent of prejudice,
Dialogue: 0,1:42:46.33,1:42:51.16,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,will have been saved by\Nyour verdict from\Nabsolute ruin.
Dialogue: 0,1:42:51.20,1:42:54.82,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,And that\Nit will leave Mr. Wilde,a distinguished man of letters,
Dialogue: 0,1:42:54.86,1:42:57.38,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,to live a life\Nof honor and repute
Dialogue: 0,1:42:57.43,1:43:01.21,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,and to give, in the\Nmaturity of his genius,\Ngifts to our literature
Dialogue: 0,1:43:01.26,1:43:04.17,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,of which, already,\Nhe has shown such\Nbrilliant promise.
Dialogue: 0,1:44:34.05,1:44:36.09,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,COURT USHER: Be\Nupstanding in court.
Dialogue: 0,1:44:48.71,1:44:53.11,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Gentlemen of the jury,\NI understand that you are\Nunable to arrive at a verdict.
Dialogue: 0,1:44:53.15,1:44:54.81,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,That is so, My Lord.
Dialogue: 0,1:44:54.85,1:44:57.24,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Is there any prospect\Nthat if you retired
Dialogue: 0,1:44:57.29,1:44:59.59,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,and continued your\Ndeliberations a little longer,
Dialogue: 0,1:44:59.64,1:45:01.73,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,you'll be able to\Ncome to some agreement?
Dialogue: 0,1:45:01.77,1:45:04.34,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,We have considered\Nthe question\Nfor three hours, My Lord.
Dialogue: 0,1:45:04.38,1:45:07.64,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,And the only\Nresult we have come to\Nis that we cannot agree.
Dialogue: 0,1:45:07.69,1:45:11.43,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Yes, I have no doubt\Nthat you have tried\Nvery hard
Dialogue: 0,1:45:11.47,1:45:14.43,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,to come\Nto some agreement,\Nbut on the other hand,
Dialogue: 0,1:45:14.48,1:45:18.05,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,the inconveniences\Nof another trial\Nare very great.
Dialogue: 0,1:45:18.09,1:45:21.01,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,My Lord, I fear there is\Nno chance of an agreement.
Dialogue: 0,1:45:21.05,1:45:23.70,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,JUDGE:\NThen, gentlemen,\Nyou are discharged.
Dialogue: 0,1:45:23.75,1:45:25.10,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,FOREMAN: Thank you, My Lord.
Dialogue: 0,1:45:25.14,1:45:27.49,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,My Lord, on the\Nquestion of bail,
Dialogue: 0,1:45:27.53,1:45:29.71,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,it may be some weeks\Nbefore a retrial...
Dialogue: 0,1:45:32.41,1:45:38.63,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Retrial!\NRetrial! Retrial! Retrial!\NRetrial! Retrial! Retrial!
Dialogue: 0,1:45:48.42,1:45:50.30,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Hello, Robbie.
Dialogue: 0,1:45:50.34,1:45:52.99,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Mr. Wilde, we managed\Nto raise bail.
Dialogue: 0,1:45:53.04,1:45:55.47,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Come on, Oscar.\NLet me take you home.
Dialogue: 0,1:45:55.52,1:45:57.17,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Who put up the money\Nfor my bail?
Dialogue: 0,1:45:57.22,1:45:59.83,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Bosie's brother Percy\Nput up most of the money.
Dialogue: 0,1:45:59.87,1:46:01.87,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Percy? How kind.
Dialogue: 0,1:46:01.92,1:46:04.09,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,The rest was put up\Nby the Reverend Headlam.
Dialogue: 0,1:46:04.14,1:46:05.96,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,拢5,000 in all.
Dialogue: 0,1:46:06.01,1:46:09.40,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,It's preposterous.\NA common felon would not\Nbe so heavily penalized.
Dialogue: 0,1:46:10.36,1:46:11.80,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,The Reverend Headlam? Mmm-hmm.
Dialogue: 0,1:46:13.41,1:46:16.10,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Extraordinary!\NI hardly know him.
Dialogue: 0,1:46:37.08,1:46:39.17,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,-Oscar, let's go to a hotel.\N-No!
Dialogue: 0,1:46:46.22,1:46:48.88,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,ARTHUR: Mr. Wilde!
Dialogue: 0,1:46:48.92,1:46:53.75,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Mr. Wilde.\NOh, sir, I've done\Neverything I could.
Dialogue: 0,1:46:53.79,1:46:57.23,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Your manuscripts.\NI've managed to save\Nsome of them,
Dialogue: 0,1:46:57.28,1:47:00.37,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,but they've been going\Nthrough the house like\Nvultures, sir.
Dialogue: 0,1:47:02.15,1:47:04.33,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,AUCTIONEER: 拢20! 25!
Dialogue: 0,1:47:04.37,1:47:09.77,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,拢25 I'm bid for this priceless\Nfirst edition by Walt Whitman,\Nwhoever he may be.
Dialogue: 0,1:47:09.81,1:47:12.90,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Now, now, come along,\Ngentlemen. Do I hear 拢30?
Dialogue: 0,1:47:12.94,1:47:14.64,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,拢30, 30. 拢35.
Dialogue: 0,1:47:14.68,1:47:17.56,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,拢35, 35. Come along,\Nwe haven't got all night.
Dialogue: 0,1:47:17.60,1:47:21.87,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Going then at 拢30.\NGoing once, twice,\Nthree times.
Dialogue: 0,1:47:21.91,1:47:24.17,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Charles, the gent\Nover there with the cigar.
Dialogue: 0,1:47:24.22,1:47:29.31,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Now then.\NHello, hello, hello.\NWhat have we got here?
Dialogue: 0,1:47:29.35,1:47:32.92,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,A painting of\Nthe dear boy himself.
Dialogue: 0,1:47:32.96,1:47:35.31,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Very pretty, I'm sure.\NVery pretty.
Dialogue: 0,1:47:35.36,1:47:39.62,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Now what am I bid\Nfor this masterpiece?\NDo I hear 10 shillings?
Dialogue: 0,1:47:39.67,1:47:41.89,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,MAN: Ten shillings.\NAUCTIONEER: Ten\Nshillings I'm bid.
Dialogue: 0,1:47:41.93,1:47:43.23,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Do I hear a pound?
Dialogue: 0,1:47:43.28,1:47:44.15,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,-拢1.\N-拢1!
Dialogue: 0,1:47:44.19,1:47:46.63,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,拢1, 1.
Dialogue: 0,1:47:49.02,1:47:53.55,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Excuse me,\Nladies and gentlemen,\NI think we have company.
Dialogue: 0,1:47:55.81,1:47:59.47,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Perhaps His Eminence will\Nbid for this artistic\Npainting.
Dialogue: 0,1:48:01.82,1:48:03.38,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,What about 30 bob, sir?
Dialogue: 0,1:48:04.60,1:48:06.48,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Come on, Oscar.\NHaven't you seen enough?
Dialogue: 0,1:48:09.57,1:48:11.83,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,-No?
Dialogue: 0,1:48:11.87,1:48:17.88,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Well, all right, then.\NGoing at a pound.\NGoing, going...
Dialogue: 0,1:48:17.92,1:48:19.18,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,40 guineas!
Dialogue: 0,1:48:19.23,1:48:22.01,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,-AUCTIONEER: 40 guineas.
Dialogue: 0,1:48:22.06,1:48:24.97,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Well, then.\NAny advance\Non 40 guineas?
Dialogue: 0,1:48:26.58,1:48:29.45,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,All right. Sold to\NHis Lordship for\N40 guineas.
Dialogue: 0,1:48:29.50,1:48:32.76,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Charlie, give the\Ngentleman his painting.
Dialogue: 0,1:48:32.81,1:48:34.85,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,-40 guineas.\N-Thank you, My Lord.
Dialogue: 0,1:48:34.89,1:48:36.94,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,-Thank you.\N-What are you going to do\Nwith it now you've bought it?
Dialogue: 0,1:48:36.98,1:48:38.38,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Hang it in the bathroom!
Dialogue: 0,1:48:47.21,1:48:50.39,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Aw, blimey, governor.\NWhat a waste of 40 quid.
Dialogue: 0,1:48:50.43,1:48:53.39,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,MAN:\NI say, a little\Nbit rash, what?
Dialogue: 0,1:48:56.57,1:48:57.61,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I feel like a drink.
Dialogue: 0,1:49:01.92,1:49:03.18,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Excuse me, please.
Dialogue: 0,1:49:04.62,1:49:07.32,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Excuse me. Thank you.\NExcuse me, madam.
Dialogue: 0,1:49:08.36,1:49:10.02,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Excuse me. Thank you.
Dialogue: 0,1:49:11.50,1:49:12.50,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Excuse me.
Dialogue: 0,1:49:15.89,1:49:17.11,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Come on, Oscar.
Dialogue: 0,1:49:19.37,1:49:21.85,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,AUCTIONEER: Well,\Nwe weren't very\Nquick there.
Dialogue: 0,1:49:21.90,1:49:25.47,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,We should have\Nasked His Eminence to\Nautograph a few books, eh?
Dialogue: 0,1:49:27.38,1:49:30.82,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Now then,\Nan original manuscript\Nof that uproarious comedy,
Dialogue: 0,1:49:30.86,1:49:33.65,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,The Importance\Nof Being Earnestby\Nthe late Oscar Wilde.
Dialogue: 0,1:49:33.69,1:49:35.48,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,-Now, then, do I hear 拢10?
Dialogue: 0,1:49:58.76,1:49:59.98,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Mr. Wilde.
Dialogue: 0,1:50:01.81,1:50:03.59,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I'm most dreadfully\Nsorry about this, sir,
Dialogue: 0,1:50:03.64,1:50:05.99,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,but I'm afraid\Nwe must ask you to leave.
Dialogue: 0,1:50:06.03,1:50:07.81,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Ask us to leave?\NBut how dare you\Ncome up...
Dialogue: 0,1:50:07.86,1:50:09.64,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,-I'm very sorry, sir.\N-Don't you realize\Nthat Mr. Wilde's...
Dialogue: 0,1:50:09.69,1:50:10.90,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,It's all right, Robbie.
Dialogue: 0,1:50:10.95,1:50:11.95,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Let's go.
Dialogue: 0,1:50:19.48,1:50:21.74,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Remarkable, the sort\Nof people they allow\Nin here these days!
Dialogue: 0,1:50:21.78,1:50:23.92,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,-I thought it was\Na high-class place!
Dialogue: 0,1:50:23.96,1:50:26.05,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I think it's\Nblooming disgusting.
Dialogue: 0,1:50:26.09,1:50:28.70,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Come on, my friends, drink up.\NPay the bill, will you,\NFreddie?
Dialogue: 0,1:50:28.75,1:50:30.01,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Why, certainly, Q.
Dialogue: 0,1:50:30.05,1:50:31.18,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Cab!
Dialogue: 0,1:50:31.23,1:50:33.19,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,God bless you, Mr. Wilde.
Dialogue: 0,1:50:34.19,1:50:35.19,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Hello, Amy.
Dialogue: 0,1:50:36.84,1:50:38.19,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Knightsbridge, cabby.
Dialogue: 0,1:50:38.24,1:50:39.06,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Yes, sir.
Dialogue: 0,1:50:42.89,1:50:44.89,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,MAN 1: Blimey! It's raining!
Dialogue: 0,1:50:44.94,1:50:46.24,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,QUEENSBERRY: Get my carriage.
Dialogue: 0,1:50:46.29,1:50:47.46,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,So long, Oscar!
Dialogue: 0,1:50:47.51,1:50:48.77,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Are we going to have\Na bit of sport then?
Dialogue: 0,1:50:48.81,1:50:50.07,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Yes, I think so.
Dialogue: 0,1:50:50.12,1:50:52.47,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,MAN 2: Come on, there we go,\Nlet's get in.
Dialogue: 0,1:50:53.03,1:50:54.12,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Come on.
Dialogue: 0,1:50:55.30,1:50:57.43,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Follow him. As fast as you can.
Dialogue: 0,1:50:57.47,1:50:58.78,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,MAN 2: Tallyho!
Dialogue: 0,1:51:06.87,1:51:09.57,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,By God,\Nthey're following us.\NThe man must be mad.
Dialogue: 0,1:51:09.61,1:51:11.53,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I should have thought it\Nwas common knowledge\Nby now, Robbie.
Dialogue: 0,1:51:11.57,1:51:12.70,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Go faster, driver!
Dialogue: 0,1:51:16.53,1:51:17.84,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,MAN 2: Tallyho!
Dialogue: 0,1:51:20.58,1:51:22.76,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Faster, driver, faster!
Dialogue: 0,1:51:22.80,1:51:24.15,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,MAN 2: Tallyho!
Dialogue: 0,1:51:27.72,1:51:30.55,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,This is madness.\NI'm going to walk.\NStop the cab, driver!
Dialogue: 0,1:51:30.59,1:51:31.90,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Oscar, don't be foolish.
Dialogue: 0,1:51:31.94,1:51:32.90,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I'm not\Ngoing to put you\Nthrough all this.
Dialogue: 0,1:51:37.77,1:51:39.30,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Oscar, where will you be?
Dialogue: 0,1:51:39.34,1:51:40.60,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,-I'm going to my mother.\N-Right.
Dialogue: 0,1:51:40.65,1:51:41.99,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Carry on, driver.
Dialogue: 0,1:52:18.81,1:52:20.82,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Well, now,\Nmy old darling,\Nwhere's your friend?
Dialogue: 0,1:52:20.86,1:52:22.34,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Why are you doing this,\NQueensberry?
Dialogue: 0,1:52:22.38,1:52:23.95,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Why are you hounding\Nthis man in this way?
Dialogue: 0,1:52:23.99,1:52:26.87,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Haven't you had\Nyour pound of flesh?
Dialogue: 0,1:52:26.91,1:52:28.91,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,You don't know me\Nvery well, do you,\NMr. Ross?
Dialogue: 0,1:52:28.95,1:52:30.35,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I'm not so easily satisfied.
Dialogue: 0,1:52:30.39,1:52:31.48,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,That's quite evident.
Dialogue: 0,1:52:31.52,1:52:33.26,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Tell Wilde that\NI shall not be happy
Dialogue: 0,1:52:33.31,1:52:35.09,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,until I see him\Nunder six feet\Nof earth.
Dialogue: 0,1:52:35.13,1:52:36.61,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Six feet of earth,\NLord Queensberry,
Dialogue: 0,1:52:36.66,1:52:38.70,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,puts us all very much\Non the same level.
Dialogue: 0,1:52:40.66,1:52:42.97,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I've not finished with him yet!
Dialogue: 0,1:52:43.01,1:52:45.01,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I shall hound him\Nuntil his dying day!
Dialogue: 0,1:52:46.97,1:52:49.19,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Until his dying day!
Dialogue: 0,1:52:49.24,1:52:51.46,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Well, what now, Q?\NIs the hunt still on?
Dialogue: 0,1:52:52.54,1:52:53.76,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Let's go to The Savoy.
Dialogue: 0,1:52:53.81,1:52:55.68,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Ah, let's go to The Savoy.\NGo to The Savoy.
Dialogue: 0,1:53:04.77,1:53:05.95,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Oscar!
Dialogue: 0,1:53:06.60,1:53:08.52,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Oscar, is that you?
Dialogue: 0,1:53:10.04,1:53:11.08,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Willie!
Dialogue: 0,1:53:11.13,1:53:15.09,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Dear darling Mother.\NYes, what is it?
Dialogue: 0,1:53:15.13,1:53:18.53,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Dearest Mother,\Nyou know you should\Nhave been an actress.
Dialogue: 0,1:53:18.57,1:53:21.14,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I doubt if the great\NSarah Bernhardt herself
Dialogue: 0,1:53:21.18,1:53:24.10,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,made a more imposing\NLady Macbeth.
Dialogue: 0,1:53:24.14,1:53:27.36,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,But aren't you just\Na little premature\Nto wear mourning?
Dialogue: 0,1:53:28.88,1:53:31.97,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Oscar isn't quite\Ndead yet, you know.
Dialogue: 0,1:53:32.02,1:53:33.58,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,They crucified him.
Dialogue: 0,1:53:33.63,1:53:35.46,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Now, Mother,\Nif you're going to\Ngo on like this, I...
Dialogue: 0,1:53:48.69,1:53:49.91,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Who's there?
Dialogue: 0,1:53:49.95,1:53:51.69,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,OSCAR: Willie, let me in,\Nfor God's sake.
Dialogue: 0,1:53:58.04,1:54:00.65,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Willie, let me stay.\NLet me stay.
Dialogue: 0,1:54:01.57,1:54:03.14,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Or I shall die on the streets.
Dialogue: 0,1:54:09.23,1:54:10.27,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Are you drunk?
Dialogue: 0,1:54:19.37,1:54:20.54,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Here you are.
Dialogue: 0,1:54:21.15,1:54:24.33,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Is this my son?
Dialogue: 0,1:54:24.37,1:54:28.68,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Is this Oscar Wilde,\Ncringing in the dark\Nlike a frightened animal?
Dialogue: 0,1:54:28.73,1:54:30.38,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Mother, for heaven's sake!
Dialogue: 0,1:54:30.42,1:54:31.99,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Stand up, sir.
Dialogue: 0,1:54:32.03,1:54:33.77,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Stand up and face them, sir!
Dialogue: 0,1:54:35.60,1:54:36.87,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,For God's sake,\Ndon't let them in, Willie.
Dialogue: 0,1:54:38.95,1:54:41.39,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Willie, open the door.
Dialogue: 0,1:54:41.43,1:54:43.35,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,My son is ready for them.
Dialogue: 0,1:54:50.79,1:54:52.88,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Robbie. Thank God you've come.
Dialogue: 0,1:54:56.93,1:54:58.76,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Ada.
Dialogue: 0,1:54:58.80,1:55:00.76,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,-Robbie, what's\Nto become of me?\N-It's all right.
Dialogue: 0,1:55:00.80,1:55:03.46,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Couldn't you have\Ntaken his coat off?\NHe's soaked to the skin.
Dialogue: 0,1:55:04.46,1:55:05.94,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,He's ill. He should be in bed.
Dialogue: 0,1:55:05.98,1:55:08.85,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,But he... He can't\Nstay here, you know.\NWell...
Dialogue: 0,1:55:08.90,1:55:10.94,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I mean,\Nit would be awkward,\Nyou see.
Dialogue: 0,1:55:10.99,1:55:12.94,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,There's been mobs hanging\Nabout in the street all day,
Dialogue: 0,1:55:12.99,1:55:14.90,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,and if they were to\Nfind out he was here,
Dialogue: 0,1:55:14.95,1:55:17.04,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,well, there's no\Nknowing what they'd do.
Dialogue: 0,1:55:17.08,1:55:19.73,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,My son is not afraid of them!
Dialogue: 0,1:55:19.78,1:55:22.35,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,He'll stand up and face them
Dialogue: 0,1:55:22.39,1:55:24.56,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,like a true Irish gentleman.
Dialogue: 0,1:55:24.61,1:55:27.83,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I can find him a bed\Nat my house. Come, Oscar.
Dialogue: 0,1:55:27.87,1:55:31.22,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Don't sit up too late, my son.
Dialogue: 0,1:55:31.27,1:55:34.23,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,You need all the sleep\Nyou can get
Dialogue: 0,1:55:34.27,1:55:37.53,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,in this terrible time\Nwe're all passing through.
Dialogue: 0,1:55:39.58,1:55:41.41,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Come on, Oscar.
Dialogue: 0,1:55:41.45,1:55:43.71,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I'm not thinking of\Nmyself, you understand.
Dialogue: 0,1:55:43.76,1:55:46.20,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,He is my brother.\NBut it's my mother.
Dialogue: 0,1:55:46.24,1:55:48.68,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,She's not very well and\Nany sudden shock might...
Dialogue: 0,1:55:58.56,1:56:00.04,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,The prisoner will rise.
Dialogue: 0,1:56:02.56,1:56:06.08,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Gentlemen of the jury,\Nhave you agreed upon\Na verdict?
Dialogue: 0,1:56:06.13,1:56:07.78,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,We have.
Dialogue: 0,1:56:07.83,1:56:11.48,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Do you find the\Nprisoner at the bar\Nguilty or not guilty?
Dialogue: 0,1:56:12.44,1:56:13.70,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Guilty, My Lord.
Dialogue: 0,1:56:14.92,1:56:16.88,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,COURT USHER: Silence in court!
Dialogue: 0,1:56:16.92,1:56:19.49,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,And is that\Nthe verdict of you all?
Dialogue: 0,1:56:19.53,1:56:21.32,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Yes. Guilty.
Dialogue: 0,1:56:23.80,1:56:26.02,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,COURT USHER: Silence!
Dialogue: 0,1:56:26.06,1:56:30.72,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Oscar Wilde,\Nthe crime for which\Nyou have been convicted
Dialogue: 0,1:56:30.76,1:56:37.07,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,is so bad that one has to\Nput a stern restraint\Nupon one's self
Dialogue: 0,1:56:37.12,1:56:42.90,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,to avoid describing,\Nin language I would\Nrather not use,
Dialogue: 0,1:56:42.95,1:56:47.13,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,the sentiments that must\Nrise in the breasts of\Nevery man of honor
Dialogue: 0,1:56:47.17,1:56:51.43,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,who has listened\Nto the details of\Nthese terrible trials.
Dialogue: 0,1:56:51.48,1:56:55.13,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,That you have been\Nthe center of a circle
Dialogue: 0,1:56:55.18,1:56:58.44,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,of the most terrible\Ncorruption among young men,
Dialogue: 0,1:56:58.48,1:57:01.75,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,it is impossible to doubt.
Dialogue: 0,1:57:01.79,1:57:06.93,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,And under the circumstances,\NI shall pass the severest\Nsentence the law allows.
Dialogue: 0,1:57:08.02,1:57:10.71,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Although, in my judgment
Dialogue: 0,1:57:10.76,1:57:14.15,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,it is totally inadequate\Nfor a case of this sort.
Dialogue: 0,1:57:15.68,1:57:19.24,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Sentence of the court is\Nthat you go to imprisonment
Dialogue: 0,1:57:19.29,1:57:22.68,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,and be kept\Nto hard labor\Nfor two years.
Dialogue: 0,1:57:24.34,1:57:25.29,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,COURT USHER: Silence!
Dialogue: 0,1:57:29.56,1:57:31.30,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Be upstanding in court.
Dialogue: 0,1:57:33.52,1:57:37.18,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,All persons having\Nanything further to\Ndo before My Lords...
Dialogue: 0,1:57:37.22,1:57:39.79,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Come on, back! Back.\NCome on, back!
Dialogue: 0,1:57:52.54,1:57:54.80,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,He'll get his hair cut now,\Nwon't he?
Dialogue: 0,1:58:46.20,1:58:51.42,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,OSCAR: "I never saw sad men\Nwho looked with such\Na wistful eye
Dialogue: 0,1:58:51.47,1:58:57.26,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,"upon that\Nlittle tent of blue\Nwe prisoners call the sky,
Dialogue: 0,1:58:57.30,1:59:02.35,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,"and at every happy cloud that\Npassed in such strange\Nfre edom by."
Dialogue: 0,2:00:24.26,2:00:25.91,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,My dearest, your hands.
Dialogue: 0,2:00:28.56,2:00:32.18,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I've\Nnever been so idle\Nand worked so hard.
Dialogue: 0,2:00:35.88,2:00:38.18,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Please, my dear,\Nwe have so little time.
Dialogue: 0,2:00:39.92,2:00:42.71,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Oh, Constance,\NI've waited all these\Nmonths for you to come.
Dialogue: 0,2:00:44.14,2:00:47.19,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I would've come\Nbefore, Oscar, only...
Dialogue: 0,2:00:47.24,2:00:49.59,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I don't know, it's all been\Nso confusing.
Dialogue: 0,2:00:51.41,2:00:52.59,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Why have you come now?
Dialogue: 0,2:00:54.11,2:00:55.90,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I have some bad news\Nfor you, Oscar.
Dialogue: 0,2:00:55.94,2:00:58.12,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I didn't want you to hear it\Nfrom anyone else.
Dialogue: 0,2:01:00.94,2:01:02.08,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Your mother...
Dialogue: 0,2:01:03.77,2:01:04.69,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,She's dead, Oscar.
Dialogue: 0,2:01:07.34,2:01:09.78,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,There was no pain.\NShe passed away\Nin her sleep.
Dialogue: 0,2:01:14.09,2:01:16.35,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I wish I could\Nleave here in that way.
Dialogue: 0,2:01:16.39,2:01:18.70,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,No, Oscar,\Nyou mustn't say that.\NYou must be patient.
Dialogue: 0,2:01:18.74,2:01:21.18,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,It's not patience that's\Nneeded here, it's apathy.
Dialogue: 0,2:01:21.23,2:01:25.23,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,And apathy is the\Nmost pitiful of vices.
Dialogue: 0,2:01:25.27,2:01:28.45,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Constance, I don't\Nthink I can survive\Nanother year of this.
Dialogue: 0,2:01:28.49,2:01:31.06,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Oh, my dear.\NIt's only the thought\Nof the children
Dialogue: 0,2:01:31.10,2:01:33.89,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,that keeps me alive in\Nthese terrible months\Nof waiting.
Dialogue: 0,2:01:35.81,2:01:36.89,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,How are they?
Dialogue: 0,2:01:41.72,2:01:42.64,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,They're well.
Dialogue: 0,2:01:45.29,2:01:47.64,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,It'll be\NVyvyan's birthday soon.
Dialogue: 0,2:01:47.69,2:01:51.04,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,-Oscar, I...\N-Is he 9 or 10?
Dialogue: 0,2:01:51.08,2:01:53.13,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,The time passes so slowly.
Dialogue: 0,2:01:53.17,2:01:56.04,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Oscar, I cannot\Nallow you to see\Nthe children again.
Dialogue: 0,2:02:05.23,2:02:07.32,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I'm only trying to do\Nwhat I think is right.
Dialogue: 0,2:02:07.36,2:02:09.40,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I've thought and thought\Nabout it and I...
Dialogue: 0,2:02:17.63,2:02:19.07,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Forgive me, my dearest.
Dialogue: 0,2:02:21.33,2:02:23.33,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Please. Forgive me.
Dialogue: 0,2:02:31.08,2:02:32.25,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Oscar.
Dialogue: 0,2:02:39.61,2:02:40.91,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I brought you some cigarettes
Dialogue: 0,2:02:42.05,2:02:43.87,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,and some delicacies,\Nsome chicken.
Dialogue: 0,2:02:43.92,2:02:45.74,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I know what the food\Nmust be like.
Dialogue: 0,2:02:53.97,2:02:54.84,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Goodbye, my dear.
Dialogue: 0,2:03:44.54,2:03:46.81,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Will he have time to catch\Nthe boat train?
Dialogue: 0,2:03:46.85,2:03:48.11,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,If we hurry.
Dialogue: 0,2:03:55.07,2:03:56.64,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Goodbye, Mr. Wilde, sir.
Dialogue: 0,2:03:56.69,2:03:58.90,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Goodbye, Dick. Thank you.
Dialogue: 0,2:04:16.49,2:04:17.62,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Thank you, my dear.
Dialogue: 0,2:04:20.71,2:04:22.10,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Oscar.
Dialogue: 0,2:04:22.15,2:04:23.23,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Come on, we must hurry.
Dialogue: 0,2:04:37.16,2:04:38.60,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,You look well, Oscar.
Dialogue: 0,2:04:44.30,2:04:45.95,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,The children send their love.
Dialogue: 0,2:04:47.52,2:04:48.48,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Thank you.
Dialogue: 0,2:04:50.57,2:04:53.13,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I told them\Nyou were very ill.\NI hope you understand.
Dialogue: 0,2:04:55.31,2:04:56.61,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Yes, of course.
Dialogue: 0,2:05:00.58,2:05:02.32,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Well, I suppose\Nwe'd better get\Ndown to business.
Dialogue: 0,2:05:02.36,2:05:03.53,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,There isn't very much time.
Dialogue: 0,2:05:06.36,2:05:12.59,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I've arranged\Nwith my lawyer to\Npay you 拢150 a year.
Dialogue: 0,2:05:12.63,2:05:15.20,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,It's not much, I'm afraid,\Nbut it's all I can afford.
Dialogue: 0,2:05:16.59,2:05:18.51,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I am very grateful\Nto you, Constance.
Dialogue: 0,2:05:20.46,2:05:22.73,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Only I'm sorry I had\Nto make one condition.
Dialogue: 0,2:05:25.30,2:05:29.39,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,If you see or communicate with\NBosie again, the payments\Nwill stop.
Dialogue: 0,2:05:34.70,2:05:37.26,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Yes, I... I understand.
Dialogue: 0,2:05:37.31,2:05:38.74,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I know that may sound harsh,
Dialogue: 0,2:05:38.79,2:05:41.01,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,but I promise you\NI'm doing it to help you.
Dialogue: 0,2:05:43.92,2:05:44.75,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Hmm.
Dialogue: 0,2:06:07.86,2:06:08.73,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Porter.
Dialogue: 0,2:06:12.82,2:06:14.04,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,-Boat train, sir?\N-Yes.
Dialogue: 0,2:06:26.66,2:06:27.62,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Ada.
Dialogue: 0,2:06:29.05,2:06:31.23,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,You look lovelier than ever.
Dialogue: 0,2:06:31.27,2:06:33.15,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Oh, it's good\Nto see you, Oscar.
Dialogue: 0,2:06:36.67,2:06:37.72,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Ticket, madam?
Dialogue: 0,2:06:37.76,2:06:39.11,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,The gentleman has them.\NThank you.
Dialogue: 0,2:06:41.72,2:06:44.07,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Oh, Robbie,\NI can't bear to\Nsee him looking so ill.
Dialogue: 0,2:06:44.11,2:06:46.12,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I was talking to the\Nprison doctor yesterday.
Dialogue: 0,2:06:46.16,2:06:48.60,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Another six months in there\Nand he'd never come out alive.
Dialogue: 0,2:06:54.65,2:06:55.56,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Constance.
Dialogue: 0,2:06:56.78,2:06:58.52,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I want you to remember this.
Dialogue: 0,2:06:59.74,2:07:02.09,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I have always loved you,\Nand I always will.
Dialogue: 0,2:07:04.52,2:07:08.31,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,You talk as if...\NYou're going to get well again
Dialogue: 0,2:07:08.35,2:07:10.92,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,and you'll forget\Nabout these past two years.
Dialogue: 0,2:07:12.62,2:07:14.19,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,You'll start work again.
Dialogue: 0,2:07:14.23,2:07:16.97,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I know you too well, Oscar.\NOnce you start writing, you...
Dialogue: 0,2:07:22.46,2:07:26.68,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Ada, don't be so depressed\Non my behalf.
Dialogue: 0,2:07:26.72,2:07:30.77,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,What better reward\Nfor one's sins than\Nto be exiled to Paris?
Dialogue: 0,2:07:30.81,2:07:34.90,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Where no doubt\NI shall die as I have lived,\Nbeyond my means.
Dialogue: 0,2:07:36.08,2:07:37.60,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,What a gorgeous hat.
Dialogue: 0,2:07:37.65,2:07:38.65,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Oh, Oscar.
Dialogue: 0,2:07:40.69,2:07:42.30,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Goodbye, my dear.
Dialogue: 0,2:07:42.35,2:07:43.91,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Take care of the children.
Dialogue: 0,2:07:56.97,2:07:58.06,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,Hello, Oscar.
Dialogue: 0,2:08:47.63,2:08:49.15,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I never understood it, Ada.
Dialogue: 0,2:08:50.50,2:08:51.89,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,I just never understood it.
Dialogue: 0,2:08:55.72,2:08:59.29,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,OSCAR: "Yet each man\Nkills the thing he loves.
Dialogue: 0,2:08:59.34,2:09:01.42,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,"By each let this be heard.
Dialogue: 0,2:09:01.47,2:09:03.47,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,"Some do it with a bitter look,
Dialogue: 0,2:09:03.51,2:09:05.69,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,"some with a flattering word.
Dialogue: 0,2:09:06.69,2:09:09.00,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,"A coward does it with a kiss,
Dialogue: 0,2:09:09.04,2:09:11.43,Default,,0000,0000,0000,,"the brave man with a sword."

